<HEADLINE>Packed with space</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay drives a Japanese saloon that has lots of prestige
WHILE Japanese executive saloons obviously have a place on their home
market, and several of them have done well in America, there is a
reluctance here to put them in the same league as their counterparts
from British and European manufacturers.
It is a matter of badge and name as much as anything else, since this
-- together with the expensive GT sector -- is a part of the market
where a certain amount of automotive snobbery seems inevitable.
Nissan came out with its first prestige saloon, the President, in 1965
and kept that model in its range through a couple of design generations.
The company's UK sales have mostly been in small and medium saloons,
estates and coupes, with a few brawny sports cars, but it took a first
serious crack at the executive market with the Maxima, a car which never
quite ''hit the spot''.
The latest top-ranking Nissan saloon is the Maxima's replacement, the
QX. I had met this combination of letters once before, in a Wodehouse
story whose hero observed a group of seemingly demented women saying
''kew'' and ''exe'' to themselves in an uninhibited fashion. In fact,
they were simply taking part in an exercise to tone up the facial
muscles. The exaggerated Q sound exercised the pout function, while the
X sound made them grin ferociously.
Neither pout nor grin seems an appropriate reaction to the QX as a
car, one into which Nissan has poured large quantities of engineering
expertise. There are six different versions of it available. Two use a
three-litre V6 engine as the SE at #21,995 and the SEL which I have been
driving at #24,995. There are also four two-litre types, but in a car of
this general size and type the smaller engine may be a case of
under-egging the pudding.
The extremely compact three-litre V6 power unit, mounted transversely
so as to power the front wheels, and remarkably light in weight, is a
really sophisticated piece of kit. It is a substantially oversquare
unit, featuring 24 valves and four camshafts, and it pushes out 193bhp
as well as a handsome amount and spread of torque.
While the QX is a robust and well-built car, that excellent engine
endows it with notably strong performance for its type. Even when
slightly muffled by the top-class four-speed automatic transmission
which is standard on the SEL, it will romp to 60mph in about 8.5 seconds
and deliver really good mid-range acceleration. The SEL is also
remarkably highly geared, loping along at 30mph for every 1000rpm of
engine speed. That allows it to be a very relaxed motorway cruiser, and
contributes to steady-speed fuel consumption expectations such as 39mpg
at 56mph and 31 at 75, compared with something like 22mpg around town.
Nissan has given this model a new and fairly complex rear suspension,
which favours what is, for a Japanese car, the unexpected side of the
ride/handling balance. The QX has fine body control on corners, although
it is no sports saloon, but the suspension struggles to suppress the
effect of small bumps or undulating surfaces at modest speeds.
A major plus point for the QX is that it is a roomy saloon, with loads
of space in the rear cabin and also a generous boot. Equipment levels
are high -- from air-conditioning to leather upholstery on seats which,
in the front at least, seem a little too wide. Nissan has made
absolutely certain that no charge of over-embellishment, as in the
earliest Japanese style, could possibly be brought against the QX.
If anything, the interior may be rather austere, in appearance
although certainly not in equipment, for some buyers in this class.
Similarly, the external lines of the body are discreet almost to the
point of anonymity. But this is a technically sophisticated car, well
built and well finished, with all the passenger space its situation in
the executive sector demands.
</TEXT>
