<HEADLINE>Co-operation pays off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A major step in Hawthorn Housing Co-operative's campaign to improve
housing in East Keppoch, Possilpark, has just been made with the
completion of the first new-build scheme of 29 houses and flats.
A further important step was taken last week when Raymond Robertson,
Minister of Housing, cut the turf on Toffs, a new site which will give
46 new housing units, many of them barrier free, and a much-needed play
area.
The co-operative has also secured funding from Glasgow Development
Agency to decontaminate the old brownfield sites in the area, most of
them formerly occupied by industries connected with the Springburn
railway works.
All the homes in the four terraces at Coulin and Glendarvel have their
own front and back gardens. Eight have two-apartments, four have
three-apartments, and there are three five-apartment homes, while the
remainder have four apartments.
Two have been sold for shared ownership; all the others are being let
at rentals ranging from #125 a month for a two-apartment home to #170 a
month for one with five apartments.
Hawthorn Housing Co-operative developed the scheme with Cruden Estates
Ltd under a design-and-build contract, and they have just heard that it
is to receive a Premier Gas Award.
Chair person Frank Galloway says: ''The new schemes improve housing
opportunities and also improve the environment.
''The bits of the jigsaw still missing in Possilpark are real jobs and
good quality, well-maintained and affordable leisure and recreational
facilities.''
The origins of the co-operative go back to 1983, when the residents of
East Keppoch were suffering from the complete decline of the area and
felt there was little or no hope for them.
At this time, Glasgow District Council began looking at a new scheme
to improve run-down housing estates by setting up co-operatives, with
the idea that residents would take over complete responsibility for
their own housing within a geographical area.
Possil was not one of the areas being considered.
Local residents embarked on a publicity campaign inside and outside
the area. They employed a firm of architects and quantity surveyors,
Gray Aitken, to carry out a feasibility study, and asked for help from
banks and building societies.
Tenants of the estate dogged politicians' footsteps, getting on
flights with them, confronting them at exhibitions and openings, and
even stopping a bus containing Scottish Office officials and persuading
them to look at the local houses.
Eventually residents won the right to form a housing co-operative and
buy a number of houses from the district council. It took them five
years to reach this stage.
Finally, in November 1988, Possil Housing Co-operative was registered
as one of only two fully mutual housing co-operatives in the city and
one of only six housing co-operatives in Scotland.
In 1989, the Housing Corporation offered financial assistance, and the
co-opertative changed its name to Hawthorn Housing Co-operative.
Now the future is looking bright, with joint venture projects with
developers, streetscape projects, and a plan by the Regenerational
Alliance to target the whole area.
</TEXT>
