<HEADLINE>New owner gets trough</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU could drive a coach and horses through the entrance to this house
near Dollar -- the place was designed for it. The Coach House at
Dollarbeg has a very attractive archway with fine carved stonework, and
it comes with its own horse's trough.
Dating back to around 1889 and built of mellow stone featuring
crowstep gables, it was built as the coach house for the Dollarbeg
estate.
The owners converted the house for their own occupation and it
contains many original oak or pine-panelled floors and period
fireplaces. The principal house has four reception rooms and five
bedrooms, while the guest wing (or grannexe!) has two reception rooms
and two bedrooms.
The house is set in about 2.5 acres of mature woodland, and the
selling agent says a kitchen garden could be created to the rear of the
property, while formal lawns could be laid to the front.
The coach house is close to Dollar and is a good base for those
working almost anywhere in the central belt.
The Dollar area maintains a predominantly rural character, set in
rolling farmlands enhanced by the Ochil Hills. Some of the best trout
fishing in Scotland is to be found at Loch Leven, 10 miles to the east.
The property benefits from full central heating and insulation
throughout. The price is #285,000 through estate agents Lindsays of
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
