<HEADLINE>Gregor's future in the balance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREGOR Townsend will know by the weekend whether his home-town club of
Gala or Ian McGeechan's Northampton will have exclusive use of his
services next season, writes Derek Douglas.
Townsend, who has spent most of the summer in Australia, where he is
turning out at stand-off for the Sydney club, Warringah, and for whom he
will be involved in the New South Wales club championship play-offs
against Canberra at the Concorde Oval on Saturday, said yesterday:
''Hopefully, it will all be sorted out by the end of the week.
''I'm still thinking things over and speaking to people back home.
It's a major decision and I don't want to rush into it.''
The key to Townsend's future -- even in this new-age of the
professional game -- is the need to balance his rugby against securing a
job in his chosen field of corporate finance, or as a graduate business
trainee.
Both clubs have been attempting to set up employment opportunities in
Edinburgh and London.
Townsend, 22, has made a full recovery from the knee injury which
threatened to put him out of the game for a year.
At the time the Gala youngster was riding the crest of a wave, having
largely overcome his propensity for the silly errors which were
nicknamed ''Toonyisms'' by his Scotland team-mates.
With a try and the Toony Flip which preceded the Gavin Hastings'
touchdown at Parc des Princes, he had played a central role in
Scotland's historic win over France and seemed set to blossom at the
World Cup in South Africa.
However, only 10 days before the World Cup squad was due to be
announced, Townsend was laid low with the knee injury and the initial
diagnosis that he might be out of the game for 12 months.
Yesterday he said:''Luckily the first prognosis was overly gloomy, and
I was out for just three and a half months. I've played six games over
here since getting back to it, and there have been no problems.''
He returns home on September 20 and so -- irrespective of which club
eventually wins his favours -- will have missed the first three games of
the new Scottish premiership by the time he arrives back.
''Down here in Australia we have had a totally different perspective
on the professionalism issue than has been the case back home. It seemed
to me as if the Australian and New Zealand unions were intent on doing
their own thing irrespective of what the International Board might have
decided at the weekend.
''The Kerry Packer, World Rugby Corporation thing was taken very
seriously indeed down here. I don't think people in the Northern
Hemisphere realise just how close it was.
''I think the radical nature of the International Board's decisions in
Paris took a lot of people by surprise.''
</TEXT>
