<HEADLINE>Black night for United despite Bett move. Lambert, Arnott make sure that all ends well</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dundee United 1 Motherwell 2
ALEX McLeish, the Motherwell manager, worried before the game that
Dundee United were the most difficult opponents they could have drawn at
this stage of the Coca-Cola Cup.
In the first half particularly, when United went in front after only
15 minutes, he must have thought that his pre-match comments could prove
prophetic. United had begun the game well, lifted perhaps by their new
singing Jim Bett.
The 36-year-old midfield player had joined the club just hours earlier
and was pushed straight into action, underlining United's need for
inspiration after a poor opening to the season. It worked well enough
early on to allow the Tannadice team to go in front when Robbie Winters
scored.
The goal came after a spectacular drive from Sandy Robertson was
pushed against the bar by Motherwell keeper Scott Howie. Winters reacted
first, and while the Motherwell defence stood spectating, he followed up
to force a header over the line with the keeper stranded.
However, the premier division side gradually began to settle and take
control. By the time Paul Lambert equalised 10 minutes before half time,
it was always going to be Motherwell's night.
Indeed, Lambert might have scored beforehand when Ally Maxwell
one-handed his shot for a corner. And he might have scored again
following his goal with a shot which struck a post and came clear.
When Robertson limped off at the beginning of the second half, United
were forced to chance things around, bringing on Paddy Connolly, and
before manager Billy Kirkwood's side had adapted to the change,
Motherwell had gone into a lead that they were never to lose.
Alex Burns, who had set up the opener for Lambert, was again at the
heart of the action in 58 minutes when he burst into the penalty box and
then whipped the ball across goal to his front-line team-mate Dougie
Arnott to finish things with a shot which went beyond Maxwell and into
goal.
In 74 minutes Andy Roddie blasted a shot against the bar and the ball
was cleared and Motherwell were left, at the end, clinging to a
single-goal lead when they might have had a wider margin.
That allowed United to make a storming finish and twice their Scotland
midfielder, Billy McKinlay, saw shots blocked in the packed penalty
area, first by Brian Martin and then John Philliben.
In the end, however, United never did have the subtlety to create a
clear-cut chance, nor the cutting edge which Motherwell had shown in
their fightback.
Now Motherwell are the team who go into the quarter-final draw on
Friday, having once again confirmed the grit and determination they
showed last season when they battled it out with Rangers at the top of
the premier division.
In contrast, Kirkwood, warned again by the referee in the first half,
finds his team out of this tournament and sitting second bottom of the
first division after a sad start to a season which everyone expected to
be crowned with immediate promotion.
There were six players booked last night, Robertson, McKinlay, and Rab
Shannon, for United, and Motherwell's Arnott, Burns, and Rob McKinnon.
United's bid to find a scoring touch by playing Brian Welsh up front
did not pay off. Still, while Bett went off before the end, replaced by
Scott Crabbe, there were signs from him that he will be able to help the
younger Tannadice players through this critical period.
DUNDEE UNITED -- Maxwell, Perry, Shannon, Dailly, Pressley, Welsh,
McLaren, McKinlay, Robertson, Bett, Winters. Substitutes -- Connolly,
O'Hanlon, Crabbe.
MOTHERWELL -- Howie, May, McKinnon, Roddie, Martin, Philliben,
Lambert, Dolan, Burns, Arnott, McSkimming. Substitutes -- Davies, Woods,
Ritchie.
Referee -- W Crombie (Edinburgh).
</TEXT>
