<HEADLINE>'Jewel' looks set to sparkle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE AND GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARK Johnston's Branston Jewel can break the winning spell of
Westcourt Magic in the conditions race at York today.
Two other runners go to post for the sprint and neither the Peter
Chapple-Hyam-trained Soviet Style nor Oh Whataknight are without a
chance. But that pair may find themselves fighting for third place money
behind Johnston's filly and the colt which his trainer Mick Easterby
describes as ''a machine.''
Although he has every reason so to do, especially after Westcourt
Magic broke the course record at Thirsk on Friday, it may be that
Easterby's charge has to settle for second best behind Branston Jewel.
The filly made an impressive debut at Windsor 11 days ago when,
despite running green, she landed the odds. While Westcourt Magic has
aquitted himself well, having improved rapidly through the ranks from
selling level to this conditions event, Johnston has always had Group
races in mind for this half-sister of Branston Abby.
Victory this afternoon will set her well on the way towards her
trainer's target, Ascot's Cornwallis Stakes.
Johnston doesn't intend letting the grass grow under Star Rage's feet
for long. This tough handicapper makes a quick reappearance following a
victory at Newcastle on Monday, in the Batley's Handicap.
His trainer feels that he didn't have too hard a race that day but it
is surely too much to ask of the five-year-old to repeat Monday's
success so soon. Richard Hannon's young apprentice Dane O'Neill is in
sparkling form at the moment and he can keep the momentum going at
Sandown courtesy of Inderaputeri, in the Dorking Handicap, and Ice Pick,
in Division 2 of the maiden race.
Martin Pipe, who was disappointed at his failure to go through the
card at Exeter on Friday, could gain compensation by grabbing five of
Newton Abbot's six races, with St Mellion Green, Toomuch Toosoon, Indian
Jockey, Errant Knight, and Most Equal.
The only race on the card without a Pipe runner, the Twins Novices'
Hurdle, should go to Philip Hobbs' Dallachio.
* BLUSHING Gleam beat Paul Cole's Like A Hawk to record an impressive
success in the Group 3 Prix du Calvados at Deauville yesterday.
</TEXT>
