<HEADLINE>Robertson Olympics bound</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Shirley Robertson, who continues to dominate the
single-handed Europe class, took another step closer to confirming her
selection for Savannah with two further wins to maintain an unbeaten
record in all five races at the Brut British Olympic Sailing Trials off
Weymouth yesterday.
In contrast, Scotland's leading 470-crew, Andy Richards and Ian Park,
were putting a brave face on a fifth place yesterday, and now lie fifth
overall.
The Helensburgh pair have spent every summer weekend logging the wind
directions, and eking out every last knot of boat speed from Weymouth's
light summer breezes -- chosen specifically to mirror the prevailing
light winds expected at next year's Olympic site.
Richards and Park fought up to third in yesterday's race but on the
last lap got on the wrong side of a wind shift which slid race leaders
Paul Brotherton and Steve Lovering back to sixth and elevated English
youngsters Jamie Lea and Simon Hughes to their first win this week.
Series leaders -- John Merricks and Ian Walker took second to increase
their overall lead.
Scotland lead the third leg of the Teachers' Round Britain Challenge
with Jon Fitzgerald's Glendronach lying second and Paul Jeffes' Lord
Inverforth in third. British Race Five results:
