<TEXT>
RACING UPDATE
VINDALOO only just failed to claim the outright 20th century record
for Flat handicap wins in a season at Ripon yesterday.
Victory No.10 looked on the cards as Jason Weaver's mount hit the
front a furlong out in the trophy race, the gelding's twenty-fifth
outing of the year. But Kevin Darley on Mellottie had other ideas.
Nearer last than first two furlongs out, the rider timed his challenge
to perfection on the 1991 Cambridgeshire winner, who got up to land the
spoils in a driving finish.
''The winning post just came too late,'' added trainer Jimmy Harris.
Vindaloo may make a quick bid to claim the record outright from
current joint-holders Chaplain's Club, Glencroft and Abell's Star Rage.
''He might go to York on Thursday for a mile and a half race,'' said
Harris ''we'll have to see how he is, though he looks pretty well now.''
SUSAN Piggott, wife of former champion jockey Lester, signed off her
eight-year training career when Alamein contested the maiden race at
Ripon yesterday.
Her final runner could not quite make it a successful curtain-call but
ran on gamely to finish fourth behind Dashing Blue.
''I just wish I could have gone out on a winning note,'' said Susan
''That would have been the icing on the cake. It's difficult to think of
a highlight in my training career as any winner -- from a seller to a
big race -- all come the same.
''It's also difficult to think of a best horse, though Nicholas was a
very, very good horse and Lester gained his first win on his comeback on
him at Chepstow.
* GROUND conditions at Doncaster's St Leger meeting, which starts a
week today, look like being perfect.
Clerk of the course John Sanderson said: ''There is excellemt grass
cover and watering will take place as necessary to maintain the
condition of the track.'' The going at the moment is good to firm, good
in places.
* WATERLOO Boy, found to have broken a leg in his box, has been
humanely destroyed.
</TEXT>
