<HEADLINE>A Multiple problem</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>49</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Scotlands Homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MULTIPLE-occupancy housing affects an estimated 5000 properties in
Glasgow. The city is said to have very strong views about it, so what's
involved?
At its simplest, it's about preventing possible exploitation. Not
quite the ''10 people in one broom cupboard'' syndrome, but that kind of
thing. It addressed the problems of lots of people living in one area,
perhaps making a bit of a din late at night as they clatter up and down
stairs, even having a party from time to time.
''We also have to look at important aspects such as environmental
health, planning, and building control,'' says Ian Robert, a chief
planning officer with Glasgow District.
It's nothing to do with large families or hotels. It is, in fact,
covered by the Housing (Scotland) Act 1987, the Housing (Management of
Houses and Buildings in Multiple Occupation) (Scotland) Regulation 1964,
and other related legislation.
Houses in multiple occupation cover bedsits, flats or houses let in
lodgings, shared flats or houses, and hostels and bed and breakfast
guest houses, where residents have their principal or only home.
Anyone -- resident or landlord -- who wants to be on the right side of
the law should ask for a copy of three free leaflets produced by the
council covering environmental health, planning, and building control.
''Nowadays, we have managed to eliminate the worst of the bad
practices,'' says Ian Robert. ''It's chasing a moving target, however,
and is still a problem.
''It can affect all sorts of people -- students, nurses, young
professional people. Any place used for multiple occupancy should be
registered with us. The conditions and requirements are clearly laid
out.
''You can't have more than a certain percentage of an area in multiple
occupation, for example. There must be a sensible quality of life,
without noise and nuisance for others.''
The regulations cover fire safety, the disposal of household refuse,
proper ventilation, piped hot and cold water, and the number of
unrelated people on the premises -- four or more in the West End local
plan area, and three elsewhere.
Professional letting agencies get their share of the problems as well.
As one agent, who sticks rigidly to the rules, put it: ''You have to
turn down people, because you don't go in for illegal multiple
occupation.
''They point out that ''Joe Bloggs next door'' has rooms. Why are you
so unfeeling? A bit later, they come back. Their landlord has been found
out. They're out on their ear. Why can't you help? Why don't you care?
It's still quite a problem, I would say.''
</TEXT>
