<HEADLINE>Careful writing is no clause for concern</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART MCINTOSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976633938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scots could be caught out by a new law if they unwittingly commit
themselves into legally binding contracts. The Requirements of Writing
(Scotland) Act 1995 came into effect on August 1 and aims to simplify
the need for special written forms. But the new rules will affect some
agreements in residential and commercial property and in credit matters.
Dorothy Kellas, partner of lawyers Morton Fraser Milligan, says:
''Anyone entering into a contract should be very careful that they are
not bound into a legally enforceable obligation without realising it.
''For example, someone may write to an estate agent outlining the
basis on which they are prepared to offer for a house. If accepted, this
correspondence could be seen as legally binding, whereas in the past it
was unlikely to be so. So now people could find themselves committed to
huge personal expenditure before they have had a chance to take legal
advice. You must therefore watch what you sign with much greater
vigilance.''
With regard to business matters, extreme care should be taken in any
informal exchanges relating to contracts or negotiations. Surveyors in
particular are affected by negotiations regarding the sale, purchase or
leasing of land or buildings.
Dorothy Kellas recommends that people seek legal advice as soon as
possible, should they have any concerns.
She suggests the addition of a clause in to any verbal or written
communication which makes it clear that what is said in the letter, or
conversation, ''is not intended to be binding upon you or form part of
any contract between you''.
</TEXT>
