<HEADLINE>Goram proves he's no longer a reluctant hero</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND manager Craig Brown has been convinced by goalkeeper Andy
Goram that he is ready, willing, and able to play for his country. The
Rangers' star, therefore, was named in the national squad yesterday.
Brown had spoken to Ibrox manager Walter Smith as well as Goram before
committing himself to the player's selection. After having been given
reassurances about the goalkeeper's commitment to his country's cause,
he then made his decision.
Said Brown yesterday: ''I asked Andy Goram whether he wanted to play
for Scotland and whether he was fit to play for Scotland. He gave me a
positive response on both counts and that is why he has re-joined the
group.
''There have been no guarantees given about playing against Finland
because it is too early to do that. I am just happy that we now have two
world class goalkeepers together in the squad.''
Brown then added: ''There have been no deals done over this. And there
have been no promises made. Andy's attitude and his enthusiasm for a
return to the squad were enough for me.''
Commonsense seems to have prevailed between Brown and his reluctant
star who left the squad last time round maintaining that he was not
''mentally attuned'' for the game against Greece.
If Goram now declares himself ready to join the other players, then
Brown is right to give him another chance. As I pointed out yesterday,
we are not over-burdened with players of Goram's undoubted calibre.
Veteran Jim Leighton may still take No.l spot at Hampden next week,
but if we reach the finals -- and victory over Finland practically
guarantees that -- then Goram will be required in England next summer.
For the moment, Brown has more to concern himself with than a
goalkeeping situation which appears to have been resolved. He must still
worry, for instance, over his strike force.
At first glance, the six men named offer him scoring options and
dangerous partnerships. Looking deeper, there are worries over fitness
and sharpness among his front players.
Aberdeen's Duncan Shearer has not played since the Greek game because
of suspension, and he now has a calf knock. John Spencer cannot get into
Chelsea's first team. And, on his own admission, the team manager still
harbours some doubts over the match readiness of veteran Ally McCoist
and the re-emerging Aberdeen striker, Scott Booth.
However, he has hopes that these worries will clear before the game.
He does admit: ''We have suffered from not being able to field a settled
strike force because of injuries. Right now, we are no nearer being able
to do so. I have been impressed by Scott Booth, a player we missed badly
last season after he was injured against Russia. He is quick and a good
finisher, and we want him back. But we are aware that he has played only
a few games since last year,
''McCoist might start the game this time -- but, again, we have to see
how his match sharpness is before we get down to selection. That is why
I have named six front men and you can take it as read that four of them
will be involved in the game, just as against the Greeks. Two will play
from the start with two others on the bench ready to go on.''
However, while questions still abound over the front men, the rest of
next week's team will retain a familiar and solid look. Brown knows the
midfield he wants, and he also will rely on defenders who have proved
themselves throughout a campaign which is now nearing its close.
They have given away few goals, and Brown will be looking to that
miserliness continuing at Hampden. If it does, and if whatever strike
force he produces can knock in a goal or two, then qualification would
be assured.
Brown, however, is still cautious. He does not want to see his players
fail at this late stage of the qualifying group and he says: ''Finland
are a proud nation and they will want to come back after that 6-0 defeat
from Russia. They must also realise that if they do not win then their
hopes of qualification have gone. A draw could still be enough for us --
but not for them.
''A lot of our thinking about the game will depend on whether their
top player, Jari Litmanen, is chosen. He missed the last game against
the Russians, but if they believe they can still qualify, then I think
he would return and that would affect our own tactical approach to this
one.
''If he is in, then I believe they will open out a bit and that should
suit us. There will be no complacency, though, among my players. There
is too much at stake for that to happen.''
Meanwhile the game is heading for a sell-out with the born-again
Tartan Army turning out in force once more. A spokesman for the SFA
stressed yesterday that those fans who wish to go to the game next week
should buy tickets now.
