<HEADLINE>Night of sheer misery for Miller and Hibernian. Airdrie's cup record still hard as diamonds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Airdrie 2, Hibernian 0
IT was tough and it was uncompromising. It was just the way Airdrie
like it, and for the second successive season, the first-division club
without a home of their own took on Hibernian in the Coca-Cola Cup and
nudged them through the exit.
Last year, the Diamonds beat Hibs 2-1 in a quarter-final tie in
Edinburgh, and not a great many people expected the premier-division
side to suffer similarly again. But Airdrie have a tremendous cup record
in recent times, and they were utterly determined to attract more
attention to themselves.
In fact, the tie was won and lost after only nine minutes when Jim
Leighton was beaten for the second time, and although Hibs, who had
defended wildly and without cohesion in the first half, improved
dramatically in the second period, Airdrie were able to hold on to their
lead.
Of course life became much more straightforward for them after Kevin
Harper, whose darting speed and control had been a threat from the
beginning, was sent off in 70 minutes for a foul on Tommy McIntyre.
As though his dismissal was not enough to concern Hibs' manager Alex
Miller, he had to watch Scottish international striker Darren Jackson
take a penalty two minutes from time and balloon the ball over John
Martin's bar and off into the black night over Cumbernauld.
Miller shook his head in despair.
What a night, what a disgraceful defensive performance from his lot,
who were kept indoors for a long time after the final whistle.
Eventually, the manager emerged from the dressing room and said of his
team's defensive frailties: ''Too many people trying to be too clever.''
In particular, he was referring to Hibs' Steven Tweed, who scored
Airdrie's first goal. In seven minutes, the ball was played into the box
and Tweed rose to connect, but succeeded only in looping a header over
the stranded Jim Leighton.
The manager was looking even more forlorn and he refused to provide
his side ''with a get out'' by drawing attention to the number of
players he had to do without at Broadwood in last night's third-round
tie.
Miller did have to do without Graeme Mitchell, Keith Wright, and
Willie Miller, but Airdrie also were without three players -- Kenny
Black, Paul Jack, and Sandy Stewart because of injury and suspension.
''All players I would hang my hat on,'' said their manager, Alex
MacDonald, who prevented any of his triumphant side from talking about
their victory after the game.
Jimmy Sandison and Martin, players who normally can't resist an
audience, made their way out of the ground heads bowed and looking
apologetic, but MacDonald's word is law and he was determined that no
more of his players would find themselves in trouble with the SFA
because of comments attributed to them in the newspapers.
Two of his people have received letters from Bleak House and because
last night's tie had been, shall we say, robust, he told everyone to
keep quiet.
Perhaps after the next round he might relent, even if they don't
manage to go any further although they played last night like a team
intent on reaching yet another cup final. ''Doesn't matter who we get in
the next round,'' he said. 'We don't even have our own hoose, but we'll
go anywhere for a piece 'n' jam.''
Airdrie's second goal was scored by Jimmy Boyle in nine minutes when
he thumped the ball into the roof of Leighton's net, and again Hibs'
defence was negligent. ''We had five men in the box and Airdrie had two,
with one coming in support,'' Miller said as though still unable to
accept that it had happened. ''Yet, their player (Boyle) is unmarked
close to goal.''
Hopefully he will have a word with Harper, whose challenge on McIntyre
was silly and could have caused serious damage.
His team-mates, Pat McGinlay, and Michael O'Neill, also professionals
with flair and ability, were booked and Airdrie had four players
cautioned. Both McIntyres, Tommy and Jimmy, Tony Smith, who had a good
match shuttling up and down the left, and Stephen Tait, a substitute for
the injured Sean Sweeney, were cautioned by referee Jim McCluskey.
Sweeney was hurt in a tackle with Harper after only 15 minutes, and
MacDonald said afterwards: ''Sweeney had three stud marks on a knee.
Four and it could have been serious.''
MacDonald expressed himself pleased with the evening's work, and the
manner in which they coped with their more illustrious opponents was
acceptable. They knew Hibs would be stung into action after having
fallen behind, but Airdrie absorbed the Edinburgh side's attacks before
eventually pressing forward themselves and threatening to score a third.
AIRDRIE -- Martin, Boyle, T McIntyre, Sandison, Sweeney, Davies,
Wilson, Harvey, J McIntyre, Duffield, Smith. Substitutes -- Cooper,
Connelly, Tait.
HIBERNIAN -- Leighton, Jackson, Dods, McGinlay, Tweed, Hunter,
McAllister, Millen, Harper, Jackson, O'Neill. Substitutes -- Donald,
Weir, Love.
Referee -- J McCluskey (Stewarton).
</TEXT>
