<HEADLINE>Renewal of original Georgian elegance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHANIE DORAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF Allan Dreghorne's masterpiece St Andrew's Parish Church could talk,
what a tale it would have to tell. Completed in 1759, it has witnessed
-- and is about to witness again -- some of the finest and most
prosperous years of one of Glasgow's most historic areas: St Andrew's
Square.
The houses on St Andrew's Square were originally built as elegant town
houses for the businessmen and merchants of Glasgow, who combined the
sophistication of city living with the pleasures associated with the
open landscapes of Glasgow Green, literally on the doorstep, where they
could enjoy a game of golf or a leisurely stroll.
St Andrew's Square was a hub of gracious living. It was only minutes
away from where David Dale, co-founder with Robert Owen of the
conservation village of New Lanark and vice-president of Britain's first
Chamber of Commerce, built his magnificent mansion, designed by Adam, in
Charlotte Street.
It was a stone's throw from Monteith Row, another prestigious address
for the rich and successful. Its reputation was maintained until well
into this century, with doctors and lawyers still living there in the
1930s.
Against that background, almost two centuries later, St Andrew's
Square is being re-created by City Link Developments in association with
Glasgow Development Agency and Glasgow District Council, and has been
designed to re-capture that period of beauty and refinement.
''We are looking forward to the regeneration of another part of the
city going ahead positively and coming back into residential use after
lying derelict for some time,'' said Ronnie McLetchie, director of City
Link Developments. ''We see this as a return to gracious living first
created in the time of the tobacco lords.''
The square is bordered by London Road, High Street and Glasgow Green.
Its majestic focal point is St Andrew's Parish Church, at present used
for recitals, which is flanked at either entrance to the square by two
refurbished listed buildings, the Orphanage and the Tannery.
These ''book-ends'' of the square are joined by a third existing
listed building, the Hide, Skin &amp; Tallow building round the corner in
Greendyke Street.
The St Andrew's Square area was the first town planning exercise for
Glasgow. Sadly, over a long period, as fortunes came and went and the
city began to sprawl beyond its original limits, the buildings fell into
disrepair, and latterly many were converted into warehouses and
workshops.
Now City Link's architect Robert Johnston has created a sympathetic
design using natural stone, and the result is a terrace of classical
homes which will re-create and complement the Georgian architecture of
the original existing buildings. The planning guidelines were fairly
rigid and involved creating a master plan for the whole area
incorporating the development of the eight packages.
City Link has already refurbished the Tannery and is developing the
buildings around the square, while Scotia House is responsible for the
Orphanage. Woolwich Homes is developing the buildings around St Andrews
on the Green, and the New Housing Association is developing proposals
for housing along London Road.
The building programme for St Andrew's Square is now well under way,
the Tannery Building is complete and all 18 town flats and two office
units have been sold.
City Link's current phase is the building of 122 new flats around St
Andrew's Square. These are being constructed with Georgian-style stone
facades.
City Link has found that residents of the nearby Merchant City
development are a potential market, as their requirements change and
they want to move on to something bigger, with accompanying parking
facilities. A number of people living in The Tannery have come from the
Merchant City.
</TEXT>
