<HEADLINE>Rangers are warned to keep their minds on the Albion job</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR, CHIEF SPORTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COCA-COLA CUP PREVIEW
THE biggest threat to Rangers in tonight's Coca-Cola Cup third-round
tie could be a fragile state of mind rather than anything their Division
2 opponents, Stirling Albion, might conjure up.
The Ibrox side are having to spread their attention over a wide
playing field which stretches from domestic cup ties all the way up to
Champions' League football.
Even yesterday, while manager Walter Smith was preparing his players
for the game at Ibrox, news from the European front was still filtering
through, and the latest bulletin should be to Rangers' benefit because
Steaua Bucharest's captain, Marius Lacatus, will be suspended for the
opening tie in Group C on Wednesday, September 13.
Lacatus was booked in both of Steaua's preliminary matches, as was
Rangers' David Robertson, but the Romanian's absence will be the greater
loss. Smith's right-hand man, Archie Knox, will watch Steaua when they
open their league programme tonight and they will be examined again when
they play a week on Friday.
By then, Rangers hope to have demonstrated their desire to make up for
last season's early exit in the Coca-Cola Cup -- they were beaten by
Falkirk -- and work towards that end begins this evening.
''My main concern is that the players will be coming off some big and
important matches for this club, and that maybe they might not treat
this game in the same manner,'' said Smith, who will travel to Germany
on Friday to watch Borussia Dortmund, another of their Champions' League
rivals.
''However, I hope the run of results we have had continues and that we
can avoid another early exit in this competition.''
Smith was unsure last night whether or not Richard Gough would be able
to play against Stirling Albion, who were beaten 4-0 by the Ibrox side
in a pre-season tournament, because the captain has a stomach upset.
Although he couldn't train last night, he hopes to have recovered in
time to maintain his partnership with Gordan Petric at the heart of the
defence.
Brian Laudrup and Paul Gascoigne are close to full fitness again, but
neither will be risked.
Oleg Salenko, who made his debut as a substitute in Saturday's match
against Kilmarnock, played and scored for the reserves at Rugby Park
last night, and provided he reports back this morning without injury, he
will be used as a substitute against Albion. ''The idea is to give Oleg
as many matches as possible to increase his sharpness,'' the manager
said.
Albion, of course, are managed by former Rangers striker Kevin
Drinkell, who knows the kind of dangers which can befall the unprepared
at Ibrox. ''It would be foolish to think that we could hold out because
an onslaught will come at some point,'' he said.
''However, I have no injuries -- everyone wants to play at Ibrox as
you might imagine -- but it does worry me that some people have been
saying Rangers are not playing too well. That's when they are liable to
come out and do something.''
Falkirk, beaten 3-2 by Aberdeen at Brockville on Saturday, entertain
the Pittodrie side again tonight, and they will be especially vigilant
with regard to Scott Booth who scored the winner.
The stiker was named yesterday in the Scotland squad for next week's
European Championship qualifying tie against Finland, and it will be
intersting to see how he celebrates his return to the big time.
Partick Thistle will be relieved to get back on the pitch and away
from talk about a possible take over, but Livingston won't be easily
beaten on their own turf. Remember they beat St Johnstone in the
previous round.
Hearts are at home to Dunfermline in what could be one of the ties of
this round, and the Tynecastle side's striker, John Robertson, should be
back in his leading role after injury.
George Shaw could be back in Dundee's side for their tie against
Kilmarnock at Dens Park. ''We have had other front players doing well,
but George has made it clear he is bursting to play,'' said Dundee's
manager, Jim Duffy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
