<HEADLINE>Atherton's men hit critics for six</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDY JALIL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Atherton lead by example and the praises showered upon him by West
Indies' manager Wesley Hall was indeed something of which to be proud '
AFTER having drawn the last Test series against the West Indies it is
all too easy to become carried away that the England team is better than
it really is, but as ANDY JALIL explains, they have taken a step in the
right direction.
ENGLAND surrendered the Wisden Trophy 22 years ago when they went
down, at Lord's, to the West Indies. Now, after more than two decades of
attempting to win it back, this latest series provided them with the
best chance of getting their hands once again on the elusive silverware.
They failed but the pluses gained from this intensely contested series
have outweighed the minuses and have given a clear indication that Mike
Atherton and his men had taken a small but positive step in the
direction of a revival in English cricket.
Throughout this glorious summer, the fortunes have swayed and when it
came to the final showdown it balanced out.
For England, who have suffered five defeats in six series here since
1973 against the West Indies, this drawn encounter will be quite
heartening.
Atherton has shown with his own performance with the bat as well as
his captaincy that he has the ability to instil confidence and
enthusiasm in a team that has struggled season after season.
It may be a shade early to speak about a definite revival of English
cricket, for until England have won a series abroad and performed
consistently well at home, a true measure cannot be taken. That they are
on the road towards it, may be a fairer assessment.
Certainly, there are players who have emerged from this gripping
series with encouraging performances.
Dominic Cork was outstanding from the time of his debut at Lord's with
a seven-for-43 spell. He followed that with four for 69 at Edgbaston and
then crowned it all with four wickets in each innings in the next Test,
which included a hat trick. His batting brought valuable runs as did
Mike Watkinson's, particularly, at Trent Bridge in a heroic partnership
with Richard Illingworth. The Lancashire captain's bowling, too, proved
more than adequate.
Graham Thorpe was most consistent and took his aggregate of runs to
506 in the series. He became the only England batsman to score that many
in a single series in 67 years of Test cricket between the two
countries.
A much-maligned Graeme Hick proved his point, after his highly
publicised talk with the chairman of selectors. It remains to be seen,
however, if he has permanently rectified his weakness against the
short-pitched fast deliveries.
Atherton himself, lead by example. His fighting qualities and tenacity
was never more in evidence than on the last day of the series, and
during the hour on the previous evening. The praises showered upon him
by West Indies' manager, Wesley Hall, was indeed something of which to
be proud.
While the excellent performances of the mighty West Indians, who
dominated world cricket after the mid-seventies, were largely to be
expected, mention must be made of Brian Lara, the man of the match and
the West Indies' player of the series.
He stood out above all others with three centuries and hitting 765
runs at an average of 85. But the most extraordinary feat was reserved
for his final innings on Saturday when his 179 transformed the match,
taking it out of England's grasp and putting West Indies in a commanding
position.
It has been an enthralling, vivid series which has generated
scintillating cricket, and one which will be remembered for many a year.
Perhaps, the only reservation is that for the final showdown with both
teams level at 2-2, the benign Oval wicket remained too true to produce
a clinical finish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
