<TEXT>
* WHEN Glasgow echoed to the thunder of dark satanic mills, its
schools were full of coughing children. Smoke and chemicals from the
foundries, forges, locomotive works, mines and shipyards turned
buildings black -- and filled the young lungs with soot.
Yet the city was surrounded by beautiful countryside and clean air.
Charities were set up to offer the poor a holiday away from the gloom.
In a bid to offer a ''fresh-air fortnight'' to the peely-wally weans of
Glasgow, Montrose House was built on the banks of Loch Lomond at Balmaha
by the Duchess of Montrose in 1891.
It was a generous gesture, though the low building costs of 100 years
ago meant that charity came at an economic price. The building's fine
red sandstone came from a local quarry on the banks of the Catterburn.
The price was four shillings (20p) per ton!
Today's Glasgow is a cleaner place inhabited by kids who enjoy their
fresh-air fortnights in Benidorm or Magaluf, so the imposing building
has had to find a new use. Recently refurbished and converted into three
apartments, it now offers a ''fresh-air lifetime' at an affordable
price. Each apartment is self-contained and has its own entrance. Every
window has been replaced, and new plumbing and wiring have been
installed. Each also has central heating, new bathroom, new kitchen, and
a private garden. And each has a view of Loch Lomond. Many interior
details have been retained.
The ground floor has been turned into two dwellings. Clyde Property is
seeking offers over #70,000 for a two-bedroom flat and offers over
#85,000 for a three-bedroom one (which comes with its own patio and
French doors). The whole of the upper floor has been turned into a
single apartment with two public rooms and three bedrooms. Access is via
the original entrance vestibule and reception hall -- offers over
#97,000.
</TEXT>
