<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Watsonians join club with a three-year deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WATSONIANS became the latest first-division clubs to announce a
sponsorship deal with a brewing company, prompting the notion that the
game in Scotland is being consumed by beer as opposed to vice versa.
The Myreside club will benefit from a three-year agreement with
Caledonian Brewers of Edinburgh, whose logo will be worn on the
Watsonian jerseys, track suits, and kit bags.
It is as yet unknown whether the new deal, revealed just two days
after the momentous announcement from Paris about professionalism will
result in payments being made to Watsonian players.
''It is too early to say about player payment,'' said Ian Monteath,
club president, who added: ''we will discuss the matter at committee
level and with other clubs in Scotland.
''What I can say is that it will be very difficult to pay players this
year. We would need more money coming into the club.'' That possibility
may not yet be ruled out. According to a Watsonian committee man, the
Edinburgh club's dialogue with the Gartcosh businessman, John Connor,
whose son, Fraser, is a scrum half at Myreside, ''remains open.''
Watsonians finances would seem to be directed more towards the
#400,000 project to upgrade Myreside, permission for which is being
sought from Edinburgh District Council's planning department.
Plans for ground redevelopment reveal improvements and an extension to
the east terracing to bring the spectator capacity up to 7000, a
four-corner flood lighting system, and high-quality sports ground
advertising.
The club also released details of their first XV squad which, for the
second consecutive season, is under the direction of Peter Gallagher.
There will be no Sean Fitzpatrick at Myreside but Watsonians have
recruited a number of potentially useful players this season.
In addition to Kiwis, Cameron Mather and Mike Stanaway, who return for
another season, Gallagher will have in his squad New Zealanders Stuart
Mather, the North Shore tighthead prop, and hooker Si Farland, an under
21 All Black.
Also listed for this season are Calum Crozier, the former Australian
schools No.8, and New Zealander Mark te Whaiti, who has moved from
Currie. Watsonians also have recruited well from domestic stocks.
The top newcomers are Scotland under-21 flanker Stuart Grimes, North
and Midlands prop Tom Smith, Haddington hooker Grant McKelvie, and GHK
flanker Craig Brown. It also was confirmed yesterday that Watsonians, in
common with a number of other senior clubs in Scotland, will run an
under-21 side, an extensive fixture list for which has already been
drawn up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
