<HEADLINE>Flockhart is top Brit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GILLIAN DORRICOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633951</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRUCE Flockhart looks set to become the first Scot to play badminton
for Britain at the Olympics after reaching No.29 in the new world
rankings.
The 23-year-old is now the highest-placed Brit ahead of former
European champion Darren Hall and Anders Nielsen, with only the top two
in the rankings looking set to go to Atlanta in 1996.
Flockhart reached the third round of the Canadian Open last week to
jump up 12 places. The Stirling University student is on domestic turf
this weekend at the Perth Open, where the Scottish champion lines up as
a 5/8 seed in the same half of the draw as Nielsen.
Anne Gibson, the London-based Scottish champion who was recently
dropped from the Olympic squad, moved back up to world No.41 after
reaching the quarter-finals of the Canadian Open. She is 3/4 seed in the
same section as Jo Muggeridge, who beat her in last year's final.
</TEXT>
