<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tribute to the misty past of amateur rugby. Beware the peasoup fog of professionalism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEIL Kinnock and I agree. This is a slightly unusual statement to be
found in any of my musings, yet I doff my cap to the former Labour
leader, now European Commissioner, for his remarks about the
professionalisation of rugby football. ''I am rather sad about it,'' he
commented, ''and I wonder if the game will be quite the same in the
future.'' So do I.
Before the charge of ''old bufties'' is laid, that we are accused of
looking back to a golden age which never existed, or of attempting to
prevent young men making the most of their talents, let me make this
clear. I have no problem at all with the premise that players should be
paid. It must be 10 years ago since I suggested a flat fee should be
placed in a player's Trust Fund for every international cap he gained.
Anyone, however, who believes that the new ''Declaration of Paris'' is
going to lead to the famous ''level playing field'' deserves to be run
over by a lawnmower.
Craig Chalmers will not be paid the same as Jonah Lomu; Scottish
players will not earn the same as the All Blacks. And professional rugby
might well make some participants worse off than they are at the moment.
Before developing those arguments, let me pay a tribute at the
graveside of the amateur game. At its best rugby provided fun and
fellowship for millions; it was a sport almost completely free of
cheating, of fixed matches, of drug abusers.
There was a high degree of sportsmanship, referees decisions were
rarely questioned, and international matches provided players and
spectators alike with thrilling moments to savour.
The much-derided amateur ethic, that you did your job during the week
and had your recreation at the weekends, made a lot of sense. Playing
for eight, maybe 10 months of the year at a physically demanding, and
sometimes dangerous sport -- even for money -- is maybe not so smart.
Amateur rugby was not sold out by greedy players, but by weak and
indecisive administrators. It was the International Rugby Football Board
who refused to take any action against their own members who blatantly
flouted the laws laid down. That was what made a professional sport
inevitable.
In Australia, New Zealand, South Africa, France, Wales and England,
illegal payments were made every week of the season. The move towards
''anthing goes'' at least, in the words of Fred McLeod of the SRU,
''takes the hypocrisy out of the game.'' What, however, does it put in
its place?
Already Mr McLeod has stated, and would have the support of his
committee, that Scotland does not wish to see transfer fees being paid.
That's fine. But how do you stop them? What would be the position if
England or Wales decide transfers are a grand idea and offer Scottish
players inducements to join them?
It has happened, believe me. Are these players to be barred from
selection for Scotland? Then there is the ''win bonus.'' I am certain
the SRU would frown on that practice as well.
Even so, in an ''open'' sport, it must be perfectly legal for a
sponsor, or a rich local businessman, to put up an added incentive for
success in a big match. Indeed, how are we now to prevent clubs being
bought and sold like any other commodity? Club constitutions can be
changed just as easily as that of the IRFB.
I do not believe for a moment that the current Scottish squad will
attempt to hold the SRU to ransom. They are, collectively, a most
sensible and reasonable bunch of young men.
Yet all of them will know that signing a contract -- and boy, will
there be contracts -- does not come without obligation. The old days of
popping off for a fun weekend with the Saltires or the Wolfhounds, or
maybe even the Barbarians, could become a memory very quickly.
I believe the majority of the Scottish squad would wish to continue
with a career outside rugby. That would be a wise option.
If demands on their time increase, however, will they be able to do
so? If not, will they really be financially better off than they are
now? Players must know where they stand if they are injured playing the
game, whether other perks -- kit, cars, endorsements -- will be treated
as payment in kind by the Inland Revenue, whether there will be any kind
of pension scheme.
On the radio yesterday, I heard a reporter introduce an item by
saying: ''Now that the dust has settled on the proposals for
professional rugby...'' It is not dust, my friend, but a pea-souper of a
fog we are in, and that will take years to dispel.
We have not even covered the arguments about country v club, or even
to whom the players ''belong.'' We do not know whether referees will be
paid, or by whom.
In my time, the distinction between amateurs and professionals has
been swept away in cricket, largely successfully I think, in tennis, and
in athletics.
Despite the vast sums of prize money available, and staging the
world's most prestigous tournament, Britain has yet to produce a single
tennis player to frighten the world. Athletics has to battle every day
against the drug cheats, while it is more rewarding to set a world
record at a sponsored meeting than at the World Championships. And there
are fewer Scottish athletes in UK teams then ever I can recall.
How long, I wonder, before rugby is pressurised by television
companies, into changing the laws to suit the programmes? I hope the
players do well in the brave new world we have entered. I hope, too,
that the efforts of all the backroom people are recognised -- the club
secretaries, the medics, the physios, the touch judges, the selectors,
the blokes who travel with the fourth XV. And I hope these folk still
feel it is worth their while to be involved.
Maybe we are just getting old, Neil, but I have yet to be convinced we
will have a better game in 10 years' time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
