<HEADLINE>Fraser still flying the flag</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS
IT took 50 years for Japan to make public apology for events of the
Second World War. But Aussie swimmer Dawn Fraser was 19 years quicker.
During the Tokyo Olympics, Fraser was one of a trio who liberated the
Rising Sun from the flagpole at Emperor Hirohito's palace. Now, at the
World Student Games in Fukuoka, sprinter Fraser has returned a flag to
the Japanese: ''as a gesture of goodwill,'' she says.
The Aussies -- gold medal for diplomacy -- have made former Olympic
champion Fraser patron of their team.
Fraser, banned from world swimming as a result of the prank (the two
men who accompanied her kept quiet and escaped punishment) has retained
the original, auctioning it to raise funds for disabled Olympic
sportsmen.
Flying the sporting flag is often a painful experience, as Doug
Walker, in Japan, and Yvonne Murray in Lanarkshire, testified yesterday.
Edinburgh sprinter Walker, sole Scot in the UK track team in Fukuoka,
safely negotiated the opening two rounds of the 200 metres. Walker, who
has needed intensive back treatment since arriving in Japan, races the
semi-finals and, hopefully, final today.
Motherwell's Murray, meanwhile, has had a weight removed from her mind
by a 20-stone chiropractor. Now, relieved of sciatic pain, she travels
to the Berlin grand prix on Friday, and a 5000 metres world record
attempt by world champion Sonia O'Sullivan, more composed than at any
time this season.
''My physio, David Mclean, was nursing me along, but I did not wish to
admit even to myself that I had a problem,'' confessed Murray. ''I don't
like letting negative thoughts into my head. But the truth is that I
have not been able to get on my toes to sprint.''
Murray however will need to be exceptionally sharp when she faces
O'Sullivan and the current world record holder, Fernanda Ribiero.
O'Sullivan is chasing a possible #165,000 in gold bullion.
Melanie Neef may lose her place in the German event thanks to the
return of reinstated drug cheat Grit Breur. The suspension on the former
world junior 400m champion, banned along with Katrin Krabbe for using
the annabolic and stimulant agent, clenbuterol, expires tomorrow, and
Neef's lane may go to German.
</TEXT>
