<HEADLINE>Prestige award for site with new ideas to tempt buyers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DARREN RODGER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633955</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ADAM Homes was sure potential buyers visiting its new #6.5m
development of luxury flats and villas in Bearsden would be impressed.
And they were. The feedback has been more than favourable, with the
first apartments selling so quickly there hasn't been time to establish
a showflat. Then came the villas -- which sparked a similar, and
continuing, demand from buyers.
Now the luxury housebuilder is delighted to have further, concrete
confirmation of its achievements on the site in the form of a
prestigious National House-Building Council award.
Site manager James Harkins has been selected to receive a Quality
Award in this year's UK Pride In the Job competition, established by the
NHBC to foster quality in construction and reward commitment to quality
workmanship.
''I am absolutely delighted James has been chosen for this award,''
said David Nelson, managing director of Adam (Scotland). ''Henderland
Gate has been complimented by the general public and visitors throughout
this summer, and now this award indicates that their enthusiasm is
shared by the construction industry, and there is no higher authority in
house building than the NHBC.''
In fact the combination of the site -- in tranquil surroundings just
off the Switchback in Bearsden, with splendid views over the surrounding
area to the Erskine Bridge and Clyde estuary -- and Adam Homes' unique
House Exchange Plan is proving one which discerning house buyers are
finding hard to refuse.
Billed as the brave new world of house-buying, the deal removes
clients' fears about being unable to sell their existing home and
guarantees they simply cannot lose. The only ''catch'' is the
customer's: a brand-new luxury home.
But time is running out, as David Nelson explains: ''There are still a
few days left if anyone wants to take advantage of this successful
summer offer before we head into autumn, which is traditionally one of
the busiest seasons for house builders.''
Under the exchange plan, after reserving one of the villas the
client's own home is valued by an independent valuer and a mutually
acceptable minimum part-exchange price is agreed with Adam.
Once missives for the purchase of the new home are concluded, the
seller's property will be marketed by a leading estate agent, with all
advertising costs and agent fees to be borne by Adam. Should the
property be sold for more than the agreed minimum value, the seller
keeps all the proceeds. Should it sell for less, or not at all, Adam
will still pay the agreed minimum price in part exchange for the new
home.
''We've been delighted with the response. We are giving the client the
confidence to go ahead and put their house on the market because we are
picking up the estate agents' fee and advertising and providing a
minimum fall-back. It's a no-lose situation,'' said David Nelson.
''People are worried about spending weeks and weeks advertising with
the costs going up, worried about two mortgages. What we are doing is
underpinning that. We are saying we will take it on the chin.''
The development comprises a range of two and three-bedroom flats (28
in all) and 15 four and five-bedroom detached homes. All are built to
the highest standards, offering exceptionally spacious accommodation and
a very high level of specification. People have moved into the first
phase of flats, finished recently, and work is now under way on the
second phase.
''The flats have been selling so quickly that we haven't had time to
have a showflat, but we do have a completed flat which people can look
round.''
On the house front, the first residents have also begun to move in.
The show home, a five-bedroom Carnoustie detached villa with interior
design by Decorum of Sauchiehall Street, opened in March.
The rooms are generally much larger than usual, and the double doors
into the lounge, the patio doors in the dining room, the generous
hallways on both ground and upper level, the large ensuites, and the
extensive landscaped gardens all serve to give a feeling of space. A
choice of stylish bathrooms and fully equipped quality kitchens --
designed to maximise on space and storage -- are included in the price.
''Another reason for the continued popularity is the amount of space
in these flats and houses,'' said David Nelson. ''In the five-bedroom
house, for example, even the fifth bedroom can take a double bed, and
all the kitchens -- even those in the flats -- have been designed to
take a table for dining. All of the flats have balconies leading off
from the lounge, most with a view.''
Each flat is supplied with satellite television, and there is an
aerial point in every room. The villas have living flame fireplaces and
patios leading to the gardens, and the developers offer a carpets and
curtains package.
Henderland Gate is close to shopping and transport facilities as well
as being within easy reach of the city centre. Prices are from #98,000
for a two-bedroom flat and from #198,000 for the Braemar four-bedroom
detached villa.
''We think we have a winning package at Henderland Gate, and James's
award is a real bonus when you consider that the NHBC is the premier
standard setting and warranty organisation for the UK house-building
industry,'' said David Nelson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nicol will be tested</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH champion Peter Nicol, who underwent a tonsil operation in
June, faces a stiff test of his fitness when he opens his season against
former British title-holder Paul Gregory in today's first round of the
Cathay Pacific Perrier Open in Hong Kong.
The operation was a success, but the world No.4 did miss several
weeks' summer training and has not played since the Champion of
Champions in early June.
''I'm a bit short of match practice, and it's a tough draw,'' said
Nicol, who goes on to compete in the JSM Classic in Japan next week.
Nicol is in the same quarter as Simon Parke, winner of last week's
Malaysian Open, and the same half as world No.1 Jansher Khan.
Neil Harvey, Nicol's London-based coach, regards this as the start of
the build-up to the World Open in Cyprus in November. He said: ''I'll be
delighted if Peter reaches the semi-finals this week.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Goal-hero Platt to have surgery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN ENGLAND
DAVID Platt will undergo surgery tomorrow to repair a torn cartilage
in his right knee and he will miss England's match against Colombia next
week as well as at least two Premiership games.
Arsenal manager Bruce Rioch revealed Platt's injury after the midfield
player scored a fine goal in the 1-1 Highbury draw against Nottingham
Forest.
''He did it in training the day before we played Inter-Milan in a
pre-season friendly three weeks ago, and now we are going to lose him
for two games at least, although the doctors say he could be back in
training inside 10 days,'' said Rioch.
The game stated well for the Gunners with Platt's strike, but Kevin
Campbell, who left Arsenal for Nottingham Forest in the summer for
#2.5m, notched his first goal since December from a pass by Scot Gemmill
after 63 minutes.
And two minutes from time, the Highbury reject almost grabbed a
glorious winner, forcing keeper David Seaman to save from a fiercely
struck volley. It did not look like Campbell's night when he missed a
golden opportunity in the first half, driving the ball against Seaman
when clear.
Bryan Roy missed a similar opportunity but it took a spectacular
effort from Platt to put Arsenal's noses in front three minutes before
the interval. Good work by Ray Parlour got the ball out to the flank for
Lee Dixon, whose cross was volleyed home by Platt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bruno ready for 'demon' McCall</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRANK Bruno and Oliver McCall had the gloves off yesterday, in a
verbal sense, when they met at the National Maritime Museum in
Greenwich.
Bruno was upset that the American referred to his mother, wife, and
children during the build-up to Saturday's WBC heavyweight title clash
at Wembley. ''To bring my family into it is not right,'' said the
Englishman. ''He is a disgrace as champion, he's a demon.
''I can't wait to fight, I can't wait to put my fist in his face and
shove all those words down his throat.''
The crossfire was music to promoter Don King's ears, but the hatred
looked genuine, with McCall having more to say than Bruno. At one stage
Bruno countered as McCall went into full verbal attack: ''Cool it,
that's libellous, man.''
McCall seized quickly on Bruno's three stoppages in previous
world-title fights against Tim Witherspoon, Mike Tyson, and Lennox
Lewis. The champion said: ''To say: 'I'm going to beat him like my
father used to' makes my father sound like a child-abuser. If he has his
way and makes me look bad, losing to someone with no fighting skills,
winning is not going to make him look any better because he'll be
knocked down in his first defence.
''You have no skills, all you have is rap. You don't have nothing. I
don't even consider you beating me. It's like thinking you'll go to hell
when you die. I'll be going to heaven.''
Bruno claimed: ''It's quite simple. I'm going to knock him out. What
he is saying is all hype -- it means nothing. I'm not going to get on
this bandwagon. What I want to do is add a bit of class to the
heavyweight division. I'm grateful. I'm going to seize the moment.''
* ULSTERMAN Ray Close has had his hopes of fighting for the world
title dented by the British Boxing Board of Control. He was refused
permission to box Chris Eubank for a third time in February after
failing a CT scan. He has now received the all-clear in Ireland, but
that is not enough to satisfy the BBBC.
The former European super-middleweight champion returns to the ring on
September 9 in Cork on the Eubank-Steve Collins bill but has been
refused permission to box anyone from Britain.  An opponent for him has
still to be named.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000036</DOCNO>
