<HEADLINE>Graf is the star on show court</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US OPEN TENNIS
STEFFI Graf, the No.1 seed, regained her composure after having lost
the opening set to beat Amanda Coetzer 6-7 (1-7), 6-1, 6-4 and move into
the second round of the US Open in New York yesterday.
At first, Graf's game was full of errors but the South African's play
was not without flaw and she needed nine set points to take the lead.
Graf was in danger of becoming the first top-seeded woman to fall in
the first round since seedings began in 1922. But she found the range on
her ground-strokes, especially the forehand, and Coetzer began to hit
more errors. Graf closed out the tie on her second match point, gaining
revenge for her only defeat so far this year.
One seeded player did fall, with Austrian Barbara Paulus beating No.13
Iva Majoli, of Croatia, 6-4, 6-4.
Seeds advancing included the No.4, Conchita Martinez of Spain, Czech
Jana Novotna, seeded fifth, Kimiko Date of Japan (7), American Lindsay
Davenport (10), Germany's Anke Huber (11), Natasha Zvereva, of Belarus
(12), American Mary Joe Fernandez (14) and Brenda Schultz-McCarthy of
Holland (16).
In the men's event, Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi had easy successes,
Agassi defeating hard-serving Bryan Shelton 6-2, 6-2, 6-2, while Sampras
brushed Fernando Meligeni aside 6-0, 6-3, 6-4.
Agassi was ranked only No.20 for last year's tournament as he battled
back from wrist surgery and made the adjustment to his new coach, Brad
Gilbert. Since then, the flamboyant American has posted an amazing 88-10
match record, including 20 wins in a row.
Another British player, Chris Woodruff, went out, beaten 6-4, 7-6
(7-5), 6-4 by Australian Todd Woodbridge.
Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov, seeded No.7, defeated Jeff Tarango,
playing in his first match since being defaulted at Wimbledon, 6-0, 6-4,
7-5. The No.13 seed, Marc Rosset, of Switzerland, the No.9, Swede Thomas
Enqvist, and Spain's Sergi Bruguera, seeded No.11, also went through.
* SCOTLAND'S Donald Watt opened his bid for the men's singles title at
the British over-35 championship in Eastbourne with a convincing 6-0,
6-3 win over Hertfordshire's Keith Abbott yesterday.
</TEXT>
