<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sterling gains against the dollar</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633968</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STERLING had a mixed tone in late European trading. In the absence of
fresh factors the pound is expected to mirror movements elsewhere.
Yesterday with volumes still light in the summer holiday season, the
pound added 0.1 on its trade-weighed index to 84.6. It was almost a
third-of-a-cent better than the dollar at $1.5453 and is expected to
remain above $1.5400.
Despite a weaker German mark, sterling slipped more than
half-a-pfennig to DM2.2740. The mark succumbed to profit-taking in the
wake of sharp gains against the French franc on Monday. This followed
the surprise resignation of Finance Minister Alain Madelin.
Elsewhere, the Italian lira continued to do well and the Spanish
peseta remained steady.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Few firms comply with Greenbury</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SURVEY of 50 leading companies by Arthur Andersen showed that none
complied fully with the recommendations of the Greenbury report on
boardroom pay and many had a long way to go.
The international firm of accountants analysed the latest annual
reports of 50 of the UK's top 250 companies and found the average level
of compliance with the Greenbury code was only 31%.
The biggest companies came out better than smaller ones, but the
degree of compliance varied greatly from sector to sector.
Privatised energy companies had a relatively good compliance rate of
50%, but the financial sector came off worst with only 13%.
Many of the annual reports analysed were published before the
committee headed by Marks &amp; Spencer chairman Sir Richard Greenbury
announced its recommendations on directors' pay and conditions in July.
But Arthur Andersen said they all came out at time when disclosure was
already major issue and there was strong public awareness of many of the
best practice points highlighted by Greenbury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
