<HEADLINE>Facia group buys 245 shoe shops</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHEFFIELD entrepeneur Stephen Hinchcliffe, head of the retail group
Facia, is further expanding his fast-growing empire with the acquisition
of 245 shoe shops from the British Shoe Corporation, it was announced
yesterday.
The disposal by the British Shoe Corporation, part of the Sears group,
of its Freeman Hardy Willis, Trueform and Manfield stores has been made
at a loss ''in the region of #16m'', said Sears in a statement, although
no value was put on the sale.
But it added that the deal would allow it to focus on a small number
of competitive brands -- Shoe Express, Hush Puppies, Shore Connection,
Dolcis and Shoe City.
''The advantages to BSC of managing this simpler portfolio will be
felt throughout the business and, in particular, will allow us to review
again during the remainder of this year the level of fixed costs
required to support this simplified structure,'' said Sears' chief
executive Liam Strong.
Under the deal, Facia said it would acquire assets worth more than
#11m and take on no liabilities. It will also move its head office from
Sheffield to London.
It will add #75m to annual sales, taking group sales to more than
#250m and the number of stores to approximately 800.
The deal comes almost exactly one year after Facia was formed to
acquire Salisbury's, the luggage store, from Signet Group.
Since then the company has become the second largest independent
retailer in the country.
</TEXT>
