<HEADLINE>Overflow bonus for water show</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN before George Kynoch, MP, Scottish Office Minister for Industry
and Local Government, officially opens Scottish Water '95, the two-day
event is well on the way to success.
Now in its second year, the National Water &amp; Wastewater Exhibition in
the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre, Glasgow, which opens at
10am on Wednesday, September 6, has attracted so many major exhibitors
-- over 120 at the last count -- that it has been moved into the
centre's 2100 square metre Hall 5, and is an acknowledged sell-out.
Scottish Water '95 is organised by International Trade Publications
(ITP) Ltd, publishers of the magazine Water Services and part of Argus
Business Media Ltd which, with a current portfolio of 36 exhibitions, is
a major international exhibition organiser in its own right.
ITP Ltd also publishes Water &amp; Environment International and the Water
Services Year Book and, as a company, is totally committed to the water
industry.
With this dedicated background, bearing in mind that Water Services is
a long established and respected UK water industry title dating back to
1899, Scottish Water '95 is a precisely targeted event organised with
water industry professionals and manufacturing industry environmental
managers in its sights. It is the perfect showcase for the most
up-to-date quality equipment and technology available.
Last year Scottish Water '94 attracted more than 1000 chief decision
makers, a senior level turn-out from the Scottish River Purification
Boards, regional councils and manufacturing industry. Once again the aim
is to attract the most influential buyers and specifiers from regional
councils' senior water industry, plant, project and systems managers and
engineers; the Scottish River Purification Boards' senior pollution
control managers and officers, scientists and laboratory personnel; the
manufacturing industry's plant managers, environmental control managers
plus directors and managers responsible for effluent treatment and
environmental controls as well as water companies, contractors,
consultants and process engineers.
Roy Greenslade, managing director of ITP Ltd, the exhibition's
organisers, said: ''The event attracted top drawer members of the water
industry north of the Border. Now that we are in Scotland's No1
exhibition venue, where we have been able to accommodate an even greater
number of quality exhibitors than before, we are confident that
representatives of the regional councils, the River Purification Boards,
manufacturing industry and independent consultants will make it a
priority to attend.
This year's exhibitors are very conscious that the Scottish Water
industry is advancing with an expensive and technologically ambitious
water and sewerage programme which will result in a collective spend of
over #1bn over the next five years to meet the stringent new national
and EC water and wastewater laws.
At the same time, Scotland's manufacturing industry, including
petrochemicals, paper-making, brewing, distilling and electronics, is
under even tighter scrutiny from the powerful River Purification Boards
as they clamp down on polluters.
With suppliers to the industry all competing for the business of the
three new public water authorities, the standard of exhibition and
display at Scottish Water '95 is geared to be high.
Companies exhibiting know that it all adds up to creating a
challenging high-value market for suppliers of water and wastewater
treatment and management products and services.
The new European wastewater legislation which became law in Scotland
in 1990 has resulted in major and ongoing changes. With substantial
investment being made by the reorganised local authorities in new
equipment technologies and services, Scottish Water '95 is the ideal
shop window for providers.
The exhibition is dedicated to practical water and wastewater
solutions and is committed to attracting key Scottish buyers and
specifiers. All regional council water departments will also have stands
at the exhibition. So important is this water industry shop window for
Scotland that one company, MCS Measurement and Control Systems, hopes to
be celebrating the opening of its new Scottish premises at the show.
Over September 6 and 7, Scottish Water '95 is set to provide a
valuable and unique industry forum for those involved in the water and
wastewater industry. It is appropriate that the premier exhibition of
its type is taking place this year in the SECC. It is easily reached
from main roads into the city and there is secure car parking with over
3000 spaces.
</TEXT>
