<DOCNO>GH950830-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pinkerton secures capital base</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAMBERS dictionary describes Allan Pinkerton (1819-1884) as an
American detective. But as mosts Scots know, the Colt-45-toting,
duster-raincoated scourge of Wild West outlaws, was actually from
Glasgow's Gorbals, forced to flee these shores after a warrant was
issued for his arrest because of his involvement in Chartism, the
19th-century movement to bring political power to the lower classes.
From next month though it is the Edinburgh baddies who had better
watch out as the Pinkerton mob opens its second Scottish office.
''It's ironic really that Glasgow was the last major city in the UK to
have a Pinkerton office,'' said Bill Dunne, the company's director for
Scotland.
''The time had to be right for us to return to Scotland as it would
have been unimaginable to fail in our founder's home town, but I'm
pleased to say that since we opened our first Scottish office in January
1993, our annual Scottish turnover has exceeded #3m.''
The Edinburgh office of Pinkerton Security Services, now a major
player in the world security industry, will be on the corner of London
Road and Easter Road. The company has already won a number of east coast
contracts including Scottish Widows, the Edinburgh International
Conference Centre and the US Consulate -- a far cry from young
Pinkerton's first American client, an unknown, newly qualified solicitor
by the name of Abraham Lincoln who worked for the Illinois railway
company.
When Lincoln was inaugurated President, he remembered the young
Scotsman and asked him to set up the American Secret Service during the
Civil War.
''Just about everyone knows of Pinkerton's legendary chases involving
the likes of Jesse James and Billy the Kid,'' said Mr Dunne, but it
should also be remembered that he was responsible for the introduction
of US federal law.
''A lot of people think that it was J Edgar Hoover who formed the FBI,
but it was Pinkerton who planted the roots for both the FBI and the
CIA.''
Today, the company has offices throughout Continental Europe and the
US, and recently opened branches in Russia and China.
The posse today consists of 55,000 people and the rewards amount to an
annual worldwide turnover in excess of #1000m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
