<DOCNO>GH950830-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gartmore sees profits slide</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FUND manager Gartmore's revenue in the first half of 1995 was little
changed at #42.6m against #42.4m for the same period last year, but
there has been a decline from #17.4m to #16.2m at the pre-tax level with
operating expenses up by 9% to #28.2m, writes CHRIS STONE.
The company warned in March at the time of its 1994 results -- which
had profits 29% ahead from #27.3m to #35.3m despite volatile stock
market conditions around the world -- that the need to make significant
investments in systems and staff would weigh on profitability this year.
This investment is mainly to support the development of the company's
international client base, currently below 20%. However, the market was
not impressed with the flat revenue performance and the shares dipped 6p
to 212p at the close having lost 11p at one stage.
Fees earned on funds under management did increase on the back of new
business won and higher world securities markets, but this was offset by
reduced income from sales of unitised funds and the launch of new
products.
Gartmore gained new funds under management of #1300m during the period
which, together with market movements contributed to an increase in
funds under management of 12% from #20.8bn at December 31 to #23.3bn at
June 30. New business was particularly strong in UK pension fund
management but the momentum slowed as the period progressed.
Chairman Paul Myners also reported that retail investment sentiment
remained subdued with net sales of UK authorised unit trusts down to
#38m compared to #62m in the first half of 1994. He made the point,
though, that this experience was rather better than the industry as a
whole.
Net sales of #29m by Capital Strategy Fund, Gartmore's main offshore
fund, were also down from the #35m chalked up in the same period last
year.
As part of its higher overseas profile strategy, Gartmore recently
established a joint venture with NationsBank of the US -- Nations
Gartmore Investment Management. It is developing plans to establish a
wholly owned investment management subsidiary in Tokyo.
At present, Japanese investment inquiries are managed through Indosuez
Gartmore Asset Management (Japan), a company jointly owned with
Paris-based Banque Indosuez, which still retains 75% of Gartmore having
floated off 25% at the end of 1993. However, Gartmore's interest in this
company is to be sold at book value to another member of the Banque
Indosuez group.
For the moment, Gartmore is being constrained by additional costs as
it gears itself for new business opportunities, and profits, of course,
are also linked to the level of world share markets.
The interim dividend is held at 1.75p on earnings per share down from
5.6p to 5.2p.
</TEXT>
