<DOCNO>GH950830-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US bank merger poses challenge to UK sector</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976633974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE merger between two of America's largest banks, Chase Manhattan and
Chemical which will have combined assets of $300bn, has direct
implications here not least because it will lead to the loss of several
hundred jobs.
Like other banks operating in global wholesale money markets, the two
have built extensive operations in the City of London over the past
decade or so and now employ 2150 between them. Chase's international
custody operations are based in Bournemouth where it has 1500 staff,
making it one of the town's largest employers.
Chemical has a similar operation in Cardiff with 200 people. Overall,
the merger will lead to the loss of 12,000 jobs worldwide out of a total
of 76,000, representing about 16%. This would equate to about 600 here,
though a spokesman cautioned against making a straight calculation,
adding that the effects of the merger had not been worked out yet. There
is also considerable staff turnover so compulsory redundancies may be
much lower than this figure.
As in so many things it is tempting to believe that what happens in
the US will soon happen here, but in the case of banks this looks
unlikely. For a start, the industry has developed differently in the UK
-- it is already highly concentrated here whereas it is fragmented in
the US as a result of a ban on inter-state banking.
Bank of Scotland and TSB are sometimes thought vulnerable to a
takeover but it is hard to see what a predator could bring to Bank of
Scotland, for example, given the goodwill cost of such a pillar of
Scottish business. It is also 32% owned by Standard Life which would not
sell in a hurry.
Mergers between the big clearing banks can be virtually ruled out
because of monopoly considerations. The Office of Fair Trading simply
couldn't allow a further concentration of ownership. But other factors
at work will make it vitally necessary for all banks to keep driving
their costs down which before long is likely to prompt another round of
branch closures.
Cost-cutting is the over-riding reason for the Chase and Chemical
union, as it has been in the wave of mergers among smaller US banks this
year. Chemical will emerge on top, with its managers in key positions in
the combined enterprise and its shareholders having 55% of the equity.
Chemical has come up fast, having merged with Manufacturers Hanover in
1991, and it will now top Citicorp to become the biggest US bank.
However, Chase has a major consolation prize in that it will provide the
name of the enlarged group.
US banks have recovered well this decade from the poor-quality lending
debacles of the eighties, greatly helped by the Federal Reserve Board
which ensured that long-term rates fell less quickly than short-term so
the banks could profit from the differential. Now the sector is strongly
capitalised.
So the merger certainly doesn't indicate financial weakness. But it
does reflect shrinking earnings growth opportunities and increasing
competition. The slowing US economy has curtailed loan demand and
devices such as share buy-backs have run their course. Earnings can be
kept moving by achieving economies of scale and rationalisation after
merger.
Competition is coming from non-traditional areas. Financial services
companies such as Fidelity have moved from fund management to
stockbroking to money market accounts with cheque books, and other
services are sure to follow. Then there are the software giants like
Microsoft eyeing electronic banking.
Without the deadweight of a branch network such companies promise to
pose as much of a competitive challenge as the direct insurers have done
to traditional insurance companies with branches and sales forces.
However, in the UK the main action as far as consolidation is
concerned will involve the building societies where a lot more corporate
activity lies in store as mutuality is abandoned and over-capacity in
stagnant mortgage markets forces rationalisation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
