<HEADLINE>Broker withdraws from ram infertility insurance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FINDING insurance against infertility for expensive pedigree rams will
now be almost impossible following the news that a leading Scottish firm
of brokers is to withdraw from the market after heavy losses.
A spokesperson for the broker, who wants to remain anonymous, said
that recently claims of #45,000 had been settled against the premium
income of only #3000 and that no underwriter was prepared to look at
this aspect of livestock insurance.
The NFU Mutual, which has also provided cover against infertility, is
''urgently reviewing the situation'', but will still look at each
individual case ''on its merits''. However, a spokesperson for the
Mutual said she thought it was more than likely it would also pull out
of the market.
The final event at which the Scottish broker offered cover was last
month's sale of pedigree Suffolks in Edinburgh, where a new record price
of 68,000 guineas was set. The broker explained that in the past it had
only been the more expensive rams which were insured against
infertility.
He also explained that if breeders were serious in seeking cover it
should be a matter for individual breed societies to initiate a scheme
under which all rams sold at official sales were automatically covered.
This, he said, would provide sufficient premium income to cover any
losses.
Most breed societies currently have a fertility guarantee, which in
the case of the Suffolk Society says that a ram has four months to prove
himself by putting just one ewe in lamb. The society's rules state that
this period can be extended by both the seller and buyer entering into a
written agreement.
If at the conclusion of the trial period the ram is still infertile
the seller must refund the full purchase price plus any expenses, but
there is no allowance made for consequential loss.
When cover was available the cost was in the region of #500 for a
#10,000 ram. Cover for death alone runs at 12.5% so the same ram would
cost #1250 to insure for a full year. Recently there have been rumours
that a larger than usual number of high priced Suffolk rams were
infertile when tested after the Edinburgh sale.
However, Dr Bill McKelvie of SAC said this was not the case.
''Absolutely not, I have seen most of the top priced Suffolks and I have
to say that in the main fertility is very good.''
However, he did add that following the stress involved at sale time
some rams might not be 100% fertile, but that after a period of two or
three weeks they would be back to normal.
</TEXT>
