<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United offloads cheap brands.      Guinness arm sells two US distilleries and agrees bulk whisky deal.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633978</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNITED Distillers has completed its withdrawal from the lower end of
the US spirits market, selling two US distilleries and a 37 brand names
to Barton Inc, a subsidiary of the fast-growing Canandaigua Wine
Company.
The deal also provides for United Distillers to sell bulk Scotch
whisky to Barton for several years and for Barton to continue packaging
United Distillers products in the United States.
United Distillers, a subsidiary of Guinness, will receive a total
consideration of $171m, part of which will be paid in future years
against bulk whisky shipments.
The company declined to detail the value or volume of these bulk
whisky sales.
United Distillers tried to boost its presence at the bottom end of the
US spirits market in 1991, when it bought Glenmore Distillers for $161m.
The acquisition made it the third-largest player in the US market with
a 14% market share.
But a policy reversal came two years later when it sold 70 minor US
brands to Heaven Hill for an undisclosed sum to concentrate on premium
brands instead.
The Barton deal completes United Distillers' exit from the lower end
of the US market and gets rid of most of Glenmore's remaining assets.
But the UK company has hung on to the jewel in the Glenmore crown --
Scoresby whisky, which is America's top-selling locally bottled Scotch.
Scoresby, which sells just under one million cases per year, ranks
number four overall in the US Scotch whisky market after Dewars, Johnnie
Walker Red Label and Johnnie Walker Black Label.
United Distillers managing director Finn Johnsson said the Barton deal
was ''consistent with our strategy of concentrating our efforts on
premium high-priced brands with long-term growth prospects.''
Alan Gray, whisky analyst with Edinburgh stockbroker Sutherland and
Partners, welcomed the move.
He and other analysts said it showed that Mr Johnsson was making his
mark on United Distillers after taking over as managing director in
February.
''I was surprised by the acquisition of Glenmore in 1991 which took
United Distillers into the lower end of the market at a time when they
were emphasising their commitment to brand building,'' Mr Gray said.
''Withdrawal from this end of the market makes it look as if it was an
area they should not have gone into. Hopefully it marks a return to
concentration on quality brands,'' he added.
Among the cheap brands sold to Barton are the US rights to Inver House
Scotch and the popular vodkas Fleischmann and Skol. Barton also takes
over the Glenmore distilleries and bottling plants at Owensboro,
Kentucky, and Albany, Georgia.
The brands sold generated $231m of gross sales last year and $19m of
operating income. In volume terms they represented about five million
cases of spirits.
Guinness shares fell 7[1/2]p to 493[1/2]p, but traders said this
reflected a general decline in blue chips rather than negative reaction
to the Barton deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
