<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adman's Scotland heads for a fall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976633980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AH, BLISS! When I came through from Glasgow to Edinburgh on an early
train today the whole Central Belt was covered in a thick and thoroughly
satisfying Scotch mist, lightened only by the infernal fires of
Grangemouth.
It was a huge relief after what is always the worst weekend of the
year, the last in August, when the flood of tourists swells to a
torrent. With the lemming-like instinct of the English on bank holiday,
waves of them spill over the Border to submerge the capital in their
sweaty selves and their detritus.
The nethermost pit of this Hell is the George Hotel, where luvvies
gather for the Television Festival. As a reactionary, I scorn even to
own an idiot-box, so have no interest in their back-slapping and
glad-handing. But I once let myself be led in by my good friend
''Brute'' Anderson, political editor of the Sunday Express, a son of
Shetland who promised I would detest every minute of it. What was on the
contrary diverting, after I entered in such exalted company, was how
many people pretended to remember who I was: Simon Heffer, to whom I
bear a faint resemblance. At least it meant plenty of free triple
whiskies and, when Brute and I at length meandered out into the
sunshine, he turned to me and said: ''Aye, it's not long till
November.''
Still, even while we long for the clocks to go back and the permafrost
to descend, we might usefully reflect that this has been reckoned a
bumper tourist season. It has by the same token confounded the forecasts
of our tourism experts, who in an earlier report appeared to be warning
that Scotland as a destination was in terminal decline. A review of
strategy should therefore be undertaken, and no doubt more support
should come from the Government: the usual stuff.
Nothing daunted, when Ian Grant, chairman of the Scottish Tourist
Board, was asked how the experts had got things so wrong, he blithely
put it down to the success of his outfit's latest advertising campaign.
It would be interesting to discover what was so much better about this
campaign than all the previous ones.
If I may judge from my own American visitors, they came in complete
ignorance of what to expect. The North-east of the United States is not
exactly the end of the world, but they had found it impossible to get
any worthwhile information, and were reduced to phoning me to ask what
books to read. ''Gee, I never guessed you had all this,'' one said as we
drove under a magnificently cloud-capped Ben Loyal. ''I thought Scotland
was just fat men in kilts jerking about with tree trunks.''
So much for projecting Caledonia, stern and wild. I learned besides
that, in contrast to their minds' foggy image of Scotland, my American
guests had believed Ireland to be the most beautiful country in this
quarter of the globe, with rugged mountains, limpid lochs, tinkling
burns etc. Since Ireland is my ancestral home, I know it well, and can
vouch that, apart from a few knobbly bits round the edges, it is flat
and boring in its landscapes, if not in its inhabitants. When we in
Scotland have so much more, I wonder about the long-term efficacy of the
Scottish Tourist Board's advertising campaigns.
I wonder again when I read about some of its future plans, for example
the promotion of native cuisine. Can this be the same Scottish Tourist
Board as was responsible for the ghastly Taste of Scotland, with salmon
swimming in whisky and similar horrors? True, our restaurants have
improved beyond measure in recent times, and we now have some of the
finest country house hotels anywhere, but the best would not touch Taste
of Scotland with a bargepole. We owe them to the dedication and skill of
people such as David Wilson at the Peat Inn, or the Browns at La
Potiniere, or the Allens at Airds, people whose commitment is to quality
rather than gimmicks.
Here is a clue to how the performance of Scottish tourism might be
improved, if indeed it can be improved in the conventional sense, which
is by no means certain. This is not, and never will be, a mass market to
be manipulated by tourist boards. The mass market can fly to Benidorm,
and good luck to it as long as it stays away from me. Given that, we are
foolish to measure success in terms of hordes attracted. We should try
to be not the Spain of the North but the Switzerland of the North, a
place for discerning tourists, above all rich ones, who make up in
spending what they lack in numbers.
To attract them we need more Scots committed to quality rather than
gimmicks. I cannot tell you how to find them, but then Mr Grant of the
Scottish Tourist Board cannot tell you either. They find themselves,
through whatever motivates them. And if they are good at what they do,
they find customers too. This is what we call a free market, and I have
never heard of a free market run by a quango. But it is the way the
world works.
For the remainder of the year we can look forward to Mr Grant's Autumn
Gold campaign. This is surely the last resort. America's fall foliage
attracts tourists, so it must follow -- mustn't it? -- that Scotland can
attract them with a feeble imitation. Let me tell you something,
Scotland's autumn is not golden. It is cold, wet, and miserable, I am
looking forward to it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000058</DOCNO>
