<DOCNO>GH950830-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>College lecturer alleges racial bias</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN electronics lecturer at the Glasgow College of Nautical Studies has
alleged that he missed out on promotion because of racial
discrimination.
Mr Ali Liaquat, of Dalry Gardens, Earnock, Hamilton, has worked as an
electronics lecturer at the college since February 1984.
He claims racial discrimination prevented his promotion to senior
lecturer in radio and marine electronics last January.
In his application for a hearing before an industrial tribunal, Mr
Liaquat claimed that ''his qualifications were better than the
successful candidate''.
He also stated that there was a campaign of racial discrimination
against him in 1987 and his promotion had been ''blocked'' and that in
1994 he was again the victim of racial discrimination.
A preliminary determination hearing of the tribunal has ruled that the
alleged acts, prior to those events which culminated in the unsuccessful
application for promotion last January, are themselves time-barred.
However, the tribunal noted: ''In a case of this kind, we are clearly
of the view that there are circumstances in which a limited reference
might be made in evidence to historical matters, without in any sense
regarding such reference as being for the purpose of developing a case
of a continuing act of discrimination.''
A full tribunal hearing will be held at a later date to decide the
issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
