<DOCNO>GH950830-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>S&amp;N director cashes in</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH &amp; Newcastle director Ian Hannah made nearly #265,000 by
cashing in share options last week, it was yesterday revealed.
His profits from the share dealings are greater than his annual
salary.
Mr Hannah, who is chairman and managing director of the group's retail
division, exercised options to purchase 103,309 shares, at prices
ranging from 225p to 395p, on Friday.
He sold all of these shares, which cost #365,602, on the same day for
#630,185.
Mr Hannah, 52, joined Edinburgh-based Scottish &amp; Newcastle in 1979. He
is a former chairman of The Newcastle Breweries, William Younger and
Thistle Hotels.
At April 30, Scottish &amp; Newcastle's most recent year-end, Mr Hannah
had 153,363 options over Ordinary shares under the company's executive
and savings-related schemes. At that date, 132,443 of these were
exercisable.
No options were exercised by directors under the executive share
option scheme during the 12 months to April 30.
A Scottish &amp; Newcastle official yesterday pointed out that the
company's directors had been unable to sell any shares during the
lengthy closed period relating to the #425m acquisition of Courage from
Fosters Brewing Group, which received the regulatory green light earlier
this month.
She added: ''The sale of these shares was obviously for personal
reasons.''
</TEXT>
