<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fisons sells distribution business for #201m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FISONS, under #1700m bid siege from US-based drugs company
Rhone-Poulenc Rorer (RPR) which is 68% owned by Rhone Poulenc of France,
yesterday announced the sale of its distribution business to Fisher
Scientific for #201m cash, writes CHRIS STONE.
This comprises the distribution businesses within the the
pharmaceuticals group's laboratory supplies division, Curtin Matheson
Scientific Inc in the US and Fisons Scientific Equipment in the UK.
The agreement, which is subject to obtaining necessary regulatory
consents and the approval of shareholders, is part of the company's
strategy of selling divisions to fund its transformation into a sales
and marketing-dominated operation, a policy already described by RPR as
''high risk''.
Fisons is also in a late stage negotiation with other parties
regarding the sale of US-based J&amp;W Scientific, the remaining business
within the Laboratory Supplies Division. Analysts expect this to fetch
between #30m to #40m.
The sale of the distribution side will be the third major disposal by
the group in the past six months and was generally accepted by the
market as beefing up the company's strength against the RPR bid.
Fisons' chief executive, Stuart Wallis, said: ''It effectively
completes the company's disposal programme and creates a focused
pharmaceutical company with a clear strategy for profitable growth. When
completed, these deals will have generated proceeds of #600m which will
adequately support the continued development of the business.''
RPR's terms of 240p a share represent a valuation of 24 times this
year's estimated earnings, but after disposals earnings will rise next
year and there will also be the company's cash pile.
Given that Fisons' share price at 257[1/2]p, up 2p yesterday, is still
substantially above the bid price the market has felt all along that RPR
would have to offer more. But there does not seem to have been much
questioning of the logic behind the bid, just doubts about whether the
price is right.
</TEXT>
