<DOCNO>GH950830-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conservation scheme proves to be popular</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS,FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Environmentally Sensitive Area Scheme, which offers payments of up
to #7000 to farmers who undertake a farm conservation plan, is the most
popular of the five major initiatives which form the Agri-Environment
Programme.
The total area covered in Scotland by the scheme is almost 1.5 million
hectares, representing 19% of the agricultural land, the Farming and
Wildlife Advisory Group said.
Participating farmers and crofters are encouraged to adopt practices
aimed at basic management of environmental features such as heather,
moorland, native woodland, field and waterside margins.
The scheme is generally considered by farmers to be a good one, the
advisory group said. ''There are many positive aspects, including
additional farm income, improved wildlife habitat and enhanced visual
impact.'' It also helps to keep rural communities alive by providing
funds for contract labour for capital projects such as fencing, building
dikes or hedging.
The next most popular programme is the Habitat Scheme which was
launched in November last year. Steady demand is expected, especially if
the land involved is eligible for entry into set-aside. The scheme
requires long-term withdrawal of land from agricultural production in
order to create a range of wildlife habitats. Annual management payments
can go up to #360 a hectare.
One participant is Norman Massie of East Cairnhill, Insch, who is
creating a wetland on a poorly-drained field to attract wading birds
such as snipe, lapwing and redshank.
''I've always had problems with that field, which is difficult to
drain and getting wetter,'' said Mr Massie. ''Now I can manage the site
for the benefit of birds and receive an annual payment of #105 an acre
for 10 years.''
The Organic Aid Scheme has attracted interest mainly in the island
communities of Orkney and on the west coast mainland.
One of the least popular programmes is the Set-Aside Access Scheme --
a five-year agreement under which farmers are paid #90 a hectare for 10
metre wide access strips. Conditions include provision of gates for
access, regular mowing and erection of signposts and fences. ''It all
seems a lot of work for very little return,'' FWAG said.
Bottom of the list comes the Heather Moorland Scheme, which was the
last to be launched. Farmers are entitled to payments in return for
reducing livestock grazing.
* FWAG, under the direction of new chief executive David Ball, has
published advice for farmers on the safe storage and use of manufactured
fertilisers and farmyard manure.
''Heeding the advice in this booklet will save farmers money as well
as safeguarding the environment,'' said the National Rivers Authority,
which co-operated in producing the publication.
The booklet sets out advice on establishing buffer areas at field
edges and making the best use of nutrients in animal manures.
</TEXT>
