<DOCNO>GH950830-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rise and rise of supportive superwoman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YVE Newbold has one of the highest profiles of any British
businesswoman. She was visible at the top of Hanson when it was less
common to have women in senior positions in major companies, writes
NICOLA REEVES.
As such she is one of the great and good turned to when a woman is
needed to make up the numbers on various panels. She was a member of the
Royal Commission on Criminal Justice. An accomplished public speaker,
she has appeared several times on the BBC's Question Time.
In addition to her work at Hanson, she is a non-executive director of
BT and Coutts Bank and a governor of the London Business School.
She began her career as a lawyer at IBM UK and moved on to Rank Xerox
and Walt Disney.
She has all the trappings of corporate success. She is reputed to earn
#200,000 a year, drives a red Jaguar XJS and owns a house in London's
exclusive Regent's Park.
Despite her success, she does not take herself too seriously and is
supportive of other women who are trying to climb the corporate ladder
elsewhere. She is a member of womens' networks such as Forum and hosts a
monthly breakfast meeting at the Ritz for other senior businesswomen.
Women are very thin on the ground when it comes to directorships of
public organisations but Ms Newbold said that while she was in favour of
more women in the boardroom, they have ''got to earn their spurs''. She
thinks there are still too few women with experience and understanding
of how public companies work.
It is not just more women that she would like to see contributing to
the decision-making of some of our big public organisations, but ''more
of a representation of modern industrial Britain'', that is a wide range
of people of both sexes, all ages and colours.
The younger of two sisters, Yvette Monica Newbold was born in
Southport, Lancashire, on July 6, 1940. After her Belgian father left,
her Irish mother moved the family down to London where she worked on a
magazine. The girls were sent to convent school first in Wales and then
in Brighton.
She differs from many other high powered businesswomen in being
married with children -- three sons and a daughter. She met her husband
at London University where they were both reading law. She had her first
baby at 18 and is particularly close to her daughter, a barrister in the
City. By the age of 27, when she and her husband had both qualified as
solicitors, there were four children.
Her busy life leaves little time for hobbies but she enjoys
fell-walking, jogging and more recently swimming.
Many women find it very difficult to combine raising a family and a
busy professional life. Indeed, Ms Newbold thinks that today's young
women may have got it wrong. Rather than wait until they have
established careers and good salaries, she believes they should get
their child-bearing over as early as possible, then forge ahead with
their career. She herself appears to be an example of that rare breed,
Shirley Conran's superwoman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
