<HEADLINE>Midnight Sun shines on Younger &amp; Melrose</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FINLAND, which once provided a quarter of Scotland's butter, is set to
elbow its way back into the market after a 20-year absence.
Younger &amp; Melrose, a Glasgow-based distributor of dairy produce, has
signed an agreement to become sole UK distributor of Finland's Midnight
Sun butter, which has not been seen on British supermarket shelves since
the seventies.
Younger &amp; Melrose began importing Finnish butter before the Second
World War and shipments peaked at 25,000 tonnes per year in the early
fifties.
But these imports petered out soon after Britain joined the European
Community in 1973. Neutral Finland, under pressure from the Soviet
Union, stayed out and suffered new tariff barriers on its dairy exports.
The end of the Cold War removed any external constraint on Finland
joining the European Union and last year, even before Finns voted in a
referendum to join the EU, Younger &amp; Melrose got a call from Valio
International, its old supplier in Helsinki, suggesting they resume
business.
Peter Davie, a partner in Younger &amp; Melrose, is proud that his small
family-owned firm beat competition from at least three English companies
to gain Midnight Sun distribution rights for the UK as a whole.
''We are certainly looking for 5% of the UK market within three
years,'' Mr Davie said, adding that sales should build up to 5000 tonnes
a year quite quickly. That would give Younger &amp; Melrose a #20m stake in
Britain's flourishing #400m per year butter market.
</TEXT>
