<DOCNO>GH950830-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>3i takes stake in Sanmex</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633994</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT capital group 3i has taken a seven-figure equity stake in
the award-winning Sanmex International, which is heading for a
stock-market listing.
The presence of an institutional investor with a significant minority
shareholding should ease the proposed flotation of the toiletry and
household products group.
Sanmex, which lifted The Herald and accountancy firm Ernst &amp; Young's
coveted TrailBlazers award this year, is most likely to opt for the
Alternative Investment Market, the Stock Exchange's recently-launched
market for smaller and growing companies.
It could move on to AIM with a market capitalisation of about #20m.
Depending on the rapidly-expanding company's capital requirements, the
flotation could take place as early as next year.
Alternatively Sanmex may float in 1997, on the back of next year's
results.
Before the investment by 3i, Sanmex, based in Rutherglen, Glasgow, was
100%-owned by the Groden family.
Roy McKelvie, senior investment controller at 3i's Glasgow office, has
been talking to Sanmex for more than two years.
He said: ''It is useful for Sanmex to have a shareholder with deep
pockets which can help to fund its growth.
''A family business which already has an institutional shareholder
will be viewed more positively by the market when we do eventually float
the company.''
Sanmex, which grew in the 1930s providing janitorial supplies to
Glasgow's cinemas and hospitals, was in something of a rut five years
ago.
Its traditional markets were in decline but, unlike some other family
companies, it took radical action to ensure it did not end up as
takeover fodder or, even worse, in the hands of the receiver.
Between 1990 and 1993, Sanmex, which now sells washing-up liquids,
fabric softeners, disinfectants, multi-surface cleaners, and aerosol
toiletry and household products to Tesco, Morrisons and Superdrug,
doubled its turnover to #11.2m.
With an insurance claim having resulted from the loss of one month's
production after December's flooding, the 1994 sales figure is as yet
incomplete.
However, turnover is expected to top #14m this year and approach #18m
next year.
Sales director Norman Ferguson is looking to attract more business as
a result of Kwik Save's expansion north of the Border. The deep-discount
group, which recently acquired Shoprite's Scottish stores, is already a
major customer.
About 180 people are currently employed by Sanmex, which should take
its workforce through the 200-mark during the next few months as it
increases aerosol production.
Sanmex, which manufactures both supermarket own-label and its
proprietary Charm and Dispel brands, exports to between 25 and 30
countries.
Its fly sprays are much in demand in China, while, in the Middle East,
kaftan-wearers find relief in Sanmex's de-static product. Eastern Europe
is a growing market for the company, which also sells to the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Newbold leaves Hanson for Pro-Ned</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633995</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YVE Newbold, the high profile company secretary of Hanson, is leaving
at the end of September after nine years, to become chief executive of
Pro-Ned. This is the headhunting organisation which specialises in
finding non-executive directors for public companies. Lord Hanson,
chairman of Hanson, said: ''We are very sorry to lose Yve, but wish her
well in her challenging new role.''
Pro-Ned, founded in 1982, has played a major role in improving the way
in which companies are governed. It was set up by the Bank of England
and has developed from a mainly campaigning role into an employment
agency. In January last year it was sold to a joint venture made up of
the Swiss recruitment firm Egon Zehnder International and its own
management.
The number of companies with non-executive directors has increased
dramatically since Pro-Ned's inception. Ms Newbold, who said she was
''excited'' by the challenge of her new job, feels there is still much
to be done to ensure that the right sort of people get on to boards.
''It can't be the chairman's cousin any more,'' she said. She believes
the calibre of boards is all the more important given the increased
liability and responsibilities which they now face following
investigations by the Greenbury and Cadbury Committees.
Given her successful career to date and comfortable life, 55-year-old
Ms Newbold could have been expected to be considering retirement. Far
from it, this year she felt it was time to seek new challenges and
wanted to be ''more in charge of something of my own, however small''.
She is succeeded at Hanson by Jonathan Azis, a solicitor who has been
with the company as a tax manager since 1992. Ms Newbold's resignation
comes just days after the death of Lord White, the 72-year-old
co-founder of the Anglo-US industrial conglomerate whose UK interests
include Imperial Tobacco, the ARC aggregates business and Seven Seas
Vitamins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strong mark threatens Germany's recovery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976633996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bonn, Tuesday -- The strength of the mark and high wage deals earlier
in the year could choke off recovery in the German economy, the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development said today.
''The main risk (to our forecast), operative from the second half of
this year, is that the double blow of exchange rate appreciation and
high wage settlements could undermine competitiveness, profitability and
business confidence to a greater degree than expected,'' the Paris-based
think-tank for wealthy nations said in its annual report on Germany.
The 25-nation OECD has predicted that Europe's powerhouse economy
would grow by 2.9% this year and 2.7% next.
''In contrast a reversal of the recent exchange rate appreciation
could imply stronger activity, linked to better prospects for exports
and enhanced investor confidence, but in this case inflation would tend
to be higher,'' the report said.
Inflation would stay around 2% but it said unemployment would not
decline significantly in western Germany. ''Recent adverse
competitiveness shifts are likely to maintain the impetus towards
rationalisation in manufacturing,'' it added.
A further risk to the forecast is that people might save more than
they are at present and, therefore, spend less.
It predicted the main factors that had driven the recovery until now
-- housing and exports -- might slow in the second half, but business
investment would take over.
Eastern Germany would remain the fastest growing region in Europe, it
said, aided by double-digit growth in investment. -- Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
