<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>English rugby set for taste of Scottish courage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976633998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S all change in the world of rugby football as money not so much
talks but screams at the top of its voice. One piece of sponsorship
which we hope will continue for many years is the deal with Courage, the
brewers, and the English club championship.
Courage have, of course, been taken over by Scottish and Newcastle
Brewers. The resulting merged beer-making outfit is to be called
Scottish Courage.
Which means that, all going well, England's premier rugby tournament
will be called the Scottish Courage Club Championship.
Chalk and cheese
REMEMBER the old People's Labour Party? How it was run by politicans
who had come out of the shipyards, the coal mines, the odd lawyers'
office, or even a classroom?
How different is Tony Blair's New Improved Labour, as epitomised by
one Suzanne L'Estrange of Battersea Constituency Labour Party in London.
Ms L'Estrange is standing for election to the party's national
executive. She is described as a ''recent recruit'' to Labour and has
lived in London for 25 years apart from a brief period ''working as a
goatherd and cheesemaker in France''.
Presumably she is a member still in good standing of the Amalgamated
Union of Goatherders and Cheesemakers.
Beat retreat?
LABOUR'S troubles with geography continue. Our man in Westminster was
summoned by the Opposition to be given ''details of Government plans to
centralise further the control of Britain's police forces''.
It turned out to be not about Britain at all, but merely about England
and Wales. A common mistake among southerners you say -- except that the
senior Labour person chairing the news conference was none other than
Jack Straw, who has been ordered by Tony Blair to redraft the party's
devolution plans.
Those of you hanging about in expectation of a Labour U-turn on
devolution take note.
Sole beneficiary
DEPT of We Know What They Meant. A sign in the Ingram Street office of
a well-known law firm urges clients to get their affairs in order as you
never know the minute. ''Making a will?'' it reads. ''Leave everything
to Ross Harper.''
And there's more
THAT lovable London duo, the Jamesons, who have brought their skills
north of the Border to broadcast to the nation on Radio 2 of a late
evening, have been dipping into the Edinburgh Festival. Ellen, Mrs
Jameson, took quite a strict line during an interview with dancer Mark
Morris.
How, she asked, could he square the athleticism of his artistic form
with smoking and drinking? Mr Morris said he could see no contradiction.
Mrs Jameson pursued the point at which Mr Morris declared that not
only did he drink and smoke but also he was ''a sodomite''. And he
didn't see how it affected his art. This information seemed to bring
that aspect of the conversation to an end.
Sick story
SEE Strathaven? See showbiz. We read in the Echoes, the weekly journal
which carries all the news fit to print in the aforementioned douce
Lanarkshire burgh, the life story of one Stevie Starr.
His tale is headed ''Brought up in Strathaven'' and begins: ''Famous
professional regurgitator Stevie Starr was brought up from the age of
four months at local children's home Glenavon, however his Strathaven
connections do not stop there.
''Previously known as Stevie Wright, the young boy was swallowing
money by the age of six, much to his friends' horror and excitement. He
then progressed to bumble bees and Cadbury creme eggs.
''Nancy and Bessie, elderly twins who previously worked in the
children's home, recall vividly how Stevie swallowed razor blades and
regurgitated them later . . . Stevie was working in McIvor's butcher
shop, Barn Street. Staff there remember how Stevie used to drink a whole
bottle of lemonade in one gulp.''
A local hotelier, spotting Stevie's talent, bought him a set of stage
clothes and entered him in a talent competition. The rest, as they say,
is history.
Prey on his mind
AN apocryphal story, we hope, from a police court somewhere in the
Highlands where the chap in the dock has been caught red-handed shooting
a capercaillie and then having it for his tea. The magistrate duly
imposes a hefty fine for this transgression of the laws on protected
species and, before sending the miscreant on his way, summons him to the
Bench.
''Tell me,'' says the magistrate, ''what does a capercaillie taste
like?'' ''Well, your honour,'' he replies, ''It's better than the osprey
but not as good as the golden eagle.''
A few regrets
WE asked you some time ago to suggest suitable Japanese Prime
Minister-style apologies. We apologise for taking so long to announce
the winner.
Murray Macmillan of Bridge of Allan wins the whisky for his suggestion
that Bonnie Prince Charlie should apologise for not carrying on to
London -- and tearing down the goalposts at Wembley and lying blootered
in a fountain in Trafalgar Square.
</TEXT>
