<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stones from the glass house of political apathy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE lady doth protest too much. That could have been my slogan for the
eighties. If there was something you could get ants in your pants about,
from Nelson Mandela being banged up to massive cuts in the stationery
budget of the university's publications department, I'd be rustling up
placards and womaning (I was that rad a fem) the barricades before you
could say ''Maggie! Maggie! Maggie! Out! Out! Out!'' Which we did, quite
loudly at the drop of an authentic Russian Army hat.
I was reminiscing fondly about the good old days last night and
bonding with a new-found friend by sharing a few choruses of the Maggie
chant, to the mild bemusement of those around us who clearly thought we
were trapped in a time warp. Their bemusement was only mild because it
is, after all, Festival Edinburgh and anything goes; we might have been
rehearsing a scene from an agit-prop biting satire on student
radicalism.
A radical approach has been sadly lacking among the few protesters who
have been popping up during the Fringe, lobbying against all things
French and shunning the Perrier awards. They've managed to make me feel
guilty about munching on a Golden Delicious -- and, tsk, me being such a
health-conscious chick that's a big sacrifice -- but their pallid
protests haven't exactly encouraged me to show solidarity and boost
their numbers.
While their professional comrades in Greenpeace have been displaying a
dazzling gung-ho activism, buzzing the French fleet in helicopters and
sailing perilously close to full-scale naval battle, the Edinburgh
entourage are contenting themselves with the politest of objections.
Each morning on my way to the Herald empire in the capital I pass the
group patiently picketing the French Institute and marvel at how wrong
they've got it. For a start they look all shiny and clean when it's a
well-known fact that protesters should favour a grungey fashion
statement, with unkempt garments and matted locks, a look which clearly
announces ''I'm so committed to my cause I don't even have time to go to
the bathroom, let alone iron my togs.'' The people who dwell in trees
who get ratty about motorways have this one sussed, while hunt saboteurs
have it well nigh perfected, obviously holding Arrid Extra Dry in the
same contempt as hunters.
Holding prettily inscribed placards the anti-nuke crowd circle the
Institute with a careful precision which could have been choreographed,
instead of surging around in the tried and tested tradition of the angry
mob. They're even quite quiet, which is simply unforgivable, but worse,
much worse, they're smiling.
This is simply unacceptable behaviour. They nod in a friendly fashion
as I scurry past them when they should clearly be screaming insults in
my wake --''Capitalist, reactionary, militarist bitch -- I hope you
choke on your Golden Delicious.'' They're so un-intimidating it makes me
sick, although I do live in terror, oh horror of horrors, that they will
wish me a nice day.
Where's the fun in being nice to people? What's the point in that? The
biggest kick I ever got out of marching up and down the country in the
eighties was the sheer unadulterated pleasure of turning on interested
bystanders and screaming, to their bewilderment, ''Don't Spectate!
Demonstrate!'' in a snarling froth of righteous fury.
I watched, with weary disdain, someone attempting, and failing
miserably, to get his point across last week. The Hill Street Theatre
cafe had been commandeered, with typical arrogance, by a television crew
doing an ad hoc interview with a member of the Perrier judging panel.
While they filmed the famous-for-15-minutes judgette wittering on
about all the jolly funny people she had been privileged to see, a young
man hovered in the background. I assumed he was trying to tell them
their cappuccinos had arrived. The interview concluded, he dashed up to
the slick trendy female presenter. ''Can I just say a few words about
nuclear testing?'' he asked in chorister tones. ''No you can't,'' she
snapped, strutting off in killer stilettos. ''Oh, OK. Sorry,'' he noted.
And smiled.
I wanted to shake him like a rag doll. What a missed opportunity.
Dykes can rampage through the News at Ten studios and storm Parliament
and he didn't even have the balls to interrupt a silly little satellite
show? Where are the anti-nuke lot recruited from these days?
Flower-arranging classes?
Mind you, I shouldn't throw stones when I live in such a glass house
of political apathy. My protest days are over.
I SUSPECT that I had simply liked the tunes, and the putative Baroness
was such a formidable foe, allowing me to vent childhood fears,
embodying as she did such classic villainous qualities, a milksnatcher
who was as terrifying as the Child-Catcher in Chitty Chitty Bang Bang,
who made as many poisonous promises as the evil queen in Snow White.
I had more time on my hands then and marches and campaigns were a
perfect outlet for resentments and aggressions stored up through
adolescence. Now I reserve my passion for other pursuits and confine my
political outrage to half-hearted tuts and mutters over the morning
papers.
These days the only time I shake off my Scottish reserve and shyness
and give vent to rising ire is when some dork eats crisps or sweeties in
the theatre. Sad, really.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
