<DOCNO>GH950830-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Actor faces driving ban</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CORONATION Street actor Simon Gregson -- who plays tearaway Steve
McDonald -- was ordered to attend a court after magistrates found him
guilty yesterday of driving a BMW at 70mph in a 40mph zone.
Magistrates at Stockport, Greater Manchester, issued a bail warrant to
ensure that the actor appears in court on a future date after finding
him guilty in his absence of speeding, driving without insurance, and
not having an MoT test certificate.
Mrs Mary Stewart, chairman of the magistrates, ordered that Gregson,
charged in his real name of Simon Alan Gregory, should attend court
after being told that he already had six points on his licence for
driving without insurance last year, and now faced disqualification
under the totting-up procedure.
Mr Barrie Darby, prosecuting, said Gregson, of Thornton Road, Heald
Green, Stockport, was clocked driving a BMW 525i at 70.6mph in a 40mph
zone in Cheadle, Stockport, at 11.14am on January 16.
Traffic was light at the time and he had overtaken three vehicles.
When cautioned, the actor told police: ''No reply.''
He subsequently failed to produce his insurance, MoT documents, and
driving licence at a police station.
Mr Darby said Gregson had been told of yesterday's hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger over grant for sewage system</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ''SELF-SUFFICIENT'' community in Morayshire was criticised yesterday
for using taxpayers' money to build a sewage works for its
''economically sustainable village''.
A local resident has hit out at the Findhorn Foundation, near Forres,
after it secured an #80,000 grant from the European Union to build a
US-style organic sewage system.
The community itself raised half of the system's #160,000 cost.
However, a former Fleet Air Arm officer, who has retired to Findhorn and
whose house overlooks the foundation's premises, says it should have
paid for the lot.
Sir Michael Joughin, of Ederslie, Findhorn, a former chairman of
Scottish Hydro Electric, said: ''How can they say they are economically
self-sufficient if they are going to Europe with a begging bowl?''
He added: ''The foundation could not run their activities without the
relief from UK taxes given by their charitable status.''
He continued: ''There is also the social security system, which allows
their 'wider community' to return to this area and add to Forres's
mysteriously high unemployment figures. It is a joke to say they have an
economically sustainable village.''
However, Mr Glenn Walters, the foundation's American-born spokesman,
replied: ''We are not a net drain on the community. We spend around
#800,000 per year on essential services and none of our members is
allowed to draw the dole.''
He added: ''The sewage works we have received money for is extremely
innovative and could point the way forward for others.''
Local people fear the community may be interested in extending its
stake in the local housing market, which some say is already as much as
10%.
However, Mr Walters said: ''We have no plans to take over the
village.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Patrick brogan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was plenty of security in the parliament building in Tiflis,
capital of Georgia, when I was there last month. The place was the scene
of hectic political activity as parliament voted on a new constitution,
and men with droopy moustaches and machine guns hung around in every
corner, to protect the government against rebels, rivals, and the mafia.
So they used a car bomb. First reports from Tiflis suggest that the
President, Edward Shevardnadze, is lucky to have survived.
Parliament now operates out of the former Communist Party
headquarters. Parliament itself was demolished in a civil war in 1991,
when the first democratically elected President of Georgia, Zviad
Gamsakhourdia, retreated to a bunker under the building and defied his
enemies. They shelled the place with tanks and mortars, destroying it
and several neighbouring buildings.
The war was provoked by Gamsakhourdia's raving xenophobia and
paranoia. He incited the Georgians to purge their country of foreign
elements. Since that meant over one-third of the population, there was
of course an immediate uprising against him.
The Ossetians in north Georgia drove out the Georgians, and then the
Abkhazians on the Black Sea coast started their own ethnic cleansing.
The Georgians, much to their credit, turned against the man who had let
the genie out of the bottle. He eventually escaped from the parliament
building and took to the hills. He was killed a year later.
Yesterday's attack on President Shevardnadze could have been the work
of ''Zviadists'' seeking revenge. There is still the running threat of
civil war from the ultra-nationalists.
Shevardnadze is immensely popular: when he threatened to resign last
year the streets in front of his office were blocked by huge crowds
demanding he reconsider.
All the same, there is still bitter opposition. Shevardnadze cut a
deal with the Russians earlier this year under which Georgia rejoined
the Confederation of Independent States and guaranteed the Russians a
20-year lease on their bases.
Alternatively, the attack could have been the work of a disgruntled
minority. The Abkhazians have driven out 250,000 Georgians. They
naturally fear that the Georgian army will seek to recover its lost
territory. Killing Shevardnadze might postpone that evil event.
But the President himself first accused the mafia, the hoodlums who
nearly wrecked the country in the aftermath of the insurrection that
overthrew Gamsakhourdia, so they are the prime suspects.
Shevardnadze returned to Tiflis from Moscow after Gamsakhourdia was
driven from office. He stepped into the vacuum and was made President.
He was Georgia's most celebrated citizen, the only one known outside the
Caucuses.
He has been Gorbachev's Foreign Minister in Moscow during perestroika.
He resigned at Christmas, 1990, claiming that Gorbachev's enemies were
planning a coup.
The coup duly took place, in August, 1991, leading to the
disintegration of the Soviet Union -- and the independence of Georgia.
For the first year he was home he controlled nothing much beyond his
own office. The mafia, calling themselves the ''Mkhedrioni'', meaning
the Horsemen, modelling themselves on the Cossacks, seized everything
else. Georgia, for several months, hovered on the brink of total
dissolution, before Shevardnadze at last brought some measure of order
to the country -- with Russian help.
He also cut a deal with leaders of the mafia, allowing them to convert
to legitimate business. Some of them, no doubt, felt left out.
I was in Georgia to address a seminar on the press. It is a country
more than half free, but still burdened by the legacy of Bolshevism.
There is not much toleration for opposition, and all too many Georgians
still believe that disputes are best settled with the gun, or the bomb.
Shevardnadze himself has all the democratic credentials. He encouraged
a free press in Moscow, much more convincingly than Gorbachev, and
rallied to the defence of parliament when the tanks were sent against it
four years ago. He was with Yeltsin on that occasion, a choice that
served him well later.
All the same, being nearly blown up can change a man's view of things
considerably. There are elections scheduled for next November. The real
test of Shevardnadze's democratic instincts, and Georgia's, is whether
they go forward, and if the opposition is allowed to contest them,
despite the attack of the Horsemen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saddam 'planned to test atomic bomb'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE PAGANI</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ViennaTHE Iraqi regime plotted to use nuclear fuel from two research
reactors as a short-cut to an atomic bomb and planned to test it by
dropping it on an enemy, a UN nuclear chief said today.
The Vienna-based International Atomic Energy Agency said the Iraqis
were only stopped by Allied air raids during the Gulf war.
Professor Maurizio Zifferero said details provided by Saddam Hussein's
Government this month came as a surprise.
''We believed before that the Iraqis were years away from obtaining
sufficient weapons-grade uranium,'' he said.
''What happened in Baghdad was that they admitted to having tried a
short-cut. It was a very well-guarded secret.''
The Iraqis told Prof Zifferero that a crash programme to build a
nuclear device began in September, 1990, a month after Saddam sent his
troops storming into Kuwait. The aim was to extract enriched uranium
from two research reactors, one of French design, the other Soviet.
''The fuel elements contained a sufficient amount of highly enriched
uranium for at least one nuclear device,'' he said.
Baghdad reckoned it could extract at least 22lbs of uranium from each
reactor.
Prof Zifferero also learned that the Iraqis had thought about testing
their planned device either through an underground explosion or by using
it as a weapon against an enemy.
''They were not sure what the final experiment would be, whether in
the form of a test, such as an underground test, or an actual deployment
in the field,'' he said.
''They were considering both.''
Prof Zifferero led an IAEA team in Baghdad from August 17 to 20 to
receive fresh information on Iraq's schemes to develop weapons of mass
destruction.
The crash atom bomb programme would have cut the time needed for
Baghdad to manufacture a device. But Prof Zifferero said it had yet to
overcome huge technical challenges to turn the fuel into an ingredient
suitable for a bomb.
Some progress had been made, however, as the Iraqis had already set up
a centrifuge enrichment programme at their engineering design centre at
Rashdiya, north of Baghdad. Research work on building a nuclear weapon
was also being carried out at Al Atheer and Tuwaitha.
''This all came to a halt in the second half of January, 1991, because
of the damage inflicted at the installations by the coalition bombing
raids,'' Prof Zifferero said.
The ''short-cut'' programme had been ordered by Hussein Kamel Hassam,
a son-in-law of President Saddam Hussein, who defected to Jordan on
August 7. He confirmed the details of the crash programme when Prof
Zifferero spoke to him in the Jordanian capital.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
