<TEXT>
I AM sorry that W J O'Hagan did not read my letter properly before
replying to it (August 25). I would reiterate that I have nothing
against single parents who find themselves in that situation through no
fault of their own.
Secondly, in the case that he outlines, does he not think that the
fiance has an obligation to the child? Where is he now? Why must the
taxpayer, who has no choice in the matter, be left to pick up the tab?
Thirdly, I have never asserted that ''only the well-off should have
the right to have children''. If that were the case, I would never have
been born. I believe it is up to individual couples to decide when it is
right for them to have children. Can they afford the time, the energy,
the patience, and yes, the money?
Matthew Smith,
67 Dorset Street,Glasgow.
</TEXT>
