<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lecturers rule out strike over job cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN, EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LECTURERS have voted against taking strike action in support of three
colleagues made redundant by a further education college.
The Educational Institute of Scotland, which represents eight out of
10 FE college lecturers, said it was disappointed to have lost the vote
among its members at Jewel and Esk Valley College in Dalkeith.
Only 45% of EIS members took part in the ballot, with 33 voting
against taking action, and 20 in favour of supporting those who have
lost their jobs.
Mr Jack Dale, the union's further and higher education secretary, said
the outcome was especially disappointing for the three unpromoted
lecturers.
Mr Dale said: ''I am sure that the very low poll reflects the extent
to which members in the college feel vulnerable in the face of a
management which, backed by legislation which has stripped employees of
their protection rights, has refused to negotiate with branch leaders.''
The union remained opposed to managements using compulsory
redundancies and would pursue unfair dismissal claims on behalf of the
three, he said.
The EIS had argued that there was no need for the college to make
compulsory redundancies after it had achieved more than 20 job losses by
voluntary means.
The college sought to reduce its staff costs after experiencing a
shortfall of almost #650,000 in its budget.
Some lecturers at other colleges which have had their funding cut have
volunteered to go early, although disputes are also looming where
compulsory redundancies have been sought.
There will be further staff cuts in the sector as colleges, which are
now free-standing institutions run by boards of management, adjust to a
new system of formula funding from the Scottish Office.
No-one was available for comment yesterday at Jewel and Esk College.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
