<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Board chiefs seek more funding</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH tourism chiefs made an appeal for more funds yesterday to
build on the best early season figures for the last five years.
However, the tourist industry will need to find its own financing for
marketing and the new area tourist boards over the next few years.
Buoyed by the latest figures, the Scottish Tourist Board said
yesterday that a ''considerable'' amount of money would be needed to
continue the momentum.
The figures for UK tourism to Scotland from January to May 1995 show a
16% increase in bed nights, an 18% rise in trips, and a 14% increase in
turnover compared to the same period last year.
STB chief executive Mr Derek Reid said: ''It does seem that our
marketing message is hitting its target but what we must aim for is
long-term growth and not the boom-and-bust cycle which has characterised
our industry's performance in recent years.
''1995 may prove to be the year we set that pattern in motion.''
Representatives of the tourist industry from throughout Scotland met
in Pitlochry yesterday to hear of the work the board carried out last
year and its plans for the future.
But, despite an enthusistic response from delegates, Mr Reid stressed
that millions of pounds were still needed.
An extra #3m alone would be required if television advertising at the
level seen in the Granada area was carried out throughout England.
Mr Reid said: ''Funds by themselves are not the solution. You've got
to have the correct focused marketing. We need to present Scotland on
its strengths.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fraud team to question Leeson</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Frankfurt
FRAUD investigators arrived in Germany today to see jailed Barings
Bank trader Nick Leeson, the man blamed for the collapse of the
London-based bank.
The Serious Fraud Office said one of its officers and two policemen
probing the bank's collapse last February were in Frankfurt.
They are expected to see 28-year-old Leeson for the first time
tomorrow at the Frankfurt prison where he has been held since his arrest
at the city's airport on March 2.
He will speak to the investigators ''under caution,'' meaning he has
been warned that anything said by him can be used in a British criminal
trial.
Leeson has been waging a high-profile campaign to be sent to Britain
to face justice rather than be extradited to Singapore, where he says he
fears an unfair trial and long prison term.
But the SFO has said it is under no obligation to apply for his
extradition and will only do so if Singapore's request is rejected.
A Frankfurt court is expected to issue a final ruling early next month
on whether to send Leeson to Singapore to face trial on 12 charges of
forgery and cheating.
A German prosecutor handling the case, Hans-Hermann Eckert, has said
he does not expect the Singapore request to be rejected and that Leeson
could be on his way as soon as late October.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adopting the wrong attitude</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS ONE who was a mere child, the oldest of three, when his parents
divorced, I find the one-dimensional views of Kirsty Scott offensively
ignorant and unhelpful in establishing a rational debate (August ).
We live in a complex society in which most of us have had to lower our
aspirations as the comparatively affluent UK continues to drop down the
world's economic pecking order. Economists of every political viewpoint
agree that the cost of social services is a major public-spending
millstone around the country's neck, though they differ considerably on
the best solutions.
A few percentage points' swing, either way, can make an awful lot of
difference in these circumstances, down to the size of the district
housing queue.
It is a fact that single mothers, among others, are given priority in
matters of housing. I have young family friends who were advised by
social services not to legalise their offspring, despite the threat of
an in-law fatwa, until a council flat was obtained, and I have witnessed
the same advice given to others in social service offices.
In those areas where the housing list is booked solid for the next
decade or so, priority status for anyone obviously becomes meaningless,
a particularly galling situation for married folk condemned to a
lifetime of over-priced rented accommodation when so much of public
housing in their area is taken up by single-parent families.
I know of several mainly working-class communities across the UK,
including at least one in Glasgow, where teenage girls get themselves
pregnant for this very reason, with no intention of marrying or living
with their far-too-immature, loutish boyfriends.
A decade ago, a fast-track social services administrator admitted to
me the system had encouraged her to deliberately get pregnant by a
toyboy, whom she promptly threw out on missing her next period so her
friend could return swiftly to her bed.
All these things happen, they are not just Tory tales, and it doesn't
require many of them to throw a poorly thought-through system badly out
of kilter.
Out-of-wedlock teenage pregnancies do, I believe, arise from a similar
combination of social and physical interactions as with any other sort
of pregnancies. The real question is, what was a supposedly decent girl
of 15 with a broad liberal education doing having sexual intercourse
with a 16-year-old boyfriend, and without either taking the necessary
precautions?
If she did mature into responsible adulthood, probably with loving
family support and her child/children healthy and well-adjusted, she is
in a tiny blessed minority.
What John Redwood proposed was not a catch-all adoption policy for
every teen offspring but for the mechanisms to be in place to realise
the timely adoptions of babies where the too-young, isolated mothers are
unable to cope; they are a far larger group!
I am sure there are those who would wish to turn the clock back 40
years or more and whip unmarried teen mothers into solitary confinement.
A civilised society should make reasonable allowances for human errors
of judgment but not bend over backwards into the sort of schemes which
encourage the behaviour they are supposed to alleviate.
Possible solutions lie as much in indirect approaches as in direct
support. Unmarried and single parents share problems in being inhibited
from acquiring employment which would cause them to lose income with
respect to family support.
Policies which are too directed to the poorest creates the deepest
poverty traps and discourage employment. Thus recent attempts to reduce
those on benefit have actually increased the number of recipients.
Tapering working families gradually from benefit into employment
should accelerate their complete removal from state support.
Encouraging successful firms and some unions to appreciate the follies
of over-slimmed, not always underpaid, workforces is another component
in a complex equation.
Families forced to live on benefit for years do suffer genuine
deprivation. But the extent of some benefits, such as comprehensive
household fittings and fixtures, are more than working families can
afford. There should be greater solidity and quality to public housing
and fewer trappings.
Those who have come up in the world should expect to move into more
comfortable and spacious private homes, releasing basic public housing
for the genuinely poor.
Many would be persuaded more easily if such a transfer kept them in
their own neighbourhood. Except that local authorities of old had the
knack of concreting whole wards with public schemes which they
maintained miserably. Breaking them up conceptually or with dynamite is
very necessary.
True progress is achievable with open debate, not posturing mind-sets
and attitudes.
Robert D.M. Graham,
7 Ardoch Gardens,
Cambuslang.
</TEXT>
