<HEADLINE>Partick Thistle take-over</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634015</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the fans-with-typewriters stakes Ken Smith's coverage (August 29)
of the proposed Partick Thistle take-over wins the brown-nose award. It
is nearly as difficult to count the inaccuracies and the unverified
statements from Jim Oliver as it is to trace the money the chairman
claims to have put into the club.
George Galloway and I have never publicly identified the members of
the consortium. This was on their wishes, presumably because they feared
the kind of odious remarks Mr Oliver has come out with.
Charan Gill has, however, identified himself so it is fair to comment
on his part in this. Your article claims that his involvement was
''based only on a short phone call'' with Mr Galloway. This would be
incredible if it wasn't just plain laughable.
Indeed, a Herald journalist and photographer joined me, Mr Galloway,
Imran Muneer, and Mr Gill for lunch at the Ashoka resturant in Ashton
Lane, Glasgow, photographed the meeting, and reported on it!
Further, Mr Oliver is quoted as asserting that no businessman
contacted him about any offer. Explain then the formal fax and letter
sent to him on Monday morning from a respected business consultant --
more than three hours before our press conference -- which not only
intimated the interest of three businessmen, one of whom was Mr Gill,
but also carried the name of his accountant.
The Herald goes on to say that prior to the press conference Mr Gill
told George Galloway that he was pulling out of the bid. I have checked
this with Mr Galloway -- unlike your reporter -- who says that this is
totally untrue.
Charan Gill did phone him late in the morning and in the brief
conversation said only that he was holding a meeting later in the day
with eight prominent businessmen who were interested in taking over the
club. I understand that this meeting subsequently took place at the
offices of Pannell Kerr Forster.
Mr Oliver's remarks on the premium-rate ''Jagsline'' and subsequently
to BBC Scotland are repugnant to me and to all Thistle fans. Sadly he
still clearly fails to appreciate the import of what he has said. His
record at Firhill, however, speaks for itself.
To take just the issue of the ''new #2.5m stand'' (#2.3m actually!)
which he looks across to from his office. It must, indeed, give him
immense pleasure that, like Yossarian and the officers' club in
Catch-22, he had almost nothing financially to do with it.
As the club's accounts show, #1.7m was contributed from public funds,
another #300,000 from the fans, with the balance presumably met from the
sale of a string of players last year including Gerry Britton, George
Shaw and Craig Nelson.
Under Mr Oliver's stewardship players have consistently been sold to
balance the books and none purchased. This is a matter of record and
blindingly apparent to any fan. And on this issue of supporters, I not
that I have ''now'' become one.
In which case I suppose I'd better throw out all my pathetic
memorabilia -- like the cotton hooped shirt and the shiny one with the
Watson Towers sponsors' logo, both of which substantially pre-date Jim
Oliver's involvement at Firhill -- and start to learn the names of the
present team.
Will Mr Oliver put any money into the side? I think not. Will he be
around to steer the club towards its annual flirt with relegation? I
hope not.
Ron McKay,
Little Mosside Farm
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
