<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh predicts record year for tourism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH is set to have a record year for tourism, it was predicted
by the industry yesterday.
Hotel room occupancy rates for the first six months of the year show a
rise of 5% over the corresponding period last year to an average 69%.
With several major events having taken place in July and this month,
including the Tall Ships Race, the Open Golf Championship, and
apparently record-breaking Edinburgh Festival, figures for the second
half of the year look likely to ensure a record 12 months.
Mr Alan Clarke, Edinburgh Tourist Board's director of marketing, said
that hotel occupancy in May reached a record 83%, up 7% on May last
year.
''Edinburgh appears to be performing better than most, if not all, our
competitor cities in England.
''Most sectors of the industry in the city are reporting growth -- not
just hotels but also guesthouses, visitor attractions, and shops.''
Mr Clarke said that next month figures would also be boosted with the
opening of the new Edinburgh International Conference Centre and later
in the year the Phantom of the Opera season at the Playhouse Theatre.
</TEXT>
