<HEADLINE>Cheap misuse of the word 'evil'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S nothing more guaranteed to wake you up over breakfast than
finding yourself described in The Herald as ''unnatural, dangerous, and
evil'' -- an experience which is unlikely ever to befall any of your
heterosexual readers (I hope), but which those of us who are gay were
treated to today, thanks -- yet again -- to John Macleod (August 29).
Where does one begin to counter this tide of abuse from him? If I and
my fellow gays who lead our lives of occasional romance, occasional
eroticism, frequent tedium, and sometimes -- the greatest experience
life has ever given me -- love for another person of our own sex, are to
be described as ''evil'', how in the world can John Macleod describe
ethnic cleansing or nuclear war? The whole currency of ethical debate is
cheapened by such misuse of the word.
John Macleod is correct when he says that many gays live with
self-loathing and that alcohol abuse, neurosis, and attempted suicide
are all more common amongst gays than in the community at large. But who
can be surprised by this when we are subjected to the kind of hostility
John Macleod expresses articulately and many people in much cruder
terms?
Gays are ordinary human beings, no weaker than anyone else, and no
stronger either. When we read that our loves are ''absolutely and in all
circumstances wrong'' some of us begin to believe it; some of us cannot
shake off the feeling that John Macleods of this world might be right,
except when in a haze of drunkenness.
I can tell him what is ''absolutely and in all circumstances wrong''
-- it is to misuse the skill of the writer to contribute to a bigotry
which so oppresses some of its victims they are driven to take their own
lives.
Graeme Woolaston,
10 Uist Cresent,
Stepps.
</TEXT>
