<HEADLINE>Scotland's religious inheritance not lost</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEVER one to tiptoe away from a topic which he believes should be
aired, John Macleod in his essay, On course for paganism, bemoans ''the
strange death of Reformation Scotland'' and the loss of ''a religious
tradition which once fired our culture''; and he asks ''what reality
remains to religious feeling in central Scotland'' (August 26).
There is no doubt that the ''Scottish Protestant dream'' was real to a
very significant proportion of the population in the sixteenth and
seventeenth centuries.
Tom Nairn referred to it in a fine essay analysing ''The Three Dreams
of Scottish Nationalism'' over 20 years ago. He concluded that the
egalitarian and humanitarian vision of the Reformers was not achieved
because they did not have the economic power, the capital, to put it
into effect.
I accept his case and thus argue that it is only fruitless nostalgia
to think of what might have been. Humanity has moved on and so has
Scotland.
One of the ways in which we have moved on is the diminution of
''religious feeling'' using Mr Macleod's phrase to mean feeling in the
practice of the Christian religion. Some words of a noted American
lecturer on psychology, Robert A Johnson, are relevant to this:
''Much of our religious heritage is a map or set of instructions for
the deepest meaning of our interior life, not a set of laws for outer
conduct. To relate to our religious teaching only in its literal
dimension is to lose its spiritual meaning.''
In other words, if genuine spiritual experience is not present in a
religious practice, such practice becomes a form of materialism. It is
like an electric bulb which has fused. I suspect that much religious
practice in this country is like that.
We have not lost our inheritance. But we cannot live in it. Of course
it informs our present, and we should be aware of it. The power of the
holy spirit which fired the Reformation is a universal power.
It is still available to those who can attune to it, whether they are
Protestants, Catholics, Muslims, Jews, Buddhists, Hindus, or none of
those, even ''pagans.''
William C Wolfe,
37 Woodside Crescent,
Kaimend,
by Carnwath.
</TEXT>
