<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>This is a party political broadcast on behalf of democracy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEX SALMOND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634023</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first -- and by far the best -- film version of The Thirty-Nine
Steps is the Hitchcock version with Robert Donat playing the lead. There
is a particularly nice moment when Richard Hannay, having sought refuge
from his pursuers on a political platform and been mistaken for the main
speaker, excuses his delay in rising after the chairman's effusive
introduction by saying that he completely failed to recognise himself
from the chairman's opening remarks!
I often have that same feeling. Among the many spectacular successes
the blurb handed out to hard-pressed chairpeople claims for me is in
once producing a party political broadcast which attracted more viewers
than Coronation Street.
This is true, if only by virtue of the fact that the offending
broadcast appeared on three channels compared with Coronation Street's
one. The broadcast was one of a series run by the SNP some 10 years ago
on a soap opera format.
If I remember correctly the plot which grabbed the attention of
viewers was called The Nightmare and concerned our hero settling down in
front of the television and dreaming of waking up after the election to
find the newsreader telling him that a re-elected Margaret Thatcher had
taken the axe to Ravenscraig. There then followed an animated political
discussion with the newsreader and a happy ending which unfortunately
was not repeated in real life.
Thanks to the ingenuity of the BBC staff in Glasgow and the
considerable acting talent of many of the then Take The High Road cast
these little political vignettes were rather successful, despite being
produced on a shoestring budget. They were part of an early attempt to
break away from the stilted format of political broadcasts which had
people immediately searching for the remote control.
Other parties have tried the same trick, albeit in different ways, and
the broadcasts are now usually totally different from the
face-to-the-camera presentations of the 50s and 60s. Kinnock the Movie
was generally regarded as something of a mini classic for Labour in 1987
while Sean Connery specials shook and stirred the political scene for
the SNP in 1992.
Recently I saw the Tories try the soap opera format and do it so badly
that I found it not altogether surprising that new research indicated
that Tory broadcasts were having a negative impact, ie, they were
persuading people not to vote Tory.
Since shooting the messenger is a longstanding political tradition it
seems that the Tory response to this disquieting statistic might be
voluntarily to pull the plug on its broadcasts. What would be sinister
would be if this were used as a lever to attempt to turn off the switch
on all the others.
PPBs, as they are known, have few friends outside the political
parties. To the broadcasters they are an annoying headache in their
schedules, particularly in Scotland where opt-out spots are often
difficult to find. An SNP broadcast was once on the receiving end of
outraged complaints from space enthusiasts because BBC2 opted out just
after midnight at the very point the space shuttle was landing!
Despite its unpopularity there is an argument that the humble PPB is
the single most important reason why corruption in UK politics is at a
lower and lesser level than across the good-old USA.
Over here the number of PPBs is set by the number of votes gained at
the last election, and during elections also by the number of
candidates. Despite the odd complaint here and there it is basically a
fair system. No-one is allowed to buy television space beyond the quota.
Over there all elections are basically determined by television
advertising, and this produces two predictable results. First, that the
message is negative because that is the most effective use of 15-second
TV spots. Secondly, that the funds required to finance such campaigns
place candidates and parties hopelessly in hock to vested interests.
The Tories spent around #20m at the last election -- much more than
the other parties combined -- and around 200 times the entire campaign
budget of the SNP. Big although this may seem, it would be a drop in the
ocean compared with what would be necessary to fund an intensive TV
advertising campaign. A dozen or more Asil Nadirs would be required to
finance such an extravaganza.
To keep up, Labour would either be forced into even more reliance on
trade union funding or Tony Blair would need to produce his own set of
millionaire supporters. Neither the Liberals nor the SNP would be able
even to attempt to compete with that level of money swilling about.
Of course PPBs don't necessarily need to stay on the present format of
four minutes forty seconds. They have already been shortened from the
previous 10 minutes, which is an eternity in modern television terms.
Conceivably the time coud be swopped for a number of 30 second slots
which would cause broadcasters and the public less inconvenience. But if
this were to be a foot in the door of paid political advertising then it
should be treated with great suspicion.
The much derided PPB is in fact one of the few remaining bulwarks
protecting genuine democratic competition in the UK. By all means reach
for the remote control, and certainly get upset at poor presentation
from the Tories, or any of the other parties for that matter. However,
like many things, we might not miss the PPB or understand its importance
until it is gone and we open the can of worms that could replace it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
