<HEADLINE>Evacuation order stays as Montserrat's volcano still threatens to erupt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634024</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Salem
A NEW vent on Montserrat's rumbling volcano belched steam and ash for
a second day today and authorities left in place a week-old evacuation
order that affects half the island's population.
Volcanic activity was ''at a level high enough for us not to be able
to talk at this moment about anybody being able to return to the hazard
zones'', according to Montserrat's Governor Frank Savage.
The new crack in the volcano in the Soufriere Hills at the south end
of this British colony has issued a constant stream of hot gases and ash
and at least seven small earthquakes were detected under the mountain
late yesterday and early today.
The southern half of Montserrat was evacuated last Wednesday when
scientists warned there was a good chance the volcano, which came to
life on July 18, would erupt.
About 6000 people left their homes -- some for other islands but most
to the north end of Montserrat, where they are staying in public
shelters or with friends and family.
Authorities were keeping a wary eye on sanitation facilities, which
were strained by the number of evacuees using them.
Governor Savage said officials were looking at plans to add toilets to
existing shelters to ease the pressure.
He said there was frustration at the length of the evacuation, which
was in its seventh day. Officials have said they would need to see
several days of decreased volcanic activity before they would consider
lifting the order.
''I think people are putting a brave face on it, but . . . they're
getting frustrated and they really are in pretty uncomfortable
conditions,'' he said.-- Reuter
</TEXT>
