<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man and machine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Gulf War brought smart weapons and the wonders of electronic
wizardry into the public domain for the first time. Popular perception
since 1991 has been that all things are possible with new technology.
Reality is another story. The death of a US airman at the start of an
old-fashioned spy mission yesterday underlines the true and continuing
human cost of any military action, even in the hi-tech nineties. It
remains a fact that in the circumstances of a limited conventional
conflict in difficult terrain there is no substitute for the age-old
''eyeball'' form of intelligence gathering with all the risks that the
process entails. Satellites are expensive and difficult to manoeuvre
into the desired orbit. Even high-resolution cameras and infra-red
detectors, the state-of-the-art technology, can be countered or fooled
by a clever opponent. Satellites are also inflexible once committed to a
particular course over the earth's surface.
The U2, on the other hand, is a veteran Cold Warrior. Though little
more than a high-powered glider, it has provided the United States and
Nato with reliable and vital close-up data on potential opponents for
more than four decades. Despite its age it has not yet reached the end
of its shelf life in an increasingly uncertain world. The Americans have
lost two remotely-piloted spy planes over Bosnia in the past two weeks.
Further flights of the top-secret Predators have been suspended to avoid
the possibility of their sensitive surveillance equipment falling into
hostile hands. The unmanned aircraft has the advantage of not putting a
pilot into harm's way. It also deprives an enemy of the chance to parade
a high-propaganda-value hostage for the world's media. Mechanical
failure or unexpectedly skilful Serb air defences appear to have removed
that piece from the board for the meantime.
That was the reason behind the decision to pinpoint Serb targets by
the proven means of the U2 overflight. A pilot can respond instantly to
changing events or priorities, as opposed to a satellite. The downside
is the danger, demonstrated so tragically in yesterday's crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Carey to visit Sudan again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Khartoum
ARCHBISHOP of Canterbury George Carey, whose trip to rebel-held areas
of southern Sudan two years ago caused a row between London and
Khartoum, is to visit Sudan in October, state radio said today.
Bishop Gabriel Roric, Minister for Foreign Affairs, announced the
visit after meeting Britain's ambassador to Khartoum, Alan Goulty, the
radio said.
Goulty's predecessor, Peter Streams, was expelled by Sudan after Dr
Carey called off a trip to Khartoum in December 1993 and visited instead
the rebel-held Christian-dominated south of the mainly Muslim country.
Britain reacted by expelling Sudan's envoy in London.
Sudanese President Lieutenant-General Omar Hassan al-Bashir had wanted
Dr Carey to be an official guest of the government but the archbishop,
said it was his practice to travel overseas only as a guest of the local
Anglican Church.
His visit to areas in southern Sudan controlled by the rebel Sudan
Peoples Liberation Army, which includes many Christians in its ranks,
infuriated the government.
The radio announcement made no mention of arrangements for Dr Carey's
visit.
Human rights groups have accused the Sudanese government of
obstructing the activities of the Christian churches and of trying to
convert southerners to Islam by force.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power politics</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE time is fast approaching when a decision will have to be made
about the possible referral to the Monopolies Commission of
ScottishPower's bid for the Anglo-Welsh regional electricity supplier,
Manweb. In fact strong rumour suggests Mr Lang will make his mind up
this week. It will be his first major decision since his translation
from the Scottish Office, but few imagine that his mind will be
determined one way or another by his personal identity or earlier
governmental role. He will, however, be under strong pressure from
Professor Littlechild, the electricity industry's regulator, to make a
referral. But then the Professor wanted to refer the Trafalgar House bid
for Northern and was turned down. That might not seem too firm a
precedent, for ScottishPower is a quite different creature from
Trafalgar, and generates as well as distributes electricity. It sells
power directly into England and might have been expected to have used
this capacity to sell through Manweb except that it has anticipated
complaint in this connection and voluntarily surrendered the option of
doing so. A specific case for referral is therefore hard to justify and
the general case seems to have been lost when Northern's fate was left
to the market (though, as it happens, Trafalgar abandoned its bid after
its first stumble).
A referral might not spell failure for ScottishPower, but it would
bring a large measure of uncertainty into the bid's future. In the
interim, while the investigation was taking place (and these do not
proceed with much dispatch), a third party could intervene. The
continental expressions of interest in the English regional electricity
companies are not simply rhetorical flourishes; and ScottishPower fears
that one of these European companies might step in to take advantage of
its groundwork without any impediment, and make a bid.
Such fears may prove groundless, but there is little doubt that a
referral would be a blow to Scottish popular morale which has been
boosted by the notion of a very large UK-wide energy company based in
Glasgow. Having privatised the utilities, it would seem perverse for the
Government to want to insulate them from the operations of the market,
unless some very much larger creations were being proposed. The present
bid should take its course, which might mean a small additional
sweetener. Only the SNP would benefit from a referral, by identifying in
it an expression of anti-Scottish sentiment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Change in China</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634028</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE really should be no need nowadays to have to notice that China
is one of the greatest civilisations or that its achievement in feeding
and clothing a fifth of mankind is immense. Spokesmen for the present
Chinese Government feel, however, that they cannot take all that for
granted but have to use it to counter justified criticisms of Government
behaviour. In fact there is no justification for China's human rights
record, which is deplorable. Amnesty International, which has drawn
attention to some recent violations, has no vested interest in seeking
to denigrate China, or in treating it any differently from other
societies which deal with their own citizens in barbaric manner. The
fact that 16 people have been executed in the past fortnight to make
Beijing safer for the UN's Fourth World Conference on Women is a fearful
commentary on the Chinese Government's mind set.
Inevitably Amnesty is being accused of interfering in China's internal
affairs. Every country is sensitive about that sort of development, and
few societies are confident enough to take such criticisms without
displaying resentment. The Chinese Government has taken a major step in
admitting Amnesty -- one of the first benefits of the conference.
Amnesty's willingness to use its critical powers is hardly unexpected.
Millions of Chinese will welcome it, and unless their Government returns
to systematic repression, it is something which will have to be lived
with. The changes which China is undergoing, to make its economy a
global competitor and participant, have sociological and political
consequences. Even if these are delayed it still must seem that they are
unavoidable. For example, China is not a society which has been notably
well disposed towards women (notwithstanding the last, and unusually
powerful, Empress) and that gives the UN conference's location an
unusual irony which will not be lost either among those taking part or
those witnessing and hearing of its deliberations through the local
media. The event is part of a process, now more than a century old, to
modernise China. The modernisers seem at last to have won, but the
Government, which is probably now backing them, is not happy with all
that goes with them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Working to broaden artistic horizons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL,DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634029</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAS Richard Demarco set a welcome trend -- or a challenge? His
Festival programme of 80 exhibitions and theatre productions from 20
different countries includes an innovative foray to Dundee, courtesy of
Dundee Rep and Seagate Gallery. It's been followed by the Italians and
Norwegians in Gullane and the Danes in Linlithgow. Where will it stop?
When is a Fringe a fringe?
The middle-age spread of the Festival -- well it is in its 49th year
after all -- is reflected in both the (free) Edinburgh Gallery Guide
Festival issue which stretches to Haddington, Stenton and
North-Northumberland as well (from this week on the Internet at
http://www.hw.ac.uk/eca www/galleryguide/) and the brand new (free)
Contemporary Art Exhibitions listings produced by the enterprising
Collective Gallery.
This covers -- wait for it -- Glasgow. It includes the CCA, Street
Level, Glasgow Print Studio (who also exhibit in Edinburgh), Glasgow
School of Art and Transmission, It even has a map of Glasgow, plus one
with Castlemilk's Fringe Gallery. There's that F word again! This guide
has Glasgow exhibitions in pink, Edinburgh's in black. Any reference to
overdue electricity bills or a fading Red Clydeside is unintentional,
they tell me. It just means Glasgow's ''in the pink!''.
So? Is it possible? Can Edinburgh and Glasgow share a Festival fringe?
Glasgow's 1999 UK City of Architecture and Design bid made much of its
intention to collaborate, and grant-giving bodies view this as essential
now that cash is tight. And although 1999 officials seem to be asleep,
it looks as though the grassroots artistic community -- which has more
nous and generosity of spirit that it's given credit for -- has decided
to get on with it.
In the spirit of future friendly Festival expansionist policy, I've
spent much time plunging from one Fringe to the other, from Dundee and
Kirkcaldy (superb #2m refurbished Pathhead Theatre) to Traquair
(fabulous garden installation using motifs from the family crest), and
beyond. Tim Clifford and Dr Duncan Thomson of the Scottish National
Galleries have also been voting with their feet.
I spotted our Tim, still in a state of Grace, at the Glasgow School of
Art 150th anniversary launch, and Thomson at Keith McIntyre's
Dumfermline exhibition, a mere 15-minute drive from the rather noisy
Royal Scottish Museum Summer Party.
Linlithgow's Fringe Great Danes (applied arts and prints at the Line
Gallery), runs in parallel with the Festival's official Danish show at
the City Art Centre patronised by a delegation of 60 visiting
dignitaries and artists including two ministers of state -- this from a
country exactly the same size as Scotland.
The Linlithgow exhibits are by the same craftsmen as in Edinburgh --
but here things are for sale.
The Grange, also in Linlithgow, further bridges the east-west gap with
work by four Glasgow-based artists. Bellingham, Stewart, Smith, and
Treffry benefit from showing in a beautiful setting belonging to the
family of Cadell, the painter.
Traquair is part of Demarco's new passion: gardens. His summer school
journeyed to the Festival via 30 gardens from Hampton Court to Edzell's
Zodiac Garden. Traquair's installation, Ursa Major, uses natural
grasses, flowers, and cones to create stars, hearts, a key, a dove --
and of course the Bear.
Terry Sandell of Visiting Arts has also been holding his Festival
receptions in a garden. He's used to bridging gaps and making links
across the world. This year he's moved his team to Edinburgh for three
weeks with great success. A bright idea. Why wasn't it done before? Set
up in 1977, Visiting Arts ''promotes and facilitates the flow of foreign
arts into the UK''. Now Sandell has organised the first catalogue of
foreign events (300 so far) which gets wide distribution via embassies
abroad. There's also a conference on Friday at the Fringe Club
(telephone 0131-447 4716).
Demarco features to the fore in all this, with a 29-year record of
Bridging The Gap -- as his 1995 programme is aptly called. This year's
performers include 30 kids from Tuzla Youth Theatre who spent five days
and nights on a bus to get here, and the Polish group, Teatr Podrozy,
whose nightmare journey last year included a fatal car crash. Their
brave return to Edinburgh has been rewarded by Fringe awards galore.
In his speech at Visiting Arts, Demarco underlined his commitment to
extending boundaries, saying that in 1999 he hopes to take the Fringe to
Glasgow as part of the Year of Architecture and Design.
With Brian McMaster loath to have anything to do with the visual arts,
Demarco -- and Clifford -- take on a particular pre-eminence.
Back at the Mound, Clifford's Three Graces are packing them in at a
rate of more than 7000 on a good day; 128,000 visitors and rising.
Postcards, posters, and T-shirts are into their second reprint. And they
used to talk of bums on seats!
No doubt the Scottish Office will be inundated with
performance-related demands for increased cash. And with the National
Galleries still set on a central venue in Glasgow, could it be that
Festival 1999 will see a National Gallery bash in the new Post Office
gallery in George Square? Well, The Herald Festival party did take place
not a million miles from those Three Graces.
Reciprocity. It's a difficult word to say, to spell, to enact. How
many of Glasgow's officials ''made it through'' to the Festival? Very
few it seems. However, they're all off to London on Monday to launch the
1996 Visual Arts Programme there. Glasgow has to wait till Tuesday
night. A fringe too far, perhaps?
Glasgow-Edinburgh collaboration would be helped by a super speed
train, and the M8 definitely needs a facelift. Except for Motorola's
grass pyramids, it's a notoriously monotonous drive. However,
Baillieston's concrete flyover is vastly improved by floodlit special
effects in delicious mauves and turquoise. More please! And how about
something celebratory for 1999? Fibre optics on that gasometer perhaps?
If Prestwick can get #96,000 Lottery money for its public art, surely,
with 1999 on the horizon, the Glasgow-Edinburgh link is in with a
chance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Folk Songs of North-east Scotland, ScottishPower Gallery, Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONDAY'S sixteenth delve into the Greig-Duncan Collection was a tale
of two presenters. As a Generation Game hostess, Isla St Clair was
always a waste of a good traditional singer, a theory immediately given
full credence when she launched into Band O' Shearers. She has a natural
melodiousness and exuberance that brings songs to life, songs she has
been singing virtually since she learned to talk, be they vigorous romps
or sober ballads. Welcome back.
As a presenter (and not at all unpleasant singer) here, Ian Olson
might be reasonably accused of hiding his light under a bushell. His
theme of whether folk songs speak truth or fiction was amusingly
inconclusive and was posited with the sort of dry wit that would sit
comfortably in a Have I Got News For You chair.
Although I leave her to last, Aileen Carr was by no means making up
the numbers. Her singing is confident and strong and she makes the
longer ballads all the more easily digestible by showing that she really
cares (or occasionally otherwise) about the characters involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Itxaro Mentxaka and Jordi Galofre, Queens Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634031</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER the recent feats of Dvorak and Schubert, yesterday morning's
recital of Spanish songs and duets was like a visit to a tapas bar. As
the introductory nibbles of Falla suggested, the emphasis would be on
small, spicy treats, which seemed just right for palates by now in
danger of becoming jaded.
Starting with Falla's Seven Popular Spanish Songs -- music with which
recitalists more often prefer to finish -- was certainly a good idea, at
least in a performance as vivacious as Itxaro Mentxaka's. This Basque
mezzo-soprano brought a bright metallic ring to the music that made it
sound new-minted. The question, however, was whether the rest of the
programme could live up to such a high-definition opening.
Jordi Galofre, relying more on soulful gestures than on beauty of
tone, did not provide the most reassuring of answers, though he sang
Leandro's Romance from Irrasabal's The Port Tavern -- the first of a
series of excerpts of Spanish Operettas -- with the charm to be expected
of a pupil of Carlo Bergonzi.
If the five songs that formed Rodolfo Halffter's The Sailor On Land
proved less persuasive, that was because the words needed a composer
like Berlioz to fill them with the right sort of passionate nostalgia.
But Montsalvage's Five Negro Songs, brilliantly characterised by Itxaro
Mentxaka were another matter, and the duets -- especially the one by
Manuel Fernandez-Caballero that never seemed quite to fit its printed
words -- were a delight.
The same could be said, most of the time, for Bartomeu Jaume's
relentlessly exhuberant accompaniments, which he delivered -- luckily
for the singers -- with the piano lid down.
* Sponsored by the Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Requiem for a Young Poet, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634032</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST night the Edinburgh Festival opened the gates of a musical
Jurassic Park and unleashed a dinosaur. The sixties was a period of
great musical ferment -- anything-goes style -- as composers dipped into
the lucky bag of culture and helped themselves to anything they came
across: objets trouves, concrete sounds, electronic sounds, jazz, rock.
It was a sort of pre-digital sampling (perhaps also suggesting vacuity
of original inspiration). Weird and not-so-wonderful results ensued.
Music went out into the street, into the park in one case, into space in
another, and, in some hands, mutated into gigantism.
Generally speaking, the species is extinct. Fossilised examples
survive in recordings. The Requiem for a Young Poet, written by Bernd
Alois Zimmerman at the end of the sixties, and shortly before his own
suicide, recalls many of the features of the period. Suffused with
preoccupations addressing the inner self and the human condition
(freedom, totalitarianism, existentialism, abuse of human rights, etc
etc) the work is enormous.
It involved, on the stage of the Usher Hall, a huge symphony orchestra
(the SWF Symphony Orchestra from Baden Baden, minus violins and violas),
a jazz group, and the Edinburgh Festival Chorus. Up in the grand circle
were massed choirs from Cologne, Stuttgart, and Bratislava. Around the
auditorium were loudspeakers which transmitted the texts, electronic
sounds, and sampled recordings (from Wagner to the Beatles) that
comprised much of the work.
For all the massiveness of scale -- and it is a bleakly depressing,
formidable, and imposing work, assembled, often collage-style, as a
series of monolithic slabs -- the Requiem fails to impress. Ultimately,
it recalls the worst excesses of the period: from its intense
navel-gazing to the sheer indulgence of the assemblage (from the left
speaker the opening bars of the finale to Beethoven's Ninth, from the
right, Paul McCartney singing Hey Jude).
Perhaps because it was so slab-like -- a sonic sculpture -- it was
utterly devoid of lyrical impulse and fundamentally non-dramatic. It was
merely a presentation, like a grotesque musical mobile. You could watch
it revolve; it neither developed nor involved. It was an empty vessel, a
barren hulk, a noisy, lumbering monster of a piece. Maybe a dinosaur,
certainly a turkey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Merchant of Venice, Royal Lyceum</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634033</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GERT VOSS'S Shylock is an extroardinary characterisation; a Jew
indistinguishable from his merchant peers on the Rialto, and further, a
steady, subdued man, with Voss playing Shylock's most emotive speeches,
in particular the ''Hath not a Jew . . .'' invocation, with devastating
understatement. He is a resolute businessman, who makes his deadly
demand seem reasonable yet it is a chilly performance, pointedly
eschewing any possibility of pathos.
More extraordinary, and for the wrong reasons, is director Pete
Zadek's version for the Berliner Ensemble. His Rialto is a magnificent
money-making arena, fronted by a Docklands-type facade of steely columns
and mirrored windows and peopled by slick-suit ed businessmen clutching
briefcases and mobiles -- an interpretation which is starting to look
cliched in the extreme, for all its appropriateness to the wheeling and
dealing themes.
Zadek's Belmont is a muddled mess, signalled by descending painted
backdrops which are as sketchy as the goings on at Portia's household
are in this production.
Zadek highlights the comic elements of the play to great effect,
underscoring this focus with the bizarre double casting of Voss and
Ignaz Kirchner (Antonio) as Portia's hapless suitors the Princes of
Morocco and Arragon, but does so at the expense of the play's passion;
Shylock's revenge, Antonio and Bassanio's intense friendship, the
various romances -- all are inspidily portrayed.
There are moments of great hilarity -- the young spikey-haired Uwe
Bohm adlibbing in English makes a feast of the clown Launcelot Gobbo --
which are never counterbalanced by moments of great drama. The court
scene in particular is robbed of its tension by this dispassionate
approach.
It's a piece which seems strangely at war with itself, suffused with
too many internal contrasts -- most pointedly between the performances
of the men and the women. Eva Mattes is a bland, uninspired Portia while
the device of Nerissa (Wiebke Frost) as Absolutely Fabulous's Bubbles is
exceptionally irritating. Striking images and superb delivery from Voss
and Kirchner could not redeem this production's soullessness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dark fairy tale. The Hard Nut, Edinburgh Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Hard Nut -- deliciously outre and glam on the outside, romantic
and caringly true to Hoffmann on the inside!
Most Nutcrackers cheerfully bypass the darker inner kernel of
Hoffmann's tale, preferring instead the happy magic of a child's best
dreams -- a doll that comes to life and takes you to the Kingdom of
Sweets. But Morris, as ever, is in touch with the real dreams that grip
us all our lives. The dreams that deal in loving and being loved. The
dreams that don't always come true.
When The Hard Nut opens, it's on a seriously flaky Christmas party
being given by the Stahlbaums. It's that paradise-time of tackette
fashion, the sixties, and the guests are out to razzle in gruesome
flares, minis, and catsuits. Hovering on the edge of this Charlestoning,
bopping, frugging sea of seasonal green and red are the three Stahlbaum
children. It's their party, not.
Mother (the persuasively padded Peter Wing Healey) gets relentlessly
sauced, the guests letch and paw one another, the kids are palmed off
with Barbie dolls and expensive trash. It's light years away from the
traditional family gathering of Nutcrackers we have known -- and yet
Morris fits it all, brilliantly, into the Tchaikovsky score.
In the midst of all this is Marie (Clarice Marshall) in her
puff-sleeved, sticky-out party frock. The ideal, tender-hearted moppet
for the big adventure lying in wait once the lights go down. Here again,
Morris's invention has at once updated the time-honoured antics, made
them relevant and amusing without losing sight of their original spirit.
Here the rats battle with GI Joes, but best of all, the snowflakes are
unisex! Clad in silver lame skating skirts, cropped tops, and little
pixie helmets, these flakes spin and pirouette on point, tossing up a
snowstorm as they go. It's the essence of Busby Berkeley, it's
exquisitely camp and at the same time it's utterly magical -- everyone,
men and women, careen on point as if they never walked or ran any other
way.
In the second act Morris uses Hoffmann's hard nut as the framework for
a series of brilliant national dances -- he himself is the mysterious
Odalisque in Arabian. The denouement, when Marie declares love for the
rejected, ugly Nutcracker, is the fulfilment of what the entire piece is
about -- a travelling towards maturity, an achieving and giving of love
-- though the little red-eyed mechanical rat that dogs their footsteps
may suggest love's young dream may eventually falter.
The glorious mix of choreographic styles, the absolutely stunning
designs, are what catch one's attention first, but beyond this
marvellous overlay of style lies Morris's rare understanding of the
darker side of fairy tales and his ability to communicate that side to
us in an extravaganza shimmering with cunning wit and exuberant joie de
vivre.
* Sponsored by ScottishPower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cushioned Souls, Roxburgh Halls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOTHING quite matches here. Hundreds of confused shoes, piled
higgledy-piggledy in a heap. ''Who I am'' stories that stop short of a
name. Even the language is all out of kilter. Nothing agrees, nothing
really makes sense. Why? Well I suspect love -- or rather love gone
wrong -- if the cause of life's syntax falling into ripe disorder.
Cushioned Soles (devised and performed by NTROP Performance Theatre)
is like a beguiling surreal jigsaw puzzle. Four girls -- in between
sorting out and trying on everything from pointe shoes to Doc Martens --
talk in apparent non sequiturs that then give way to bursts of energetic
dance. But gradually, as the shoes pair up, a bizarre romance of
meetings and partings unfolds from the muddle of text . . . Engagingly
quirky, with lots of clever touches and nicely judged, almost dead-pan,
performances adding to the fun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Losing Wonderland, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MINTY DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE very youthfulness of Ablaze Theatre Company creates a closeness to
their material that is both the strength and weakness of their
performance.
Using movement, home cine footage and a pre-recorded sound track of
music and childhood reminiscences, they effectively capture the presumed
innocence of the young and frequently painful transition to
''experienced'' adolescence; moving from earliest memories, through
schoolyard fights and friendships, to the excruciating awkwardness of a
teenage disco and the first fumbling sexual experiences.
A more detached, considered, and indeed older, perspective might have
produced work of greater depth, but the company's obvious identification
with their subject matter gave a refreshing take on a much-explored
area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Traffic policeman dies after patrol car crashes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TRAFFIC policeman died in hospital early yesterday from injuries he
received on Monday night when the patrol car he was travelling in
crashed.
Constable Mark Davey, 28, was the front-seat passenger in the car when
it careered off the A96 Elgin-Forres road, near the Oakwood Motel, and
crashed into trees.
Mr Davey was cut from the wreckage and taken to Dr Gray's Hospital in
Elgin for treatment to serious head injuries, but died after he was
transferred to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary.
Mr Davey, of Ashgrove Square, Elgin, was separated from his wife Anne,
who lives in Inverness with their children, Hayley, two, and Lauren, 18
months. He was a well-known fundraiser for leukemia charities and had
raised #30,000 since his 20-month-old daughter Lindsay died from the
disease five years ago.
The Vauxhall Senator patrol car was being driven by Constable Graham
Sloan, 28, who isbased in Elgin. Mr Sloan suffered head and back
injuries in the crash and is still receiving treatment in hospital.
Chief Constable Ian Oliver said the whole force was distressed to
learn of Mr Davey's death.
He said: ''I know that everyone will be deeply shocked at his death
and, on behalf of Grampian Police, I extend our sympathies to his family
and colleagues.
''In his 10 years' service in the Elgin and Banff areas, he had
established himself as an enthusiastic and popular officer.''
Meanwhile, a patient in Raigmore Hospital, Inverness, was told
yesterday that her son -- an RAF man based at Saxa Vord, Shetland -- had
been killed when his motor cycle left the road as he headed for the
ferry on the first stage of his journey south to visit her.
Heart patient Mrs Margaret McSweeney, 62, of Logan Drive in Dingwall
had last seen her son Mr Morgan McSweeney, 23, a senior aircraftsman, in
July. He will be buried at Fodderty Cemetery at the end of the week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Psst!, The Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S a strong feel of behind-the-scenes in this piece. It's as if
Company Pyke (all members of CandoCo) were lifting the lid a little on
their lives as performers.
A giggle of girlies coo over David Toole. Is their fuss to do with his
dancing -- or the fact that, born without legs, he dances on his arms?
Come to that, just what is it we applaud?
And just what is it we expect? By all accounts, not sex. PSST! thrusts
aside common hypocrisies about integrated dance with a tender, sensual
duet between Toole and Charlotte Derbyshire where the shifts between
friendship and physical attraction are traced eloquently, openly.
It's an utterly stunning piece of choreography, part of a witty,
perceptive programme of fine dance -- how good to see Kuldip Singh-Barmi
given more to do -- that challenges perceptions by stretching them in
different, stimulating directions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heavy Breathing, Randolph Studio</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MINTY DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634039</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COULD be I'm just cynical and suspicious, or could be that launching
straight into a piece of enforced audience participation (in an audience
of around half a dozen) was just too unsettling for an emotionally
repressed Scot like myself, but I never quite shook off a creeping sense
of unease throughout Scott Carter's confessional, comediac, and very
American one-man show.
His studiedly circuitous monologue shifted disconcertingly from the
quirky humour; rye chuckles rather than belly laughs; or his experiences
as a soft porn writer into the heavier territory of near-death
encounters with chronic asthma. Acutely observed, delivered with
measured skill, and cleverly crafted as it was, Carter's story struck
chords, but ultimately failed to move.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jewels crown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY fingers are crossed. Next Tuesday Peter Chang will learn if he has
beaten a shortlist of five to win Britain's new #15,000 applied arts
award: the Jerwood Prize for Jewellery. It's a first-time prize, by far
the most valuable award for applied arts in the UK. Chang is the only
Scottish-based artist to be selected.
In the way of things, he is not really a jeweller. He doesn't make
silver rings or set diamonds in gold. He's a printmaker turned sculptor
who ended up making the most gorgeous, outrageous, exotic, eccentric,
colourful but indefinable objects which can exist in their own right as
objet d'art -- but which any stylish woman would clamour to wear. His
creations have wit and humour (''I like to incorporate a bit of fun,
spice it up. People take things too seriously'') and only flashing neon
could create more jangling, high-volume colour.
This Jerwood nomination puts him in the limelight. Deservedly so, for
he is one of the most innovative artists I know. His unique vision and
quirky but luscious sense of design goes hand in hand with superb
craftsmanship. To coin a phrase, he's the Faberge of the twenty-first
century.
So what does this master of ornamentation and adornment use for raw
materials? Gold, silver, lapis lazuli? Not at all. He recycles broken
bits of plastic toothbrush, razor handles, toys, old school rulers,
felt-tip pens, knitting needles.
''I wanted something that would reflect the age we live in, and I like
the idea of working with a substance that is usually thrown away. Using
plastic gets away from the preciousness of jewels and gold. Whereas wood
or metal imposes its own character, plastic is anonymous. It only has
the character you give it.''
The first bracelets, brooches and earrings, in 1984, were made for his
wife, Barbara Santos-Shaw, ex-head of printed textiles at Glasgow School
of Art, now teaching at London's Royal College and in Amsterdam. As she
jets around the world from their Pollokshields base she jangles her huge
bracelet cuffs and magnificent earrings in saturated yellow and red,
sometimes offset by pink, mauve and glitter gold. As a redhead, primary
colours suit her. I would love a bracelet but at #1000 have so far
settled for two brooches in red, blue, and bronze with yellow
highlights. They never fail to cause an impact.
In 1987 fashion-design guru Rifat Ozbek featured Chang's jewellery on
the world's catwalks and it hit the cover of Harpers, Elle, and Vogue.
''Rifat came to me because he thought my things went well with his
clothes.''
Soon he was showing his organic, psychedelic designs (some resembling
a cross between a flower and an insect complete with tail and horns), at
the V &amp; A, in New York, Paris's Musee des Arts Decoratif, Helsinki,
Munich, Philadelphia, Amsterdam, Zurich, Budapest, Chicago, Barcelona,
Brussels -- even in his birthplace, Liverpool.
Sounds perfect? But the truth is that although Chang has made a
top-rank international reputation, it's almost impossible to make a
living from these wonderful creations. Some take 400 hours or more to
make. And the dust and fumes from the resins are beginning to wreck his
health. The #15,000 Jerwood could literally be a lifesaver.
Chang may use twentieth-century materials, but their painstaking
application is as old as time. He starts with a carved core of
polystyrene foam which is encased with umpteen layers of brilliantly
coloured polyester resin (some sparkle!), and inset with slices of found
plastic. This is then sanded and polished back to reveal complex
patterns.
It's a version of kasane nuri togidashi, a Japanese technique used
with lacquer work. There are also hints of Byzantine mosaics intertwined
with Antonio Gaudi-esque bulbous decoration -- a far cry from the 1960s
kitsch, pop art, and pop world influences which Chang absorbed in
Liverpool where he knew the Beatles, and Barbara once slept in Yoko
Ono's satin-lined coffin!
His latest departure is into larger pieces with an edge of glamorous
decadence or the allure of the fetishistic talisman: fabulous mirrors,
dancing salt and pepper grinders, their antennae giving them an air of
alien space creatures (which, however, found a fat-cat home in Holland),
an incredible box rather like an exotic fairy-tale beetle, a table (for
a New York loft) breathtaking in its form, its legs from Dr Who, its
surface, which took months, reminiscent of a psychedelic juke box. It
was shown in London's Crafts Council gallery earlier this year to great
acclaim.
Chang's jewellery is radical; magic, unique, stylish. He has obviously
absorbed influences as diverse as Klimt, Miro, and Art Deco, and his
Chinese background gives him an innate love of decoration. But dissect
his work as you will, you can only marvel at the intelligence of his
absurdities, the surprise of his lateral thinking, the raw energy of his
creations. I just hope he wins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greek Thomson, RIAS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GAVIN STAMP continues his crusade to re-establish the Victorian
architect Alexander Greek Thomson by taking this exhibition of splendid
original drawings and photographs to the Festival.
It makes a handsome display (except for the labels' curling edges),
and presents a lot of information in a palatable way. I was glad to see
they had avoided architectural elevations -- which the public find
difficult to read -- in preference to elegant white models of the
Egyptian Halls, Grecian Chambers, Queen's Park Terrace, and more.
Many people will find the old Annan photos fascinating while new
glossy colour shots show the restoration of buildings like Holmwood and
Great Western Terrace.
The accompanying leaflet provides a succinct introduction. Sadly,
despite sterling work by many activists, including New Glasgow Society
members without whose lobbying more Thompson buildings would be lost,
many of his works have been demolished. No more, says Stamp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A world of hidden terrors. Losing Wonderland, Hill Street Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634042</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE upon a time . . . we were all children. Wandering -- just like
Alice -- through unknown places full of bewildering people, with
contrary rules that didn't make sense, and always a feeling of being
powerless.
It's this state of confusion that powers the words and movements of
Losing Wonderland. Devised and performed by Ablaze Theatre Company (from
Bristol University), the piece points up the darker sides of childhood
and adolescence.
While personal anecdotes (often brutally funny) form a clever
soundscore, the company dance out scenarios of bullying, shyness,
one-upmanship and quiet fear. The moment when one boy, having pored over
a huge newspaper, folds it into a giant hat and hides inside, is
astutely telling. The world is full of hidden terrors when you are too
young to control your own life. In all, a much-visited subject, but done
here with fresh energy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Donna McPhail, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE ain't no lady. Nor is she a sister. Rather, Donna prefers to stay
true to her calling as British stand-up's top bovver-bird and most
dapper dyke, deftly employing her rapier wit on wispy New Men; leering
old men; stupid young women; compliant Tory wives; overly-supportive
feminists in shapeless, organically-grown clothing; bad-tempered
adolescent girls.
Why is it women, not men, who tend to suffer more under the McPhailite
iron heel? Some wispy New Man sociologist might say it was because Donna
is hardest on herself -- just before Donna kicked him in the crutch.
I'll merely say that Donna's first night picked up when she forswore the
tried-and-trusted aggro approach for newer, gentler, more
autobiographical stuff. Let her hit you with it soon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Paul Tonkinson, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUNG Tonks is a palpable hit, a laddish graduate of the Lee Evans
school of high-speed twitchiness as well as being a keen-eyed
observational confessor a la Sean Hughes. He derives much mirth from the
senseless cruelty of his schooldays in north Yorkshire; from his recent
experience of undergraduate squalor, privation, and officiousness, and
from his first-hand experiences of the joys and sillinesses of the rave
era.
While Paul's depiction of amphetamine-induced girning and adolescent
mating rituals are spot-on, there's probably less accuracy in his
hilarious presentation of his girlfriend and grandparents as cousins of
Orville the duck. But what the heck: if you can't make friends with Paul
Tonkinson, you are beyond help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Richie Havens, The Jazz Cafe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID SHEPPARD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RICHIE HAVENS is famous for two things. First, for that dauntingly
solo opening slot at the Woodstock Festival and, secondly, for his
unique guitar chording technique which relies on the use of a single but
highly versatile thumb.
Running down the steps on to the Jazz Cafe's minimalist stage, Havens
cuts an enigmatic figure dressed, as always, in silk robes, his neck
supporting a mane of beads, he looks part sixties guru and, with bald
pate and greying beard, part benign uncle.
Years of performing have honed his song introductions into the laconic
monologues of the seasoned raconteur which is useful as he also takes an
eternity to tune up his guitar between numbers -- a lifetime's jet
travel having done something irreversible to his hearing, he alleges.
None of this interferes with the litany of interpretive cover versions
which constitute tonight's repertoire.
Drawing heavily on the Bob Dylan canon, this is a greatest-hits
package, though, as Havens would willingly attest, he's never had one
himself. (A version of George Harrison's Here Comes the Sun being the
nearest thing.) All Along the Watchtower highlights fluid
second-guitarist Paul Williams and sees Havens, eyes closed, giving it
some with the thumb and extemporising powerfully with that hot, buttery
voice.
Later we get a free-form Just Like a Woman and a waltz-time
re-arrangement of The Times They Are A'changin' which actually manages
to wrestle some emotional chutzpah from this stalest of protest anthems.
Van Morrison's Tupelo Honey and the aforementioned Here Comes the Sun
are given light, almost nursery rhyme, treatments and we are then given
folksy reworkings of songs by Fleetwood Mac and Sting and there's even a
version of Happy Birthday to You.
In contrast, the echo-protest What You Gonna Do About Me is dark and
sombre and distinguished by some dynamic strumming from Havens. The
crowd of unreconstructed hippies, fortysomething couples and curious
Camden trendies lap it all up -- Havens having got them well and truly
under his thumb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Place With The Pigs, Overseas House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634046</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Theatre
ATHOL FUGARD'S play deals with the ''two profound philosophical
realities . . . pig shit and time''. Pavel Navrotsky deserted from the
Russian army and fled home to hide in his pigsty, for 44 years.
The writing is a small masterpiece of concision and psychological
depth. Pavel's desertion haunts him because of the cowardice it
represents, but cowardice also prevents him seeking freedom and
responsibility.
It is only at the moment when he recognises his similarity to the
animals he loathes and beats that he finds the strength to defeat
childhood memories and a life of fear.
Pinstripe Theatre would have needed more space than they have to give
this its temporal scope and dramatic intensity. However the two actors
do enough to carry off the basic idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eleventh-hour protest off Mururoa Atoll</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634047</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
RESUMED nuclear testing in the South Pacific was ''very close'',
France said today, as politicians from New Zealand and the Cook Islands
handed an angry note to the French navy from a protest boat off the test
site.
As tension mounted at Mururoa Atoll, the French chased off a
Greenpeace helicopter and the environmental group finalised plans for a
flotilla protest.
Greenpeace has vowed to breach the 12-mile military exclusion zone in
its bid to prevent the resumption of testing.
''There is no doubt that we are very close now to the beginning of the
campaign,'' the commander of French test sites in the South Pacific,
General Paul Vericel, said from the atoll, about 750-miles south of
Tahiti.
''We are now doing preparations to make our experiments from September
1'', Vericel said in a telephone call.
French atomic energy officials said one of the nuclear explosions
would be weapon strength -- almost 150 kilotons.
Vericel was speaking as New Zealand and the Cook Islands
representatives delivered a protest note off the atoll saying the
planned tests were ''monstrous''.
President Jacques Chirac announced in June that France would resume
testing with a final salvo of seven or eight nuclear blasts at Mururoa
or Fangataufa atolls in French Polynesia between September and May.--
Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parsons and Naylor, Gilded Balloon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634048</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RUBBER-FACED prole, Andy Parsons admits to looking like Mel Smith,
Keith Chegwin and/or a potato. His unfeasibly-lofty partner, Henry
Naylor, is plainly a more mellow Cleesian fellow. The ever-altering
balance of power in their relationship is what end ears you to their
cleverly silly sketches and their amiable muggery.
Alongside some technically accomplished aural comedy, they chuck in
base slapstick employing smeary, splattery comestibles. Whether or not
you sit in the free-fire zone of the front row, you'll find Parsons and
Naylor's bare-all brand of comedy sticking with you.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cafe Flesh, St Bride's Centre,</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634049</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WATERLESS swimming -- very frisky, very flirty -- and a piece (by
Tamsyn Salter) which could well be subtitled Barbie's Revenge. The first
half, featuring works by company members and others, might leave fans
feeling that The re-Animators have deserted the familiar territory of
Gothick camp and studied decadence.
But Piers is here, in Cafe Flesh, with a sharp reworking of ideas
floated in an earlier piece, once Therapy now titled Downward Spiral.
It's a sideways spin on Orpheus and Eurydice, really. This time they
stay together, but in Hell. Visually striking with some cunningly
furious choreography that ultimately suggests Hell is endless,
relentless techno . . .
The dance ranges freely from slinking tango to pointe-work, sometimes
elegantly sinister, sometimes sweaty with all-out manic crash as flesh
meets flesh in torment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dark Tales, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIELLE NAGLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOW do you tell a horror story when the firesides have mostly turned
electric? This intelligent two-hander by Tim Arthur explores the
comparative chill factors of the horrors of modern reality and the
traditional ghost story.
Patrick Drury is a masterful Alex Crowther, a horror writer on his way
out of print, while Paul Panting gives an excellent performance as Jack
Langton, the younger would-be, clogged by twisted imaginings of his own
life's possible realities.
Despite a Sweeney Todd style ending, this production does contain some
crafted story-telling producing genuine spine thrill. The sun is cooler
and the shadows darker on the way out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Feelgood, Cafe Royal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEW drama from the prodigious playwright John Cargill Thompson, this
quirky two-hander is predicated on the premise of a homosexual version
of date rape, raising intriguing questions of politcal correctness and
male sexuality, which the text, commendably, not only opens up but also
probes quite vigorously.
Poor stagecraft, the actors stranded on a bare, too brightly lit
stage, made the production seem threadbare but the script is a sturdy
one, if overburdened with black humour, with a tendency to chase jokes
at inappropriate moments.
The performances trod a thin line between impassioned and overwrought,
occasionally slipping between the cracks and losing credibility but Dan
Swinton was convincingly distressed as Karl, the heterosexual man who
had invited his homosexual friend's advances, while Richard Forrest
radiated enough underlying menace as the thoughtful Norman to hit the
right note of ambiguity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Legend About the End of the World, Demarco European Art Foundation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634052</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS I'm about to go in I meet a young Sarajevan woman who's just heard
the casualty figures from the latest bombing of her home town. Then in
the theatre I find three Yugoslav actresses holding a requiem for all
that has been lost, not just in Sarajevo, but in Belgrade, Moscow,
Alexandria and backwards through time.
The contradictions are compelling. These women of DAH Theatre are at
once victim and life-force. They are raped and abused, their memories
lost in scattered photographs, yet lament turns into celebration, fear
into defiant violence, passive into active.
In one enigmatically beautiful image, they pour out bags of salt to
form a massive hieroglyph round a miniature town square, itself
harbouring their treasured photographs. It's an image of desolation,
isolation, yet somehow of hope, and out of the anguish emerges a
forceful plea for life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ombudsman criticises delay in handling legal complaint and recommends compensation. Law Society inquiry 'unsatisfactory'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634053</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Law Society of Scotland has been heavily criticised for botching
an investigation and told to pay the aggrieved client compensation.
The Scottish Legal Services Ombudsman, Mr Garry Watson, in his
judgment, said: ''In my opinion, this investigation has been thoroughly
unsatisfactory.'' His judgment makes a series of recommendations for
tightening up the society's complaints procedure.
Former Scots Guardsman Adrian Russo wrote to the society in February
1992, detailing several complaints dating back to 1989 against
Hamilton-based firm Hay, Cassels, and Frame. 0 Mr Russo, 31, of
Stonefield Road, Blantyre, Lanarkshire, alleged delays and overcharging
in respect of a #150 retainer and a #4000 bill for his father in dealing
with an estate when he was eligible for legal aid.
The Law Society reporter appointed to look into the complaints issued
a report in November 25, 1992, three months after receiving the files.
He found that the firm had acted reasonably, except in failing to hand
on papers to another firm of lawyers for two months.
The society's complaints committee issued its findings in January 1993
but these related only to Mr Russo's principal complaint and not the
others.
After a further two years and much correspondence, these other matters
were still not resolved, although part of the delay was due to Mr Russo.
There was confusion between the society's reporter and deputy secretary
over what needed to be investigated and which were the relevant files.
''The Law Society investigation of this somewhat complicated complaint
has been the subject of severe administrative error and of delay,'' Mr
Watson said.
''The complainer has handled correspondence relating to this
investigation with patience and decorum, naturally expecting that the
matter would be investigated on a controlled and professional basis,''
Mr Watson said.
''Regrettably, this has been far from the case and it is wholly
understandable that in his last letter to the Law Society, dated
December 13, 1994, his patience finally snapped when the mishandling of
this investigation had become apparent to him.
''While there were a number of separate complaints, each of a
relatively straightforward nature, there is no reason whatsoever why the
investigation should have become so prolonged and confused and why the
complainer should have been caused so much unnecessary inconvenience and
hassle due to such handling by the Law Society.''
Mr Watson said that although he was satisfied that Mr Russo's
principal complaint and that of his mother were ultimately handled
properly, this was not the case with his father's complaint and one
relating to an interdict.
He made six recommendations urging the society to look again at these
matters and consider making an ex-gratia payment to Mr Russo for
mishandling his complaints.
''The Law Society should give serious consideration to means of
avoiding the errors and delays which have arisen in this investigation,
which is no credit to its investigatory procedure,'' Mr Watson added.
Last night, Mr Russo said he was delighted with the ombudsman's
findings.
''I am also pleased about the offer of a payment. I think a
four-figure sum might be a reasonable amount,'' he said.
Mr Kenneth Pritchard, secretary of the Law Society of Scotland, said
it had introduced new procedures and hired more secretarial staff since
the episode, but would not comment on the issue of compensation.
''This is an exceptional case in which the criticism is severe,'' he
said.
''We are very concerned about it and we are dealing with it as a
matter of urgency. We believe the steps we have already taken will
obviate the administrative difficulties referred to and certainly any
question of delay.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>I was drunk, confesses US senator over sex claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
A PROMINENT Republican senator, facing public hearings over charges of
sexual misconduct, said today he had been so drunk some evenings that he
could not remember some of the incidents.
''In some cases I was very frankly so drunk that I cannot remember the
evening,'' Bob Packwood, who said he stopped drinking three years ago,
told CBS TV.
''That doesn't excuse the conduct but I simply can't remember.''
The Oregon Republican, who became chairman of the powerful Senate
finance committee in November, is accused of making unwanted sexual
advances to 19 women.
The allegations include complaints that Packwood grabbed and kissed
them, often sticking his tongue in their mouths, and in one case
proposed sex.
Asked whether he denied the charges, which span three decades,
Packwood said: ''Some I do. Some I don't. Some I very honestly can't
remember.''
He said he was unable to recall other incidents, such as putting his
arms around a woman at a party 25 years ago, not because of alcohol but
because they had happened so long ago.
The Senate ethics committee has also charged that Packwood asked
lobbyists and businessmen to hire his ex-wife so he would have lower
alimony payments, and that he altered his personal diaries later
subpoenaed by Senate investigators.
Possible action against him includes censure, removal as chairman of
the finance committee or expulsion from the Senate.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sir Prudent aims to bow out from Hong Kong in canny Scots manner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DIANE STORMONT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634055</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hong Kong
THERE will be none of the traditional popping of Champagne corks on
the first-class deck of a luxury passenger liner when Hong Kong's last
British financial secretary bows out next week.
Sir Hamish Macleod, speaking at a farewell news conference yesterday,
said he would leave on September 4 by air rather than sea, the option
chosen by most senior colonial servants.
He promised to return for the hand-over of Hong Kong to China at
midnight on June 30, 1997. ''We've booked a hotel room,'' he said.
At 55, Sir Hamish is taking early retirement to make way for a Hong
Kong Chinese successor, Donald Tsang, a friend and colleague who has
been groomed for the post.
''I think it will be a little more difficult,'' Sir Hamish, who joined
the Hong Kong government in 1966, said of Tsang's job.
Tsang has the 1997 transfer itself to weather. Beijing has yet to
announce whether it will reappoint the handful of civil servants put in
by the British to the top posts.
On the domestic front, Tsang, 50, will have to contend with an
increasingly politicised Legislative Council, a result of the new
pro-democracy reforms introduced by Governor Chris Patten.
The first all-elected council in Hong Kong's 150 year history will be
voted into office on September 17.
Sir Hamish, meanwhile, shrugs off the difficulties he faced in his
years at the financial helm of the world's eighth largest trading
territory.
Since he took over in 1990, Hong Kong's gross domestic product has
risen 25%, sending it up the per capita GDP ladder to rank 15th in the
world from 23rd five years ago.
''He's a canny Scot. Modest. His nickname is Sir Prudent. Ostentation
is not his style,'' said one colleague, who also described him as
''well-liked and respected by his staff even if he is better at tennis
than karaoke''.
In his role as financial secretary, the number three job in the Hong
Kong government, Macleod had to cope daily with China's fury and
suspicion of British rule in the countdown years.
Patten's arrival and his democratic reforms gave Beijing a political
stick with which to beat the British administration.
But the first, and most enduring symbol of Sino-British discord, was
an ambitious and expensive new airport and port project which Sir Hamish
has been in charge of since its inception in 1989.
China, apparently convinced Hong Kong planned to squander its vast
wealth on the #13bn project, attacked the plan almost from the start.
Early this year, after six years of wrangling and exhausting
negotiations, China finally gave its blessing. By that time, and despite
all the difficulties, the airport was more than 60% completed.
Sir Hamish plans to retire to Edinburgh, play tennis and keep himself
busy with a few non-executive directorships. He was careful to stress
they would be non-Hong Kong companies.
His name is one of 32 put forward for one of the seven World Trade
Organisation appellate posts responsible for arbitrating trade disputes.
''It would be very interesting,'' was all he would say.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
