<HEADLINE>Beijing attempts to muzzle women's forum</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634056</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Beijing
BEIJING today clamped limits on free speech at an international
grassroots women's forum, prompting a brisk challenge from the top
official of the United Nations-sponsored meeting.
Expanding on earlier edicts barring unauthorised protests in Beijing,
a senior security official said demonstrations against China and its
leaders were also banned inside the venue of the Non-Governmental
Organisations (NGO) forum in rural Huairou.
Public Security Vice Minister Tian Qiyu, security boss for the UN
World Conference on Women and its affiliated NGO forum, said protests
were allowed only in a middle school sports field in the NGO site, which
is sealed off from the Chinese public.
Speech is not free even there, he said.
''Inside the site, NGOs are permitted to have demonstrations and
processions but these should not infringe on the sovereignty of the host
country and should not slander or attack leaders of the host country,''
Tian said at a Beijing news conference.
Tian declined to explain who would determine which speeches
constituted slander or violations of sovereignty.
Forum convener Supatra Masdit, top organiser of the meeting that hopes
to influence the UN conference, issued a statement challenging Beijing's
bid to muzzle anti-Chinese opinions.
''The laws of the host country prevail only outside the site of the
forum,'' she said.
Foreign Ministry spokesman Chen Jian also contradicted Tian's decree,
saying UN rules -- not China's -- applied in areas designated by mutual
consent as ''UN premises''.
NGO forum organisers said privately they understood UN premises to
mean anywhere inside the forum site and that China had no right even to
designate a special protest area, much less to restrict what could be
said or done there.
''This is very worrying to us,'' one forum organiser said.
The new edict underlined China's sensitivity to dissent at the NGO
forum, shunted to rural Huairou from Beijing in April after senior
leaders grew alarmed that Chinese might see foreign women denouncing
Chinese policy in central Tiananmen Square.
President and Communist Party chief Jiang Zemin told Iceland President
Vigdis Finnbogadottir that China attached great importance to the
conferences, which she will attend.
''We wish to co-operate with all parties concerned and try our best to
hold this meeting well to make a contribution to improving the global
status of women,'' Jiang said and repeated Chairman Mao Tsetung's remark
that women ''hold up half the sky''.
As Tian spoke, leaders of London-based human rights group Amnesty
International attacked Beijing's ''grave'' human rights record, saying
it was unbelievable that China could execute 16 people to improve
security in Beijing before the conference. Government spokesman Chen
bridled, saying Amnesty's charges about indiscriminate executions were
groundless.--Reuter
</TEXT>
