<HEADLINE>City plans car-free estate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH plans to create a ''car-free'' housing development, thought
to be the first of its kind in Britain -- to qualify for a house you
must undertake not to own a car.
The scheme, backed by Lothian Regional Council, would be modelled on
one in Bremen, Germany, which councillors visited on a fact-finding
mission.
A site for the mix of public and private housing has been earmarked
near Gorgie Road, two miles from the city centre. Talks are under way
with potential private developers.
Tomorrow, the council's transportation committee will discuss securing
the site.
Councillor David Begg, chairman of the region's transportation
committee said: ''We are optimistic that if we can gain consensus on the
use of this site for car-free housing we will see this project taking
off.
''Since we first indicated an interest in such schemes, we have had a
very positive response from a variety of developers.
''The area itself is ideal and I am sure that everyone in the area
will be delighted to see this valuable site being used in such a way.''
He added: ''We have an opportunity here to really lead the way with an
exciting idea which is completely viable as a private and public sector
partnership.''
</TEXT>
