<HEADLINE>Stroke victim Adams vows to continue her drugs campaign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634058</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAISLEY North MP Mrs Irene Adams yesterday said she was recovering
after a stroke and vowed to continue her determined campaign against
drug gangs in the town.
Mrs Adams, 47, was forced to cut short a holiday in America earlier
this month after suffering the minor stroke in New York. She blamed the
pressures of work as an MP, including the fight to clean up her
constituency.
Nevertheless, she said yesterday: ''I feel better than I have after a
bout of flu but I'm taking things easy on the doctor's orders.''
Mrs Adams explained how she lost the feeling in her left hand and foot
one evening in the US city. She had been on a shopping trip in
temperatures of almost 100[DEG]F. Later that evening, she could hardly
walk and then found that she had lost feeling in her hand. A hospital
check-up showed she had suffered a minor stroke but was expected to make
a full recovery. She was told the heat, cigarette smoking, and stress
could all have contributed.
Mrs Adams, who has now given up smoking, has regained some feeling in
her limbs. She has promised to rest but carry on her high-profile
anti-drug campaign, despite threats against herself and her family.
Mrs Adams also blamed the pressures of work on MPs, particularly those
commuting between Scotland and London.
She said: ''The system in this country is crazy, with MPs working long
hours into the night. Scottish MPs suffer the most because they have to
travel the furthest. The daft hours they put in makes them prime
candidates for this sort of thing. I regularly work 14-hour days.''
Mrs Adams's stroke came five years to the day after her husband,
Allen, died of a heart attack.
Meanwhile, neighbouring MP Mr Tommy Graham has dismissed reports of
alleged membership irregularities as ''complete and utter rubbish''.
Newspaper reports claimed the allegations were made in a Labour Party
report into Mr Graham's Renfrew West and Inverclyde seat as well as the
two Paisley constituencies.
He was backed by Labour's Scottish assistant general secretary, Mr
Tommy Sheppard. The report is now being considered by the party's
national constitutional committee.
</TEXT>
