<HEADLINE>Sheriff visits plant in blue cheese row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF paid a private visit to a remote farm yesterday to see the
Lanark blue cheese plant which is at the centre of a court case.
Sheriff John Allan had already heard 11 days of evidence about
allegations that #27,000 worth of the cheese was riddled with the deadly
food virus listeria monocytogenes.
He wanted to learn for himself the methods and standards of hygiene at
the factory, run by cheesemaker Humphrey Errington.
Sheriff Allan barred the press from the visit.
He made it clear to both sides in the case that he was not convening a
court at the farm.
He drove to Walston Braehead Farm, near Dunsyre, Lanarkshire, early
yesterday on his way to Lanark Sheriff Court. At the farm, he had to
wear protective clothing.
Mr Errington's chief cheesemaker, Mr James Little, 45, showed the
sheriff how the blue vein cheese -- a favourite with the Prince of Wales
-- was made from unpasteurised ewe's milk.
Mr Errington is fighting a bid by Clydesdale District Council to
destroy the suspect batch of cheese stored in deep freeze.
When the case resumed yesterday, Professor Verner Wheelock, a top
chemist who advises major companies such as McDonald's and Sainsbury's
on implementing Government regulations and guidelines on food hygiene,
gave evidence.
He was critical of the council's attitude that all forms of listeria
posed a health risk and should be barred from sale.
The court has heard that there was no recorded case that the
particular strain of listeria found in the cheese had caused illness in
people.
The case is expected to conclude today but QCs for the council and Mr
Errington will make legal submissions to the sheriff at a later date.
</TEXT>
