<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother'son, Pleasance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXPLOITING the cloying, vicious potential of a mother-son bond gone
wrong, this is a harrowing portrayal of the most dismal dysfunctional
family, a relationship so soured that it has to be fated, and which does
indeed come to a particularly nasty conclusion.
A brittle, brilliant script by Raymond J Barry careens through a
myriad of themes, constantly hurling disparate and distressing images at
the audience. Lines are delivered at breakneck speed and simultaneously,
and the cast's command of them is no small accomplishment.
Pitched at a consistent hysterical level, it induces the strongest of
responses and that the most predominant one is revulsion is merely an
indication of the play's accomplishment, successfully planting sinister
seeds in  the most innocent of lines which flower into full-scale
horror. Horrible and perverted, this is breathtaking theatre.
</TEXT>
