<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Launch of a new era in off shore technology</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ferrol, Spain
THE centrepiece of a giant #250m jigsaw which, when complete, will
bring ashore the first oil from the new west of Shetland province, slid
into the waters of northern Spain yesterday.
As 14,500 tonnes of steel eased down the slipway of the Astana yard
into Ferrol Bay, it marked a milestone in the development of the UK's
newest oil frontier more than 20 years after it was first discovered.
The launch of the middle section of the Petrogarl Foinaven is the
first tangible sign that the technology that was not available to
exploit the new Atlantic province when it was first found has now
arrived.
The floating production, storage, and offshore loading facility (FPSO)
is a unique engineering project. On completion, the Petrogarl Foinaven
will be part ship, part crude oil and gas processing plant, and part
storage unit.
The former Russian submarine support vessel Anadyr has been cut in
three in the Astana yard in Ferrol, the birthplace of General Franco.
Its mid-section has been removed and will be replaced by a new hi-tech
section, including a turret which will be anchored to the sea bed by 10
massive chains and around which the vessel will rotate to enable it to
withstand Atlantic storms that could include 30-metre waves.
The turret, the most challenging of its kind yet to be built in
Britain, was constructed at the McDermott yard at Ardersier.
''This was a first for the north-east of Scotland and the first turret
of this complexity to be built in the UK and I would like to acknowledge
their courage in taking that job on,'' said Mr Colin Maclean, BP's asset
manager for the Atlantic province.
The mid-section is now constructed and, following the launch, work
will start to weld it to the modified bow and stern sections of the
former Anadyr.
When that work is done, the jigsaw will be completed by fitting 18
modules of vital equipment, weighing almost 4000 tonnes, on the top.
The average time for a North Sea project from discovery of a field to
the production of first oil is around nine years, but Foinaven is on
schedule to cut that by almost two-thirds.
Mr Maclean said the plan had been to complete the project at a rate
which would ''stun'' the industry.
It is actually less than 10 months since the go-ahead was given for
the #750m project and it is already 70% complete.
The Petrogarl Foinaven will be operated by its owners, Golar-Nor
Offshore, experts in FPSOs, and it will produce around 200 million
barrels of Foinaven's reserves.
Mr Joe Leghorn, BP's Foinaven project manager, described it as ''an
unprecedented achievement in a new frontier''. New subsea technology has
had to be developed for the field because the water depth is 500 metres
and the sea bed is beyond the reach of divers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pushing for real equality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRACE FRANKLIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Grace Franklin joins a powerful lobby of 30,000 women in Beijing.
MORE than 200 women who travelled by train for eight days to attend
the United Nations Fourth World Conference on Women, arrived in Beijing
yesterday.
They included women from several emerging countries in Central and
Eastern Europe --Albania among them. The journey was supported by
various nations including the UK, Ireland and Canada.
The British Council was also a sponsoring organisation and the UN
Development Programme was behind the idea and provided the bulk of the
funding. Those who set off from Warsaw, included academics and activists
who took time to discuss issues on the agenda of the Beijing conference.
They also prepared for the UN Forum for Women which precedes the UN
government conference to be staged from Monday to Sept 15.
Among the band of train travellers was Vanessa Vadin, daughter of Jane
Fonda. Vanessa, who filmed the journey, said: ''We thought eight days
and nights on a train would be difficult. But we ended up wanting to
spend another two days at least, just to talk.''
An activist in her own right, Vanessa said: ''I found the experience
heartwarming. At every stop we were met with official receptions. Women,
in particular, gave us bread, often still warm from the oven.
''This is symbolic. Not only does it show warmth, friendship and
hospitality, it illustrates women giving each other sustenance. They
were saying 'take our message to Beijing'.''
The message being brought by the 30,000 women who have descended on
China from around the world is that they want action on promises of
equality development and peace made to women.
Since China has discreetly placed the forum in the pretty lakeside
country town of Huairou, a good half hour's journey from Beijing where
the formal government conference is sited, the women will have a more
difficult time lobbying for the actions they want included in the final
document.
Most delegates agree the UN conference is being used by the big powers
as a pawn in their game. This preliminary forum is where
non-governmental organisations get together to lobby the government
conference and try to change the wording of the vital document it
produces.
From today till September 8, the monstrous regiment of women milling
around this hastily enlarged town, will ''Look at the world through
women's eyes''. What they see already of China is to the liking of some
and not too impressive to others.
At the official registration centre passes were issued with Chinese
administrative thoroughness -- a long line of clerks each requiring a
different bit of paper on which to log some new nugget of information.
There followed a scuffle for shuttle buses to transport lucky pass
holders to their digs.
Since another long line of paper pushers had to be satisfied before
accommodation was allocated, and since this task was done out in the
open in the heat of the day, some of the women who had already been
travelling for days from places such as Kenya were more than tired.
Many of the black and Asian women have already been treated with less
than the standard Chinese courtesy -- sent on the wrong buses or given
more expensive accommodation. But if there is latent racism, the forum
women will soon root it out.
While these first few days are for settling-in and locating the
essentials such as food, toilets and meeting places, they also set the
scene in a fundamental way. For smiles at this stage can reduce tension
and tantrums later when everyone's minds are fixed firmly on the words
which will be haggled over with governments to ensure women's peace and
equality become realities.
NGO forums at each of the three previous World Conference on Women --
in Mexico, Copenhagen and Nairobi -- have served as rallying points for
women worldwide, and have seen the beginnings of important women's
networks and organisations.
Huairou could be the reinforcement of this -- with a little help from
Scotland. Because a tapestry woven by women on Arran wilI be displayed
at the today's opening along with several hundred other works of art
from around the world. And a display of Scottish country dancing should
take place if the taped music can be retrieved from luggage lost by Air
France.
Diplomatically, China has nothing to do with that -- so it still puts
smiles on the faces of its curious visitors. That is, until the music
starts in earnest and the words become fundamental stepping stones on
the road to a better future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vital role of the spy in the sky</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE, DEFENCE CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634063</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Following the crash yesterday of a secret plane, Defence Correspondent
Ian Bruce discusses the U2's history.
THE U2 spy plane is a veteran warhorse which first flew in 1954 as
part of a frantic American programme to keep tabs on Soviet missile
development and deployment as the Cold War threatened to turn hot at any
moment. Over the next four decades, the aircraft, little more than a
high-speed glider, mounted hundreds of deep penetration missions into
the USSR. One in five of the early sorties had RAF pilots at the
controls, often from British bases under US operational control.
Its existence remained a secret until May 1960, when CIA pilot Gary
Powers was shot down by a Soviet missile over the Urals and captured
before he had a chance to destroy his aircraft or its surveillance
equipment. Soviet leader Nikita Kruschev laid on a show trial and
succeeded in embarrassing Washington internationally.
Less well known is the fact that the CIA established its first U2 base
at RAF Lakenheath in 1956 and struck a clandestine deal with the British
which meant that authorisation for spy flights was effectively removed
from US government control.
If the US President of the day vetoed a mission, the CIA could turn to
the Prime Minister to circumvent the problem. Since the RAF and the
Secret Intelligence Service were so closely involved, Premiers such as
Sir Anthony Eden and Harold Macmillan often sanctioned the flights and
assigned RAF personnel to the task.
The USSR's growing stockpile of atomic weapons meant that the Western
nuclear powers desperately needed targeting information for their own
strike forces to counter the threat. The U2 provided the solution until
the 1960 shoot-down demonstrated its vulnerability to modern
high-altitude missiles. But even that incident failed to halt spy
flights.
U2 detachments were established at Incirlik in Turkey, Bodo in Norway,
Wiesbaden in West Germany, and at Atsugi in Japan. All of its pilots
were ostensibly civilians employed by the Lockheed Aircraft Corporation.
All were, in fact, employed by the CIA, including the RAF crews on
attachment. One RAF pilot, Squadron Leader Christopher Walker, was
killed on a training mission in Texas in 1958.
Apart from the Powers incident, the US, Britain, and the USSR waged a
largely secret intelligence war. More than 30 US aircraft were lost on
such missions and 140 crewmen killed in clashes which went largely
unreported.
They were the unsung casualties of a Cold War fought over barren
mountain ranges and icy seas as each side probed its opponents'
defences.
And it was not one-sided. Between 1962 and 1964 alone, there were more
than 90 Soviet incursions into West German air space.
By the mid-1960s, the U2 had outlived its survivability over
heavily-defended Soviet territory. However, it continued to provide
photographic intelligence over much of Eastern Europe, the Middle East,
and Cuba. U2 overflights provided the first definitive evidence of a
Soviet missile build-up on the island in 1962, bringing the world to the
brink of nuclear holocaust.
For eight days, the US and the USSR stood toe to toe. Soviet warships
headed for the Caribbean, escorting missile transports. The US Navy drew
a symbolic line in the sea and warned Moscow to cross it at its peril.
President Kennedy put the U2 still shots of missile launchers before
the UN and called Kruschev's bluff. The Soviets backed down at the last
moment. As one senior American politician remarked: ''We were eyeball to
eyeball and the other guy just blinked.''
The technological explosion of the late sixties and early seventies
reduced the U2 to second-line service as surveillance satellites were
developed. But these had, and still have, serious limitations.
It is possible to photograph with perfect clarity an object a few
inches across from 30,000 miles above the earth. The trick is to have a
satellite in orbit over the desired area at the crucial time.
Satellites also have a limited lifespan of between a few days and a
few months and an even more limited stock of fuel for manoeuvring in
space to attain a new orbit. More importantly, they can carry only so
much film to be ejected over pre-arranged points for collection.
Given the profusion of world flashpoints, the need for definitive,
reliable photographic intelligence at short notice remains vital to all
major powers. A range of supersonic spy planes such as Lockheed's SR71s
Blackbird and the ultra-secret Aurora are still on the US military
inventory.
Unmanned vehicles were thought to be the perfect answer to the
reconnaissance dilemma as anti-aircraft weaponry has steadily improved.
One of the latest US models, the Predator, is the equivalent of a very
large model aircraft equipped with high-resolution video and stills
cameras for battlefield surveillance.
The Predator's controller sits at a video arcade-style console up to
500 miles away and steers the craft over the target area with a
joystick, filming chosen items or key positions in perfect personal
safety.
No pilot equates with no high-propaganda-value hostage or embarrassing
body-bag. And unlike the F16 rescue mission launched earlier this year
in Bosnia, its loss in action does not require a 40-aircraft effort to
remedy.
Five of these were deployed secretly to Gjader air base in Albania
last month to provide targeting and reconnaissance information for Nato
warplanes over Bosnia. Two have been lost in recent weeks and further
missions have been cancelled in the meantime.
The USAF refuses to say whether the still-experimental Predators were
shot down or succumbed to mechanical failure, but it is understood that
at least one was given a self-destruct signal to prevent its
state-of-the-art sensors falling into Serb hands.
That was the prime reason for authorisation of yesterday's manned U2
flight to pinpoint certain batteries around Sarajevo in preparation for
possible Nato airstrikes in retaliation for the latest Serb atrocity in
that besieged city.
The U2 which crashed at RAF Fairford belonged to the USAF 9th
Strategic Reconnaissance Wing, normally based at Beale in California.
The squadron's specialist role is precision location of targets.
RAF Fairford itself, ostensibly mothballed since the withdrawal of
major US air forces from the UK, is no stranger to ''black'' operations.
As a former home to aircraft of the US Strategic Air Command, it now
leads a shadowy existence as sometime host to US spy missions worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
