<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anne Johnstone profiles the organisations which represent many diverse strands of commercial concern. Competing voices of Scots firms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE JOHNSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHO speaks for Scottish business? It's one of those questions being
kicked around on the chat shows this week in the wake of Lex Gold's
decision to vacate his desk at CBI Scotland.
Ever since the tragically premature demise of John Davidson, the CBI
seems to have been struggling north of the Border.
Gold, along with chairman, IBM's John Ward, have made something of a
comeback with their manufacturing initiative and the well thought-out
Scottish Business Agenda but too often callers seeking a CBI comment are
referred to Centrepoint, the organisation's all-powerful UK
headquarters.
In particular, the CBI has failed to produce more than a negative
knee-jerk response to the prospect of devolution, failing to reflect the
mosaic of Scottish business opinion on this subject.
Is this because the CBI lacks a proper Scottish voice? Yes, says
Hamish Morrison, of the Scottish Council Development &amp; Industry: ''The
CBI is essentially a British organisation. If devolution comes, they can
just walk away. We can't.''
But the Scottish Council too had its problems, its functions largely
usurped by other agencies and organisations. The Institute of Directors
is, like the CBI, a national organisation.
The Federation of Small Businesses and the Forum of Private Business
have both campaigned vigorously on some Scottish issues but lack the
resources of the big city-based Chambers of Commerce.
The chambers are attempting to come together a speak for the whole of
Scottish business via their Association of Scottish Chambers of
Commerce, challenging CBI Scotland as the voice of Scottish business.
The question remains as to whether they can bury past arguments over
issues such as infrastructure investment.
Perhaps the whole question is a futile one. After all, can one really
expect a one-man ice cream business to share the same perspective as
ScottishPower? So, though at first the business of representing Scottish
business seems rather overcrowded, thoughtful observers believe we need
their several and sometimes contradictory voices because of the subtly
different constituencies they represent. Here's a brief run-down of the
six main ones:
* CBI Scotland -- Director: Lex Gold (until later this year).
Based in Glasgow, CBI Scotland speaks mostly for Scotland's large and
multinational companies. The confederation is strongly centralised. The
Scottish office with its director and five assistant directors
(including two secondees) is answerable to the British headquarters with
200 staff at the notorious Centrepoint building in London.
Supporters of this structure say the size and strength of the UK
operation enables it to tackle key areas of policy in depth and pack a
powerful punch with Government. Detractors say it has prevented the CBI
from developing and articulating a distinctive Scottish voice on such
issues as devolution.
In the past the CBI has tended to be strongly identified with the
Conservatives. However, at both Scottish and UK level the CBI has been
critical of some Government policy recently. CBI Scotland's Scottish
Business Agenda attracted support from right across the political
spectrum. The CBI's Brussels office and its membership of UNICE (the
European Employers' Federation) gives it a voice in Europe.
* Association of Scottish Chambers of Commerce -- Director General:
Charles Winter, absent throughillness. Acting DG: Peter Dunn, a past
president of Fife Chamber of Commerce.
Based in the Edinburgh Chamber of Commerce, the Association is trying
to build its reputation as a voice for Scottish business. Chambers are
strongly localised and members are mostly small and medium-sized
businesses. City branches are strongly associated with retailing and
many have long histories. Glasgow's was founded in 1783.
Some question whether the chambers are sufficiently united to speak
with a single voice. In the past there have been numerous inter-chamber
disputes, eg over airport policy. Because they can't support themselves
on membership fees alone, Chambers of Commerce are attempting to sell to
the business communities an ever-expanding range of services, eg export
advice, personnel training and information services.
They would like to make themselves more powerful and indispensable by
remodelling themselves on the French and German models. There it is
compulsory to register a business with the local chamber of commerce.
But this is fiercely opposed by other business organisations who believe
it would give the chambers too much power.
* Scottish Office of the Federation of Small Businesses -- Federation
Scottish Secretary: Bill Anderson.
Known affectionately as ''The Federation of Small Bills,'' after its
vertically challenged but energetic director, it changed its name from
the Federation of Self-Employed Businessmen. Part of a branch network
with 70,000 members all over Britain, it is both a lobbying organisation
but also offers a range of services to members, including free legal and
tax advice. The federation has campaigned on a number of Scottish issues
including rail services and the uniform business rate. Attended the
Scottish Consitutional Convention on the basis that Scottish business
should be represented at such gatherings if the business community is to
have a voice in the devolution debate.
* The Forum of Private Business -- Scottish spokesman: Jim Gorie.
Based in the Helensburgh home of its spokesman, the forum is part of a
UK network founded in 1977 and based on a similar business organisation
in the US which boasts over 1,000,000 members. It is purely a lobbying
organisation, entirely dependent on subscriptions and regularly consults
its 23,000 UK members on a range of issues via quarterly surveys and
referenda. Copies of replies go to local MPs.
The forum has recently mounted a vigorous campaign against late
payment. Gorie complains that since John Davidson sad demise, CBI
Scotland has become ineffective -- ''a small tail on the Centrepoint
dog.'' The Forum has criticised the CBI and he Chambers of Commerce for
''a lack of hard thinking on the impact of either devolution or the
changes in Europe''.
* The Scottish Office of the Institute of Directors -- Director:
Donald Hardie.
A small two-person office based in Edinburgh, with six area committees
which arrange social and educational programmes around the country for
individual directors and partners in professional firms. For example,
the Dundee branch's autumn programme includes a dinner with Lord
Parkinson amd a visit to the Highland Spring plant.
The IOD, with its plush offices in Pall Mall, is influential at the UK
level but has a low profile in Scotland, though it supported the
campaign against late payment. One observer described its input as
''gentlemanly and reflective''. A muted voice.
* The Scottish Council Development &amp; Industry -- Chief Executive:
Hamish Morrison.
Illustrious past, including the organisation of the 1938 Empire
Exhibition, but the Council has fallen on hard times recently as other
business organisations have nibbled away at their patch. They used to
have a brief for attracting inward investment until this was taken away
by the Scottish Development Agency.
They still deal with stimulating exports but this function is
threatened by the emergence of the Scottish Trade International arm of
Scottish Enterprise. Still employ 32 paid staff in Edinburgh and
Glasgow.
Morrison claims the council is different from other organisations
because of the involvement of the unions and local authorities. ''We
speak for economic development, rather than business per se,'' he says.
This gives them a distinctive voice on, for example, employment. As an
all-Scottish organisation the council can and does express views on
Anglo-Scottish issues, such as the ScottishPower bid for ManWeb, while
the CBI and other hover on the sidelines.
The council organises what is still probably the most important annual
conference for Scottish businessmen, the Scottish Forum at Gleneagles
Hotel, though these days top people tend to send their corporate affairs
directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
