<DOCNO>GH950830-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shelter's lost housing claim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH,LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT cuts in housing investment over the last six years have
deprived Scotland of 21,000 houses, according to Shelter Scotland.
The housing charity said yesterday that this investment had declined
in real terms by 26% since 1989. Over the next two years, further cuts
of 11% were planned by the Scottish Office.
Mr Gavin Corbett, Shelter's research and information officer, said
housing had suffered more than any other part of public spending. If
funding had remained at 1989 levels, Shelter estimated that the
additional 21,000 homes could have been built.
Housing had been regarded as a soft target and this was ''indefensible
and shortsighted'', he claimed.
The message was clear: housing had suffered enough. Cuts meant
homelessness, investment meant homes and jobs.
A Scottish Office spokeswoman said the Government had to balance the
demand with what could be afforded, taking account of competing demands
on the public purse such as health and education.
A total of 300,000 new dwellings had been built since 1979, about
220,000 of them by the private sector, and there had been record numbers
of private sector house completions in both 1993 and 1994.
</TEXT>
