<DOCNO>GH950830-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Zaire halts Rwandan expulsions. Refugees fear death on return after sacking of Hutu Ministers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIF KABAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634067</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Goma, Zaire
ZAIRE today gave the UN refugee agency four months to send home the
1000,000 Rwandan Hutus on its soil, backing away from its threat of
immediate expulsions.
Zairean Prime Minister Kengo wa Dondo said after Geneva talks with UN
High Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata that Zaire would assess
progress monthly and retain the right to deport refugees left behind at
the start of 1996.
Tension in the Rwandan government came to a head with the sackings of
four Ministers said to be opposed to the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic
Army (RPA) plans to put soldiers on committees overseeing the return of
refugees from Zaire.
Parliament sacked Justice Minister Alphonse Nkubito, Interior Minister
Seth Sendashonga, Information Minister Jean-Baptiste Nkuriyingoma, and
Transport and Telecommunication Minister Imaculee Kayumba over the
dispute.
Yesterday moderate Hutu premier Faustin Twagiramungu was sacked for
alleged incompetence. His departure sowed more terror among refugees
fearing reprisals at the hands of the RPA for last year's genocide of up
to 1000,000 Tutsis and allied Hutus.
Three of the sacked Ministers are Hutus. Although their successors
have yet to be named, their departure is certain to play into the hands
of Hutu extremists in refugee camps eager to portray the Rwandan
government as anti-Hutu, diplomats said.
The peaceful return of Hutu refugees to Rwanda is critical to the
credibility of the Tutsi-led government. The international community has
promised further aid to the government depending on its track record on
refugees.
Zaire's decision has eased the pressure on the UNHCR, giving it until
the end of the year to repatriate the Rwandan refugees voluntarily.
''Repatriation must be en masse, without interruption and end by
December 31, 1995 at the latest. In case . . . repatriation is delayed
beyond December 31, Zaire reserves the right to make the refugees leave
its territory,'' Mr wa Dondo told a news conference after talks in
Geneva today.
In the Zairean border town of Goma, UNHCR spokesman Chris Bowers said
UNHCR would do its best to escort the refugees home but it could not
commit itself to a rigid deadline.
''We will mobilise all possible resources in the region and do all we
can to send refugees back, but we cannot commit ourselves to
deadlines,'' he said.
Mr Patrick de Souza, UNHCR's chief in Bukavu, said today's decision in
Geneva would give a further sense of urgency to the return of refugees
and an impetus to find a solution to their problems.
''It gives an understanding that it is safer to return voluntarily
with UNHCR rather than be forced out by the Zairean government and we
hope we can implement the return,'' he said.
Zaire suspended the expulsions last Thursday after throwing 15,000
Rwandan and Burundian refugees out but five days of UN voluntary
repatriation has sent home fewer than 400 refugees.
General Ian Douglas, the Canadian commander of UN-paid Zairean forces
guarding refugee camps, said the international community must back
initiatives to get repatriation going.
''There's a lot of combined joint work to be done if now we've got
until the end of the year. They (Zaireans) have made it clear that's
probably as long as we've got,'' he said.
He added that bases of the former Rwandan military where Hutu
militants have been spreading terror stories about refugees being
slaughtered on their return to Rwanda had to be closed.
In camps near Goma, however, refugees vowed never to go back and
recounted tales of Hutus returning to Rwanda having their eyes scooped
out or being choked to death.
Only 22 refugees out of 150,000 in Mugunga went home today
voluntarily. UN trucks also went to camps in the Bukavu region but no
refugees boarded them.
Refugees said the dismissal of Rwanda's Prime Minister and the four
Ministers was proof that Hutus were not wanted.-- Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
