<DOCNO>GH950830-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Women's 'alienation' in the Church</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634068</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Scots theologian yesterday claimed there was still a huge
way to go in overcoming the ''sense of alienation'' which was
articulated so forcefully by the Christian feminist voice.
Mrs Elizabeth Templeton, a member of the Church of Scotland, was
speaking on the second day of the European Area Council meeting of World
Alliance of Reformed Churches in Edinburgh.
She told the meeting the very existence of a day where there was a
split agenda for men and women delegates had been a cause of
''heartsearching, controversy, and some pain''.
Mrs Templeton said she was not convinced there were any interesting
topics which were women's issues but not men's issues, or vice versa.
''In spite of the Decade of Solidarity with Women, or maybe even
because of it, I find that a great deal of the explicit discussion of
'women's issues' happens with a measure of male cynicism and distrust.''
She said she had overheard conversations where men talked with relief
about having got through sessions to do with women's agendas and there
was a ''dismissive and even contemptuous'' feeling.
She had also been present at women's groups where there was a
triumphalist atmosphere of working on their own without ''these
power-crazed autocratic men''.
''Both of these stances seem to me shameful and sub-Christian,'' she
said.
The theologian said that quite apart from the tactical, practical
question of what the outcome was likely to be if separate agendas
continued to be encouraged, it was inappropriate as a theological
symbol.
''I am sure that graceful co-existence must transcend the kind of
self-consciousness which bedevils so much of the relationships between
men and women, especially when we meet to discuss gender issues,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
