<DOCNO>GH950830-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquiry is ordered into direct services operation. Council officials removed from jobs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Orkney council official has been made redundant and another
suspended as the authority yesterday announced an investigation into the
operation of its direct services organisation.
The islands council refused to say whether or not other redundancies,
suspensions, or dismissals were pending but a senior councillor warned
that the authority would be ruthless if the investigation unearthed any
wrong-doing.
It is understood that the official made redundant is Mr John Drew,
manager of the DSO.
It is believed the officer suspended pending the outcome of the
investigation is senior sewerage department engineer Peter Armstrong.
However, a council spokesman refused to confirm the redundancy and
suspension. ''The council is unable to comment on staff matters such as
the reasons behind suspensions, redundancies, and dismissals,'' he said.
Earlier this month, the council did confirm that builders from the DSO
wearing council overalls had been seen working on Mr Armstrong's home in
Evie.
At that time, the council spokesman said the authority was satisfied
there was nothing improper about the arrangement.
It was a private arrangement between Mr Armstrong and the men, who
were not doing the work in the council's time, said the spokesman.
Yesterday, the council issued a short statement announcing that an
inquiry was under way.
''Orkney Islands Council has confirmed that it is currently conducting
an internal investigation into a number of matters relating to the
operation of its direct services organisation and the difficulties
within the DSO which have already been well publicised,'' it said.
''Until such times as this investigation is concluded, it is not
possible for the council to discuss this matter further, particularly in
relation to the individuals concerned.''
The spokesman refused to say whether or not the well-publicised
difficulties included Mr Armstrong's use of DSO builders at his home.
But he said: ''There has been no disciplinary action to date in
connection with that matter.''
The findings of the inquiry will be reported to the contract services
committee.
Chairman Eoin Scott said yesterday: ''Substantial inquiries are
proceeding. The committee are all of the opinion that we will be quite
ruthless if -- and I emphasise if -- any impropriety is found.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
