<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Political row deepens over sell-off of Ayrshire homes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634074</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE political row over the
the transfer of houses from Irvine Development Corporation to a
housing assocation which it helped to set up deepened yesterday.
The corporation announced that it had sold the first batch of 285
houses to Irvine Housing Association for more than #2.5m. Local MP Brian
Donohoe dismissed the move as a ''black day for Irvine'' while the
corporation's managing director described it as ''good news for tenants
now and in the future''.
Mr Donohoe, MP for Cunninghame South, has campaigned against the
transfer of houses to the association, which he has described as a front
for unwelcome and unacceptable Tory housing policies.
For several months,the corporation and the association, which is now
independent, having been assisted in the early stages,have been
negotiating over the transfer of 769 houses,which is expected to take
place by next spring.
The development corporation will be wound up by early 1997 and its
industrial stock has already moved into private control. Tenants in the
corporation's 3500 houses will be asked next year to choose a new
landlord in a ballot.
With the withdrawal of two outside housing agencies, the choice is
expected to be between Cunninghame District Council and Irvine Housing
Association.
Mr Jack Murdoch, managing director of Irvine Development Corporation,
said: ''I am surprised and disappointed at Mr Donohoe's continuing
criticism of our involvement with Irvine Housing Association. We have
made no secret of the fact that, in order to make the association a
viable choice for tenants, it must have housing stock and show that it
can manage that stock.
''We were told by independent consultants from the outset that it
would be preferable to have a local housing association created rather
than have associations from outside in the ballot.''
''For that reason, we helped the association to get started and are
now involved in an exercise to transfer housing to them in time for the
ballot. I believe the tenants will get the same kind of high standard of
service under the association that they have enjoyed for many years
under the corporation.'' Mr Donohoe responded:''I find it despicable
that the corporation is embarking on this naked attempt to give this
housing association some kind of kudos in the housing market and to
pretend that it will have some kind of experience and business acumen.
''I am also concerned at the low prices which these houses are going
for -- under #9000 each -- as there is no guarantee that they will not
ultimately be sold on at greatly inflated prices.''
Mr Donohoe wants a Commons debate this autumn on the whole question of
housing ballots and will call on Scottish Office Ministers to come clean
on the controversial practice.
He added: ''I believe that Raymond Robertson and his Scottish Office
cronies should be held personally responsible for this fiasco and should
be surcharged to make up for what could be a huge waste of money.''
Mr Murdoch said: ''If Mr Donohoe had any idea about how the price of
these houses is worked out, he would realise that it is not based on the
market value but on a formula based on the projected rental and costs on
the property.''
Housing association chairman Ms Jeanette Mason said: ''As we have now
bought our first houses, we will give the people who live in them a
service which cannot be bettered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monster catch by the water bailiffs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WATER bailiffs yesterday described a huge net they dragged from a busy
harbour as a ''death trap''.
They said the poachers' net could have cost the life of a swimmer.
The bailiffs in Ayr are now hunting those responsible.
The poachers fled while laying the net, the largest found on the west
coast, after they were spotted by bailiffs on routine night patrol.
''This thing was incredible,'' said Mr Robert McFarlane, of Ayr
District Salmon Fishery Board. He said it was 350ft by 12ft, making it
longer ''than Hampden football pitch''.
He added: ''Anything that got entangled in it just wouldn't have stood
a chance. It could easily have stopped a boat for instance if its
propeller had became jammed in the mesh.
''Basically we just couldn't believe anyone would be so stupid as to
lay something like this in a busy harbour.''
Bailiffs believe poachers laid the trap to ensnare salmon which were
moving upstream to spawn.
Only one fish was found when it was hauled ashore.
''Luckily we got the net out before any real damage was done,'' said
Mr McFarlane. ''But I hate to think of the possible disaster it could
have caused had it been left there overnight or longer.''
A board spokesman said anyone caught poaching in this manner could be
fined up to #2500 or face a lengthy jail term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Children's Act 'ready for new councils'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BROAD hint that the Children (Scotland) Act 1995 -- which received
Royal Assent in July -- will be operational as close as possible to
inauguration of the new single-tier authorities was given in Glasgow
yesterday by Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, Minister of State at the
Scottish Office.
Lord James avoided giving a precise date for implementation but told a
Children In Scotland conference on the Act that it would be introduced
''without undue delay'' while undertaking to consult with those agencies
involved in its implementation.
He added that speedy and positive contributions on implementation
would enable all involved to ''realise the opportunity offered by the
new Act and a new system of local government to introduce a new era of
child law and services for the benefit of Scotland's children''.
Lord James also announced the publication of a guide to the Act which
would set out clearly the themes and principles running through it and
the provision for responsibilities, rights, duties, and powers which it
contains.
He said he hoped it would prove particularly helpful to the members of
the new councils as they took on their social work responsibilities.
Both the Minister and Mrs Maria Fyfe MP, Labour spokeswoman on social
work in Scotland, paid tribute to the unique all-party support for the
child-centred principle of the Bill. This speeded its passage through
the legislative process but Mrs Fyfe argued that further improvements
should still be sought.
Among them should be clarification of the question of physical
punishment of children and of the rights of single mothers, she said.
Mrs Fyfe welcomed the right of children to have their views considered
when major decisions were taken about their lives and the possibility of
excluding certain individuals from a children's hearing, which she
described as ''a great advance for children who have been abused''.
She also welcomed ''the radical step of creating exclusion orders,
including emergency orders, so that an alleged abuser may be removed
from the family home rather than the child''.
Lord James added that the Act placed increased emphasis on the rights
and responsibilities of parents even after separation and divorce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joke misfires</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOUSTON: Police and sniffer dogs searched a Southwest Airlines jet
yesterday after a woman told a ticket agent at Houston's Hobby airport
that she was carrying guns, hand grenades, and a bomb. The woman, who
was taken into custody for questioning, said it had been a joke, but the
74 other passengers were placed on later flights.
* Flights in and out of New York City's three area airports were
halted for over an hour on Monday night after a bomb threat was phoned
in to an air traffic control centre. No bomb was found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Author dies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIAMI: British historian and author John Costello, 52, has died on a
British Airways flight from London to his home in Miami. Mr Costello,
whose books included a history of Soviet spying and an account of Rudolf
Hess's futile flight to Scotland to lay out a wartime peace plan, had
been researching a book about the friendship of Winston Churchill and
Franklin Roosevelt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aids alert</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON: A new study claims that commonly-used dental and medical
devices can pass on infectious diseases ranging from the common cold to
the Aids virus. Microbiologists say infections can be transmitted by
contaminated lubricants and urge wider compliance with heat
sterilisation guidelines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why wave power is all at sea</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEORGE HUME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
George Hume on the market forces hampering research into clean-energy
wave power.
THE leader of an internationally-acclaimed Scottish research team says
government parsimony and market forces dogma are pushing the successful
delivery of renewable energy from wave power far into the next century.
Professor Stephen Salter of Edinburgh University, who has had a senior
member of his team poached by Japanese industry because there is no
money to pay him, says it could be as long as 40 years before wave power
is established in this country -- and then only after all reserves of
natural gas have been exhausted.
Wave-power research began in Britain 22 years ago, received Government
funding for only eight years, and has only recently won financial
support from the EC. But, according to Professor Salter, wave power,
properly exploited, could meet Britain's entire domestic and industrial
energy needs.
''The Government's policy is to have no policy and to let market
forces have their way. The market, of course, prefers to do what it can
do immediately and that is burn gas,'' he says.
Projected costs for wave power, however, are high -- pointing to bills
at least twice the target level. ''We will just have to be twice as
clever, see rougher seas -- which we have in recent years, or have the
cost of gas go up,'' says Professor Salter.
The energy crisis of 1973, brought about by the Yom Kippur War in the
Middle East, saw the start of wave-power research in Britain. Government
funding -- ''steady and adequate,'' according to Professor Salter -- ran
from the following year until 1982 and then dried up.
Over the years Government support amounted to #17m and covered
research into 12 devices. The Department of Trade and Industry now makes
no contribution to the research programmes that continue . . . one of
them on Islay. The device, developed by academics in Belfast, has so far
survived several heavy winters.
Not until three years ago did the EC put up funds after the admission
to the European Union of Spain, Portugal and Ireland -- countries which
considerably enlarged the European coastline and the scope for wave
energy generation. Portugal was at the fore in pressing for financial
support.
''We have had eight years of proper funding from the Government and,
prior to the EC money, 12 years of fiddling to keep wave-energy research
alive,'' said Professor Salter who claims, however, not to be
despondent.
''Frank Whittle invented the jet engine in 1929 but the first Boeing
707 did not carry passengers until 1959. These things take time. But
there is no doubt that wave-energy research is poorly co-ordinated and
spasmodic although it is moving.''
EC funding for wave-energy research at Edinburgh University amounts to
800,000 ECUs -- about #660,000 -- which is currently being employed on
the development and production of a variable pitch turbine that will be
fitted towards the end of the century in a Portuguese wave research
development in the Azores.
Wave-energy research is being carried out in a number of countries
outside Europe -- including China, India, and Japan.
Britain's natural gas reserves are estimated at around 15 years at
present levels of consumption, with the prospect of a further 10 years
worth being found in the waters west of Shetland. Thereafter supplies
would most likely have to be bought in from Algeria and states formerly
in the Soviet Union -- current political instability in these countries
puts a question mark on the future reliability of supply.
''Our present policy is to burn gas as fast as we can -- something
only a maniac or a marketeer would do. It is extremely difficult for
renewable energies to compete with fossil fuels -- after all, one only
has to burn them,'' says Professor Salter.
''Only when the gas is exhausted in maybe 20, 30, or 40 years time
will renewable wave energy come into its own. We should be doing the
research now ahead of the need. Wave-energy research in laboratory is
very cheap, and the three on my team deliver very high value.
''Wave energy is big, renewable, in no-one's way and without pollution
-- a prize well worth putting in a tiny amount of money for. But here we
have market forces, what can be done immediately with no thought for the
future,'' he says.
According to research figures wave energy from 10km of sea-front can
produce the equivalent output of a large power station. With 900km of
coastline round Britain, sufficient energy could, it is claimed, be won
from wave power to meet the country's total demand.
A scheme is already on the drawing board that envisages wave-energy
generators running from Cape Wrath to Valencia in Spain -- broken only
by sea lanes for shipping. The possibility of wave-energy generation as
far north as Iceland -- a submarine cable being used to bring the
electricity to Britain -- is also being considered.
Osprey, which sank off Dounreay in hurricane force winds at the
weekend is involved with Edinburgh University in the production of the
variable pitch turbine that will be fitted to the Portuguese wave
station in the Azores.
The site for the #4m Osprey, launched on the Clyde at the start of
this month, was chosen because of the power of the waves in the Pentland
Firth. It was expected to be able to feed 275kw in the national grid.
''(It was) a public relations disaster and everyone in the wave
community is extremely embarrassed,'' said Professor Salter. ''But it
was not the waves that upset it -- rather something to do with
seamanship or at the yard, and I have been told that until it went down
everything was working well. It will go again and we have learned
lessons rather quicker, perhaps, than we had planned.''
</TEXT>
