<DOCNO>GH950830-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>School no longer skirts co-ed issue</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCHOOL which opened in 1836 with 10 young ladies on the roll
yesterday welcomed 10 members of the opposite sex to its senior ranks.
Wellington School, in Ayr, is going co-educational officially with the
start of the new session.
Headmistress Dianne Gardner is enthusiastic about the new development:
''There is a strong case for co-education in the modern world. Life
itself is co-educational.''
The move, which follows successful trials in the junior school, brings
the total number of boys at Wellington to 50.
It is one of many changes in the school's world. Mrs Gardner says few
companies are now prepared to meet the boarding school fees of the
families of expatriate executives.
Though she is reluctant to see boarding pupils disappear, she admits
that shrinking numbers, down from 120 in the early 1970s to this year's
22, will require some rethinking: ''We may buy a house and instal a
house mother to run it.''
The co-educational school has no endowments to provide for bursary
places but, of the present roll of just under 400, 40 are to receive
assistance with fees.
</TEXT>
