<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish rural workers and women still losing out on pay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIC OUTTERSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS in Scotland's rural areas earn on average up to #50 per week
less than those on the east coast and #150 less than those in Greater
London, according to a new pay survey.
The report by the Scottish Low Pay Unit also shows that women are
losing the battle to close the pay gap, and the situation has worsened
since the abolition of wages councils.
In a detailed analysis of earnings figures from the Government's New
Earnings Survey, the report says 850,000 workers in Scotland fell below
the unit's low pay threshold.
The survey shows that average weekly earnings among Scottish workers
stands at #300.80, compared with a national average of #325.70, a low of
#291.40 in Wales and a high of #415.50 in Greater London.
However, there also are wide regional variations within Scotland.
Average weekly earnings in Highland are #267.15, in contrast to
#316.20 in Grampian and #298.60 in Lothian.
The highest proportion of men on low pay were in Highland (30%),
Borders (26.3%), and Dumfries and Galloway (25.7%). More than 60% of
women in the same regions earned less than the low pay threshold of
#208.53 per week.
The report also states that 445,000 workers in Scotland would benefit
from the introduction of a minimum wage set at half-median male earnings
(#156.40 per week). Overall, women would account for 78.6% (350,000) of
beneficiaries from a minimum wage.
Ms Morag Gillespie, director of the Scottish Low Pay Unit and author
of the report, said: ''The Government's rationale behind abolishing
wages councils was the belief that low pay was a price worth paying if
more jobs were created.
''Two years on, we see that pay rates are down, and low pay is up, but
where are the jobs?
''There is only one solution to the low-pay crisis, the experts know
it and the public knows it. Britain needs a minimum wage and we need it
now.''
Labour's Scottish employment spokesman, Mr John McFall, MP for
Dumbarton, said the abolition of wages councils was responsible for
driving down wages in sectors where women predominate.
The New Earnings Survey shows that full-time female employees in
Scotland currently earn 72.7% of male earnings, while in
non-professional classes it is nearer 65%.
For 10 years prior to the abolition of wages councils, the pay gap had
hovered around 26% but had now widened in real terms.
Mr McFall accused the Government of being unwilling to close the pay
gap and claimed that current equal pay legislation was inadequate and
too complicated.
''When the Government was forced, in 1981, by the European Commission
to legislate on equal pay for work of equal value, Lord Denning said of
the procedures set up that no ordinary lawyer could understand them,''
he said.
''This has led to the system which encourages employers to engage in
long, drawn-out legal battles. It takes years to get a decision and the
costs can exceed #100,000 -- it is hardly surprising that only around 20
cases are brought each year.''
A second report, published by the Manchester-based Low Pay Network,
shows that nearly 80% of job vacancies formerly covered by wages
councils are now offering poverty pay.
It shows that 78.1% of vacancies in hotel and catering, retail,
clothing manufacture, and hairdressing paid below the amount a family
with two children would receive on Income Support.
About half the full-time jobs and nearly all the part-time jobs in the
study, carried out at 40 Jobcentres around the country, fell into this
category. Nearly 40% paid less than the National Insurance threshold of
#58 a week.
However, Trade and Industry Minister Philip Oppenheim -- who has
responsibility for wages and industrial relations -- hit back, claiming
that wages councils were inflexible to the changing needs of the labour
market and reduced competitiveness.
He said that far from reducing pay levels, wages in sectors formerly
covered by wages councils had risen by 6.3% in real terms since its
abolition in August 1993 and that the Opposition was distorting the
facts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
