<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lifeline offered to a workforce stranded by age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Margaret Vaughan finds mature workers winning support as large
companies launch an initiative to stamp out discrimination.
IT wasn't age that withered her, it was the pile of rejections stacked
higgledy-piggledy on the desk. Thirty-four interviews, 33 letters saying
sorry but . . .
''The other one didn't even bother to tell me I hadn't got the job. I
mean, do I look doddery? Decrepit?'' If it wasn't a rhetorical question,
the answer would be no, no she doesn't. ''But that's how I feel now.''
Cathy is 53. University educated, recently widowed, skills updated,
poised and polished right down to her pale lacquered nails. Ready to
return to the world of paid work. Except that the world of paid work
doesn't seem to want her. She's too old.
Cathy knows her capabilities. Convincing potential employers of them
is something else: ''All I wanted was some secretarial work, to ease me
back into it. Three agencies wouldn't even take me on, and although they
didn't come out and admit it, the implication was quite clear: it's your
age, dear.''
Then there were the interviews she did get: ''If I'd got a facelift
and dyed my hair raven, they'd still have been counting the varicose
veins. And if I sound crabbit, it's because I am now. It's just plain
stupid. When you've run a home and brought up four children, frankly,
you're rather better equipped with organisational skills to run a
company than some of those sitting behind the interviewer's desk. And I
only wanted to type their letters . . .''
Exasperated, even if not undaunted, Cathy has given up. She's applied
for a college place to study business administration.
Archie has been made redundant twice. First time round he lost his job
as an insurance executive. After 14 months of searching, he found a post
with an office furniture retailer. It folded eight months after he
joined. ''I think I was lucky to get the second chance, and I worked
hard at it. I don't suppose I'll get another permanent job now. I'm too
old.''
Archie is 48. He plays golf, potters round the greenhouse, watches
Neighbours at lunchtime. He'd like to sign up for nightclasses in
Italian or landscape painting, but says he finds it hard to concentrate:
''I feel useless. Being out of work is, for me, an unnatural state.
Sometimes it feels as if I was born old.''
Later this year, new legislation comes into force to prevent
discrimination against disabled people at work. It will sit alongside
laws already covering discrimination on grounds of sex and race. Which
will leave people like Cathy and Archie, and probably hundreds of
thousands of others, precisely where they stand now. Stranded on the far
shores of 40 with all the other middle-aged labour-force rejects.
Age will become the only major cause of discrimination not covered by
law. Those who find themselves turfed out of full-time work see hope of
re-employment receding faster than gums and hairlines.
Yesterday, around 100 of the UK's biggest companies -- including
Scottish &amp; Newcastle, Costain, the builders, and the National
Westminster Bank -- agreed to back a new initiative that aims to stop
age discrimination in the recruitment of employees. Drawn up by the
Carnegie Third Age Programme, it has resulted in firms changing their
policies to end age discrimination. The initiative has also won support
from the Prime Minister.
A recent report by the Geneva-based International Labour Organisation
identified the trends which led to structural changes in labour markets
in all industrialised countries.
Since the beginning of the eighties, young people have been encouraged
to stay longer in education while older workers were given incentives to
retire early, so reducing the labour supply at both ends.
As unemployment became more acute, a variety of schemes was introduced
to encourage older workers to retire earlier, offering compensation for
loss of earnings and to bridge the gap until pensions could be claimed.
The rate of decline of participation rates of older workers led to a
substantial lowering of the average retirement age.
In a highly competitive jobs market, older workers, women and young
people are most vulnerable to job loss.
In an aggressive cost-cutting and trimming culture of lean, thrusting
companies the more senior posts were simply too costly. But while it's
true that older workers cost more to employ, was there any reason to
believe their performance and the value of their accumulated knowledge
did not compensate for the higher cost? According to the ILO report, no
studies exist to provide a full cost benefit analysis of the employment
of older workers.
In hierarchical systems, such as the civil service, it is true that
earnings rise until the end of working life. That's not true, though, in
technical professions where salaries are linked to output and the peak
of earnings is in mid-career.
But, given the higher cost of some older workers, companies often
found it cheaper to buy them out, or show them the back door. Studies
into the relative productivity rates of older and younger workers seem
to contradict the prevailing ethos that youth always beats age to do the
best job: the ILO survey showed that in industries which want fast
reflexes, precision and acuity of vision -- say, assembling electronic
parts -- productivity starts to decline between the ages of 20 and 30.
In construction, the prime age is between 30 and 40. In the iron and
steel and car industries between 40 and 50. Studies of skilled and
semi-skilled workers in industries such as printing, knitwear, and
service engineering where performance peaks in the late thirties and
forties have found decline in performance is gradual. So that
productivity of those in their late fifties often still exceeds that of
workers in their teens and early twenties.
The young may work with more speed, but they made more mistakes.
Older workers' productivity rates were found to be similar or better
than those of young individuals in tasks which required sustained
attention, and tasks in which the older workers are highly experienced.
In decision making, they may be slower but that is because they have
more information to process and their decisions are often better.
Empirical research shows that because of longer experience, older
workers find ways to compensate for deficiencies and often still
outperform younger workers.
All studies show that older workers forced to retire, made redundant
or just laid off feel excluded from active society, their health may
suffer and they may become withdrawn and unable to adjust to their new
-- non -- status.
Almost all researchers and policy makers now agree, according to the
ILO, that the early retirement trend has gone too far. A point agreed
upon by the Carnegie Programme's director, Richard Worsley, who said
that companies had begun to think more seriously about the artificial
relationship between age and employment: ''Firms are beginning to
recognise every business needs a good mix of ages in its workforce.''
</TEXT>
