<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Divorced husband must pay #500 a month from pension he will not receive until 2001. Policeman ordered to pay ex-wife</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN,LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634092</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICEMAN has been ordered to pay his former wife #500 a month out
of a pension he is not due to receive until the year 2001.
The court order was made against Mr Derek McEwan, a detective
inspector with Fife Constabulary, despite his plea that he could not
afford to pay.
He argued that the payment should be postponed until he actually
received his pension.
In 1994, Mr McEwan was divorced by his wife, Anne, and Kirkcaldy
Sheriff Gail Patrick found the wife entitled to a capital sum of
#29,780. The figure was made up of half his pension entitlement of
#58,000 and half the value of the family car.
The sheriff ordered immediate payment of #2780 and then had to decide
on how Mr McEwan should meet the balance.
She rejected his argument that a payment of #40,000 (taking interest
into account) should be deferred until the year 2001 when he would be
due his pension on retiring after 30 years' service.
Sheriff Patrick ruled instead that Mr McEwan pay the #27,000 at #500 a
month, with interest on the balance outstanding from month to month at
8% until final payment.
If any single instalment remained unpaid for 14 days the whole
outstanding balance became payable immediately. She gave him a year to
pay the first instalment.
Mr McEwan lost an appeal to the Sheriff Principal and took the case to
three judges in the Court of Session.
Lord Penrose, sitting with Lords Sutherland and Brand, said yesterday
the sole issue was whether Sheriff Patrick had been entitled to order
payment of the #27,000 in the way she had.
The court was told that, at the time of the divorce, Mr McEwan had two
houses. One was in Methil, which he had been unable to sell and which he
now let out.
The other was a house in Leven where he now lived with another woman
and over which there was a #75,000 mortgage.
The court was told that Mr McEwan could not afford to pay the #500 a
month because he had neither capital nor free income to meet a sum of
that amount.
However, Sheriff Patrick considered that there should be capital
available from the sale of one of the houses and from his salary, from
which he could pay the instalements.
Lord Penrose said that while postponing a payment until the pension
became available was an approach that had been adopted in other cases,
it was not one which the sheriff was bound to follow.
The court had a discretion and the sheriff was entitled to reject it
in favour of another competent method. There was nothing to prevent her
opting for payment by instalments to secure for Mrs McEwan the benefits
to which she was entitled.
''The sheriff was clearly entitled to form the view that the move to
Leven had been made in disregard to Mr McEwan's obligations to Mrs
McEwan and that, having another less costly home, there was no reason
why he should not return to it and relieve himself of the burdens
related to the larger house.''
There had also been grounds in the evidence for the sheriff's view
that by taking steps which were within his control, Mr McEwan could
reduce his outlays and free a sum from which instalments of #500 a month
could be made.
Under the instalment scheme, Mrs McEwan, who also lives in Leven,
would be paid the principal sum in four and a half years -- by about
December 1999.
Lord Penrose said there was evidence in the case to justify the
decision taken by the sheriff and there was no basis for criticism of
her judgment.
The court refused Mr McEwan's appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pension plan for elderly in care</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER,POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634093</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is expected to target the plight of the elderly having
to go into residential care, by changing pension laws at the next Budget
and encouraging people to take out private insurance to meet the cost.
A Cabinet meeting next month is likely to urge Chancellor Kenneth
Clarke to raise the #8000 threshold above which pensioners must pay the
full cost of residential care in retirement.
The meeting on September 14 could also consider proposals to allow
pensioners to have cash accumulated in occupational pension schemes set
aside for long-term health care.
The #8000 rule has meant many have to sell off their homes to pay for
care, leaving them with little or nothing to pass on to their children.
A decision on changing current tax rules may depend on whether the
scheme would release sufficient funds to take the strain off the
taxpayer without considerably reducing the amount of income a pensioner
would draw while healthy.
The scheme would work by allowing pensioners or those approaching
retirement to set aside some of their tax-free pension fund money for
future health care.
The result would be a reduced pension but a bigger pay-out if someone
had to go into a residential or nursing home.
Those who favour the scheme say the regular pension would be only
slightly less and the Treasury would lose only the tax revenue from the
reduced pension.
The Department of Health says one in six pensioners is likely to need
care for an average of three years. Nursing home fees can be as much as
#400 a week.
There are more than four million in Britain aged over 75. The number
is expected to rise to 5.5 million by 2021, with the bill for their care
likely to be around #17bn.
Mr David Shaw, vice-chairman of the Tory back-bench finance committee,
said on BBC Radio 4's Today programme: ''The Prime Minister has been
very concerned that people should be able to not only save for
retirement but to save for the risks that they face in retirement.''
Labour spokesman Frank Dobson said the idea looked like ''waffle''
which the Tories were putting forward to try to persuade people they
were doing something. He thought it was likely to be no more effective
then the Prime Minister's promise to end house repossessions in 1992.
</TEXT>
