<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On course for redundancies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN, EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976634094</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Education Correspondent Barclay McBain examines the effects of the
Government's plans for funding further-education colleges.
Government speak with forked tongue.
JACK DALE, the Educational Institute of Scotland's further and higher
education secretary, is not the first person (nor will he be the last)
to make such an observation about our political masters. He believes the
Government is acting duplicitously in its plans for funding the 43
further-education colleges which have been taken out of local government
control and now receive their public money direct from the Scottish
Office.
''It is saying on the one hand that the sector must be built up, yet
on the other it says the major players must make do with less money. For
all its support for vocational training, its policies mean that FE will
have to provide for the same number of students with less funding. That
is something we are opposed to,'' said Dale.
After the colleges were removed from the largely benevolent embrace of
the local authorities, the Government made it clear that the basis on
which they had been funded would be changed.
Add to that a requirement to make ''efficiency gains'' at college
level -- where the drive for greater efficiency could lead to bigger
class sizes -- and a proposed #10m cut over two years in the Scottish FE
funding pot and you can easily understand why institutions are feeling
the squeeze.
And so are their staff. Lecturers at Jewel and Esk Valley College in
Dalkeith yesterday rejected strike action in support of three colleagues
made compulsorily redundant but the prospect of further deterioration in
labour relations in FE remains real.
More colleges will reduce their staff costs -- by voluntary means if
they can -- as they seek to come to terms with big reductions in their
budgets. As Dale put it: ''We know financial difficulties will continue
and we can expect a further round of cuts next year. The possibility of
redundancies will return.''
More than two years ago the then Education Minister, Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, announced that colleges would move as quickly as
possible towards formula funding. For those colleges which had benefited
from generous local authorities' funding -- which had good reasons for
augmenting the amounts they disbursed in line with their political
strategies -- it potentially meant bad news. For those which had
struggled to make ends meet while hitting Government targets there were
benefits.
In the event the Scottish Office has been more lenient in introducing
formula funding. Last year, 90% of college money was based on historic
funding, with the remainder determined by the formula. This year the
proportions are 60-40 and there is an expectation that, from next April,
all public funding will be formula-driven.
The Government announcement on proportions and timing is eagerly
awaited, both by institutions which have been historically underfunded
and by those which will receive less and will be anxious to plan ahead.
Under the new system, funding will be based on the number of students
colleges can attract, weighted to take account of the fact that some
disciplines are more expensive than others.
Although only partially introduced, formula funding is already
exposing colleges such as Jewel and Esk, which had benefited from
Lothian region's generous funding. Dale said: ''By moving to a system
under which colleges will be funded on the same basis, those which were
funded more generously in the past will lose out, unless there is lots
more money coming in.'' Patently, that will not happen, as the public
expenditure survey proposed cut of #10m confirms.
Dale went on: ''When colleges were managed as broad units by local
authorities, students could be directed between centres, but now every
college has to fight for students, even if that means taking them from
elsewhere.''
However Alistair Tyre, principal of Langside College in Glasgow,
believes that the future is not necessarily gloomy for those
institutions which have experienced the withdrawal of local authority
''augmentive'' funding.
''There will be difficult decisions facing colleges and their boards
of management but, given sufficient planning, they should be able to
dilute the impact of this on their communities and staff.'' Such
colleges could be helped by a decision to move to full formula funding
over a longer time-scale, or by the option of safety-net funding to ease
the transition to the new model.
Mr Tyre believes that the move to formula funding will lead to a much
closer focus on the activities of individual institutions. ''In the past
they were aggregated under the banner of regional authorities, and
things could be balanced out over time. Now decisions can be taken,
whether they are pleasant or unpleasant, in-house, hopefully with the
best interests of communities and students in mind. We have to live in
the real world. We are not exempt as a microcosm of society from the
winds of change.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
