<HEADLINE>Make my day, cyberpunk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCESCA FEARON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634096</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Francesca Fearon taps into the Internet and opens up another world of
fashion advice
I AM sitting at my computer and I want advice. I want to find the
perfect mascara. I want to know where I can get Antoni &amp; Alison's
designer T-shirts. I want to check out Jean-Paul Gaultier's new
cyber-fashion collection, if it's on-line? I want a combat jacket with
neon colour flashes, but who sells it?
Sitting here at my computer I am on-line with other ''netties'' around
the world asking their advice on my fashion and beauty problems. There
are beauty-product junkies and fashion fans all furiously trading
personal tips with me on the Internet. We are now entering the era of
cyberpunks and ''surfing'' (computer speak for browsing) the
international digital superhighway.
The Internet is fast becoming the forum for the fashion conscious,
probing the information network, known as World Wide Web for information
on their favourite subject. The worldwide population on the Net is
estimated to be 30 million and growing fast.
Surfing the digital superhighway was predominantly the past-time of
young middleclass men, however, times are changing in cyberspace.
It is now estimated that between 25% and 30% of surfers are women.
Their informal Scottish headquarters is Cyberia Cafe in Edinburgh -- a
branch will be opening in Glasgow next month. It is an Internet coffee
shop where ''netties'' can sit with their cappuccinos hunched over
screens with their fingertips racing across the keyboards, chatting to
friends on E.mail or browsing through style catalogues already on-line.
At Cyberia there are cyber-hostesses on hand to help the Technophobes
and Internet virgins to learn to surf. ''Net surfing is not a solitary
pursuit, it is fun and sociable,'' says Gavin Nicholson, who runs
Cyberia here. ''We want to offer access to the Net for everyone to show
that it is relaxed and not intimidating.''
Where technology forges ahead fashion snaps at its heels. It stands to
reason that as more people surf, fashion and beauty names are fast
developing a presence on-line. A number of style and shopping services
are available including Pepe jeans, Future Shooter, and Avant Garde
designer menswear label Griffin Laundry, which has also used the Net as
a fashion statement for their autumn collection, hi-tech urban
sportswear themed around cyberpunks.
Designer Lisa Johnson plans to use the medium to promote her spring
1996 collection and T-shirt designers Antoni &amp; Alison are strongly
tempted. Model agencies are using it as a means of downloading their
data base of photographs to clients. While journalism students at the
London College of Fashion have launched a cyberzine -- an on-line style
magazine called N-Touch.
Shiseido, the supreme Japanese cosmetic firm has launched itself on
the Net in Japan with a virtual reality shopping mall of its products.
Clinique in the US has claimed its small corner of cyberspace with
20,000 CyberFace interactive beauty disks, for those unable to gain
access to these, Clinique has an on-line counter in the US. But
difficulties of using the Net for mail order (protecting charge card
numbers) have only just been resolved.
By late autumn, Benetton will be using the Net both as a data base of
their fashion collections and provider of archival information, and as a
democratic forum for political debate on social issues -- in the same
way they use their advertising for visual communication.
Next month Diesel, the Avant Garde jeans brand will be promoting its
collection on the network.
Fashion has not only invaded Internet it has used the digital
superhighway as a source of inspiration. Gaultier and Hussein Chalayan
and Owen Gaster were all inspired by futuristic computer graphics and
virtual reality images for their autumn collections. Shiny, hi-tech
fabrics, metallics, lots of zips and slick, skin-fit, modern silhouettes
spell out the dawning of cyber-fashion.
To access Griffin Laundry on the Network go to
http://www.Griffin-corp.co.uk. Shiseido is at
http://www.Topan.co.jp/Shiseido. N.Touch cyberzine is at
http://www.dircon.co.uk/lcf/ntouch.html. The Herald News and Features
are on-line on the Internet at http://www.cims.co.uk/cims/.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
