<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Player's son given caps by benefactor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634097</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOOTBALLER Ray Kennedy, forced to sell his medals and caps after being
struck down by Parkinson's disease, yesterday welcomed the news that a
millionaire benefactor had left some of the mementoes to his son.
The 44-year-old former Arsenal, Liverpool, and England star, auctioned
the medals and international caps in 1993 but now the purchaser of his
17 England caps has left eight of them in his will to the footballer's
14-year-old son, Dale.
''It is really fantastic, a very nice gesture,'' Mr Kennedy said from
his specially adapted bungalow in Tyne and Wear yesterday. ''It was
heart-breaking to have to lose all the mementoes of my career, but with
my health being as it is, I had to ensure my financial stability. I
didn't even know who had bought the caps, but he must have been a really
nice guy.''
The caps were left in the will of Mr Lawrence Levy, of Hampstead,
north London. He specified that they should go to Dale ''in the hope
that they will not be sold''.
Mr Kennedy said: ''They will definitely not be sold. Dale was so
pleased to be given the caps. He plays for a local boys' football side
and he's not a bad player. Perhaps the caps will inspire him.''
The sale of footballing honours raised #88,407 at Christie's in
Glasgow. The eight caps cost Mr Levy #6820.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Liberty belles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCESCA FEARON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634098</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEHIND the carved Portland stone and mock-Tudor beams of Liberty's
Regent Street headquarters some big changes are taking place, notably
the launch of its own major fashion collection.
The fashion floor, once renowned for its floral Tana Lawn prints and
Kate Greenaway dresses, has swept away that
haven-to-middle-England-dressmakers image and replaced it with an array
of beautifully made aesthetic clothing from designers like Yohji
Yamamoto and Issey Miyake.
The philosophy, beside the Oriental element, has been to seek out the
very best of British design -- modernists, like Galliano, Conran, Flyte
Ostell, and Betty Jackson who possess an extraordinary understanding of
the technique of crafting clothes.
Having established the foundations of Liberty's fashion image, the
Liberty empire has taken the big step of launching its own-label fashion
collection, which will be available from branches in Glasgow and
Edinburgh next month.
The Liberty Collection is modern and colourful yet reflects something
of Liberty's extraordinary heritage. A short scarlet wool crepe coat and
dress, a funky bright tweed suit, a 1940s pinstripe box jacket and wide
trousers are the fashion looks of the moment. Yet mixed in with this are
the idiosyncratic Liberty print satin shirts and camisoles.
The firefly is one of the patterns which Dilys Williams, the head of
design, found in the archives. She recoloured it and printed it on
georgette and the shiny silks and satins currently in vogue.
''Liberty is so well known for its beautiful use of fabrics, that we
went first to the cloth, worked on the colours and recut the patterns,''
she explains. ''Some of the original patterns are really wild.''
Fashion's current passion for merging modernity with nostalgia can be
echoed now in the Liberty Collection by drawing on the decades of
Liberty prints stored in the archives.
After seasons of safe neutral colours, bright crimsons, yellows and
pinks are making a comeback. Reflecting this new colour palette is the
return of bold, vivid prints.
A generation of painters, designers and architects enthused about
Liberty. The pre-Raphaelites and their beautiful models, the Arts and
Crafts movement and writers like Marcel Proust crowded the little
Liberty store when it first opened in the late nineteenth century. They
bought scarves, ties, fabrics and artefacts from the Orient. From the
outset the Liberty name has been associated with the best in
contemporary decorative arts and design. The fashion director, Tom
Logan, Dilys Williams and the design team want to built up that House of
Liberty name again.
Dilys Williams, previously designer for Jigsaw and Whistles, has been
charged with this task. ''We started from scratch, building a design
studio with a full team of pattern cutters and production people. We
felt there is such a strength in the heritage and we wanted to be part
of it.''
The collection they have created includes the essential classic pieces
that now have a distinctly modern touch, such as the chic stretch boucle
Audrey Hepburn-style coat and dress and the pastel mohair check
tailoring. The emphasis is placed on originality of design and strong
colour combinations.
* EXCLUSIVE to Herald readers, Liberty is organising a special
customer evening at their shop in Glasgow, where Dilys Williams will
introduce the collection. It will be held on September 27 at Liberty,
Buchanan Street, Glasgow. For free tickets, contact Rozanne McElhone on
0141-221 7792. The Liberty collection will be available also at their
branch in Princes Street, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Way clear for Mellor to marry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Heritage Secretary David Mellor and Viscountess Cobham -- whose
romance became public last November -- look set to marry following her
''quickie'' divorce yesterday.
Mrs Judith Mellor divorced her husband -- the MP for Putney in
south-west London -- in March and this summer he set up home with Lady
Cobham in a #1m mansion near London's Tower Bridge.
The decree nisi ending the Cobhams' marriage was one of 30 granted
yesterday morning at the divorce registry in Somerset House, London. It
becomes absolute in six weeks.
Viscount Cobham said in a statement from his stately home, Hagley
Hall, Worcestershire, that he believed Lady Cobham and Mr Mellor planned
to marry.
The split between Mr Mellor, 46, and his wife came as little surprise,
although she previously stuck by him when news broke about his
well-publicised affair with actress Antonia de Sancha.
The scandal forced him to resign as National Heritage Secretary but he
quickly established another career as host of a BBC Radio 5 Live soccer
phone-in.
This summer, Lady Cobham, 41, and Mr Mellor declared they were ''an
item'' and set up home together.
Viscount Cobham, 52, married the former Penelope Cooper in 1974. She
is president of the Heart of England Tourist Board and has worked as a
special adviser in the Heritage Department.
Mr Mellor was not available for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634100</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Petrol bombs were thrown in Crossmaglen on the South Armagh border
last night as Sinn Fein mounted a series of pickets and rallies to mark
this week's first anniversary of the IRA ceasefire.
The petrol bombs, said police, were thrown at the Crossmaglen security
base during the rally outside.
At one stage during the protest a van load of men drove up and started
to saw down some of the perimeter security fencing. The security forces
did not intervene and the men left. A number of tyres were piled up
against the side of the base and set on fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Next year a Costa package will cost a packet</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634101</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILLIONS of holidaymakers will be paying more for their trips to Spain
and its islands next summer, it was revealed yesterday.
Tour-operating giant First Choice announced average Spanish price
rises of 9% as it launched its 1996 summer brochures. The UK's two
biggest holiday companies, Thomson and Airtours, were also expected to
announce costlier Costa packages when they reveal their plans for next
summer today.
The hike in Spanish prices was likely to add around #90 to the cost of
a package for a family of four, assuming one of the children goes free
as part of one of the many special deals on offer.
To add to holidaymakers' problems, there could be fewer packages to
choose from next summer.
First Choice said yesterday that it was offering 15% fewer holidays
next summer than it had originally intended when it first planned the
1996 brochures.
Airtours was also expected to offer fewer holidays next summer while a
Thomson spokeswoman said last night: ''We have had a long, hard look at
the market this year and made our plans for 1996 accordingly.''
A spokesman for Airtours said Spanish prices had risen because
hoteliers had put their prices up above the level of local inflation
after having had a particularly good summer.
Spain was popular not only with Britons but also with the Dutch and
the Germans, who on average have more spending power.
In addition, the Government plans to alter the conditions governing
VAT rates on part of the profits tour operators make, and companies have
anticipated this by increasing some prices for next summer.
First Choice attempted to counter the Spanish rises by extending its
''no-pocket-money-needed'' packages, including holidays to 16
destinations in Europe as well as the Caribbean in 1996. They start at
#299 for a week in Turkey.
''There is still a lack of consumer confidence and the fine weather in
the UK persuaded a lot of people to holiday at home this summer,'' said
First Choice commercial director Peter Phillipson.
''We are being more conservative about the number of holidays we are
offering next summer but we are hoping that many thousands will enjoy
the novelty of all-inclusive breaks.''
New long-haul destinations being offered by the company next summer
include Tobago, Antigua, Grenada, and Sri Lanka.
Prices start at #149 for a week in a self-catering apartment on
Spain's Costa Brava.
New from Thomson next year will be packages to the south of France,
including the top resorts of Nice and Cannes. Prices will start at #149
for a week's self-catering.
Thomson will also be announcing Florida children's prices of #99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Friends urge UN to punish the aggressor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Friends of Bosnia yesterday urged the United Nations to
take military and political action against the Bosnian Serbs after the
massacre of 37 people in Sarajevo on Monday.
Mr Mladen Grbin, secretary of the organisation, said the international
community had clearly identified the aggressor in the conflict and
should therefore act.
He said the UN should stop the Bosnian Serbs from broadcasting
propaganda and should also target military installations and
logistically important roads and bridges.
He said the international community should also stop negotiating with
the Serbian President, Slobodan Milosevic.
He suggested the Sarajevo killings this week should not be seen in
isolation.
''No-one has actually been referring to the fact that this is a
besieged city for three-and-a-half years. This was just one shell in a
war of attrition,'' added Mr Grbin.
He claimed the international community, in particular Britain and
France, were ''bending backwards'' to explain why they could not react
immediately as promised at the Lancaster House conference.
He continued: ''The American administration wants a quick fix before
next year's primaries. Europe is in disarray over the issue, its envoys
shuttling between European capitals with an unclear agenda.'' He claimed
this arose from ''cynicism of the ultimate form.''
* Cardinal Thomas Winning will formally open an all-faith 12-hour
vigil of prayer for the people of Bosnia today in the City Chambers,
Glasgow. The event, which begins at noon, has been organised by the
recently formed Save the Bosnian People Campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000180</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP urges debate on sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE SCOTTISH Secretary, Mr Michael Forsyth, was urged yesterday to
call a special meeting of the Scottish Grand Committee in Edinburgh to
debate the increasing confusion over rail privatisation.
However, the Scottish Office said last night Mr Forsyth did not have
the power to do so.
Liberal Democrat MP Charles Kennedy has written to Mr Forsyth against
the backdrop of recent reports involving the shelving of the West Coast
franchise and internal industry predictions that the ScotRail franchise
cannot be achieved before the next General Election.
Mr Kennedy, MP for Ross, Cromarty, and Skye, said yesterday: ''Under
the Taking Stock reforms, the Scottish Grand Committee now enjoys
greater autonomy and flexibility. It should be able to convene during
the summer recess for specifically Scottish reasons, quite independent
of the situation at Westminster.
''The new Scottish Secretary owes it to all ScotRail employees,
Scottish MPs, and the public generally to come clean over the developing
fiasco of rail privatisation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000181</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000181</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ugly choice for councillor over the 'armadillo'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN,MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634104</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW'S planning chairman found himself in the awkward position of
having to give planning permission for a building he thinks will be the
ugliest thing he has ever seen.
''It's too late now to change things,'' said Councillor Hugh Macrae as
he cast a critical eye over a model of a proposed new #24m conference
centre which is to be added to the existing Scottish Exhibition and
Conference Centre complex.
However, the chairman differed with his officials, all of whom seemed
to think the striking design by Sir Norman Foster and Partners showed
flair and imagination.
In the view of one official, any incongruity would be due to the
medocrity of the buildings around it.
The controversial structure, comprising eight curved aluminium-clad
bands, reminiscent of Sydney Opera House, will have a capacity for more
than 3000 delegates and is expected to provide Glasgow with a conference
facility to rival anything in Europe.
However, Councillor Macrae remained unconvinced.
He complained: ''It's the ugliest thing I've ever seen. It looks like
an armadillo in the course of burying itself in the ground. It's
unbelievable. I'm far from pleased by this building.
''However, I'm sure it will be a talking point.''
The application submitted by the SECC was approved by bemused members
of the planning committee, many of whom were concerned about impact of
such a spectacular structure on the city's skyline and what effect
weathering would have on the aluminium cladding.
No doubt Glaswegians will settle on an unofficial name for the
structure. Suggestions so far so far include the Armadillo Building, the
Isaac Azimov Centre, and, more crudely, the Silver Slug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sea record official</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634105</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROUND-the-world yachtswoman Lisa Clayton yesterday spoke of her relief
and delight at having her record-breaking voyage ratified officially.
Since sailing into Dartmouth, Devon, on June 29 after a gruelling 286
days at sea, Ms Clayton has been forced to battle doubters who claimed
she had lied about her achievement.
Anonymous telephone calls and a lengthy letter to the World Sailing
and Speed Records Council accused her of receiving help when her yacht,
The Spirit of Birmingham, was damaged at sea.
However, she proved her case with the help of a dossier of thousands
of written logs and fax messages she had sent from the yacht.
Yesterday, the WSSRC confirmed her as the first woman from the
northern hemisphere to sail single-handed, unaided, and non-stop around
the world.
A delighted Ms Clayton said: ''It is nice for everyone and a relief,
although we were confident all the way along that we would get it
ratified.''
</TEXT>
