<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Orkney family on epic trip are thrown out of China</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634106</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ROVING Orkney family who paid out thousands of pounds to escape a
courtroom wrangle in Mongolia have now been thrown out of neighbouring
China.
Mr David Grant and his three children thought their epic voyage was
back on track when they made their way to Beijing on their horse-drawn
caravan.
However, they were apprehended by Chinese police who deported them,
claiming they did not have suitable visas.
Already short on funds, they were forced to pay #3000 for passage on a
ship to Japan and then #4500 on quarantine fees for their horse and
dogs.
They are now staying at Osaka, a port south of Tokyo, and could even
face problems leaving there.
Mr Grant, 54, and his wife Kate, 44, sold their home in Orkney in 1990
to pay for the globe-trotting journey. They planned to take their three
young children across Europe, Russia, China, over to Canada, and back to
Scotland.
The Grants were four years into their trip of a lifetime when their
dream turned sour in Mongolia in April.
Mr Grant was accused of blinding a thief who tried to raid their
caravan and was forced to stay in the country's capital, Ulaanbataar.
While he and children Torcuil, 15, Eilidh, 13, and Fionn, 10, stayed
on with their horse and dogs, Mrs Grant flew back to Britain to campaign
for his release.
After months of legal wrangling, their despair ended in July when an
out-of-court settlement with Mr Grant's accuser won his freedom.
They moved on to China -- but their celebrations were short-lived.
Mrs Grant, who has been staying at her father's home in Botley, near
Southampton, will be flying out to rejoin her family on Friday.
They then plan to move on to Canada for the penultimate leg of the
journey but the move is already proving problematic.
Mrs Grant said yesterday: ''It has cost us nearly #10,000 in one week
just to get to Japan. We still don't know if we will get into Canada
because of the quarantine laws.
''Apparently, you have to be in the country of departure for 60 days
before you are allowed into Canada and our animals won't have been in
Japan for that long.
''It's sad about China. We were looking forward to being there. It was
going to be one of the highlights of the expedition. But I can't wait
until we're together again after all this hassle.''
Since their adventure began, the family has travelled through Holland,
Belgium, France, Italy, Austria, Hungary, the Ukraine, and Russia.
They expect to arrive home in 1997 after travelling across Canada and
Scotland, and Mr Grant plans to write books about the trip.
</TEXT>
