<DOCID>GH950830-000184</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union rallies Scots against sleaze</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIC OUTTERSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634107</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL campaign to highlight a link between the erosion of public
services and an increase in private sleaze was launched in Scotland
yesterday by the country's largest trade union.
The Unison campaign, which will cost #250,000 and will take place
throughout the autumn, will target the effect of 16 years of
Conservative Government which it claims has undermined public services
while business leaders have been awarded increasingly fat salaries.
It will highlight the likely effects of privatisation of British Rail
and the nuclear industry, the reorganisation of water and sewerage
services and local government as well as changes to the control of
Scottish schools.
Mr Mike Kirby, Scottish convener of Unison said: ''The idea is to
unite public service trade unions, voluntary organisations, elected
representatives, user and community groups, and the unemployed in
opposition to the greed and sleaze fostered by the last 16 years of Tory
Government.''
Mr Matt Smith, Unison's Scottish secretary, said: ''By early
September, we will have contacted 2000 Scottish organisations and have
already planned involvement with 10 of them.''
The union yesterday admitted that the campaign, which culminates in a
national demonstration in London on October 21, is politically motivated
and is geared to coincide with the next Budget and the Government's
attempt to relaunch its public image.
Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe, associate general secretary of Unison, said:
''It is vital to the future of Scotland's public services that the
campaign is a success.
''The Scottish attitude to public services is one of support, the
current Tory Government's attitude is one of sell-off and close down.''
Mr Bickerstaffe claimed the Government's next budget would ''give
away'' between #2500m and #4000m to ''buy votes'' in various forms of
tax cuts and incentives and this would be paid for at the expense of
public services.
''Therefore this is an important political campaign -- not just an
industrial one -- to mobilise support as the Government attempts to
repackage itself to the public before the next General Election,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
