<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deadly fires rage in forests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634109</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARSEILLES: Huge forest fires have destroyed hundreds of acres of
woodland in the south of France, northern Portugal, and Spain, and have
cost several lives.
Some 400 firemen and 12 water-dropping planes fought flames near the
town of Lambesc, north of the French Mediterranean port of Marseilles
yesterday, but were hampered by gusts of wind.
Another fire south of Bordeaux devastated 375 acres of pine forest
before it was finally brought under control.
Firefighters were also battling a five-mile wall of flames in Serra do
Marao, northern Portugal. Two villages were threatened and houses were
in danger near Fafe. Six people have died in Portuguese fires this month
and two firemen died in Marseilles on Monday.
In Spain, Greenpeace said about 40% of the fires that ravaged forests
each summer were caused by arson and resulted in big profits for the
timber business.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
