<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major consults Molyneaux over way forward in Ulster</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister entertained the just-retired Ulster Unionist leader
Mr James Molyneaux to lunch at Chequers yesterday and sought an update
on Unionist thinking on what happens next on the peace process in
Northern Ireland.
Mr Major, who invited Mr Molyneaux within hours of hearing of his
resignation, thanked him for his contribution to the process.
Two points especially worry Ministers. First, will Mr Molyneaux's
successor be as co-operative as he has been about the peace process or
will he be inclined to voice more loudly Unionist fears that Britain is
being steadily driven in the direction of a united Ireland?
Second, will he and his colleagues be as willing in the next session
of Parliament this autumn to come to the rescue of the Government if it
faces rebellions in its own ranks.
As the Government's Commons majority declines into single figures,
this back-stop support becomes more crucial and a different Unionist
leader may demand more for his support.
British sources still were hoping that the planned summit between Mr
Major and Irish Prime Minister John Bruton would go ahead next Wednesday
but admit that, if British and Irish officials cannot agree on proposals
on decommissioning arms for discussion by the two leaders, the meeting
may have to be postponed.
The Ulster Unionist Party is rushing through the vote for the new
leader. It will be held in 10 days to ensure that the new leader is in
place as soon as possible at a crucial phase in the peace process.
Four men, all MPs, are expected to run for the leadership. They are Mr
Ken Maginnis, the party security spokesman, Mr William Ross, the Chief
Whip, the Rev Martin Smyth, Grandmaster of the Orange Order, and Mr John
Taylor.
All but Mr Taylor have declared their interests in running.
Mr Taylor, the MP for Strangford, is generally seen as the
Government's preferred successor. Despite his strong criticism of the
framework document, he is regarded as the man most likely to take the
Unionists into historic all-party talks with Sinn Fein.
Mr Maginnis, MP for Fermanagh and South Tyrone, has taken a tough line
on the IRA and repeatedly predicted the collapse of the ceasefire, which
is one year old on Friday.
He is nevertheless seen as being on the more moderate wing of the
party and has also made trips into the republic, most recently for his
summer holiday.
Mr Ross, the MP for East Londonderry, is reportedly Mr Molyneaux's
favoured successor and seen by party colleagues as a safe pair of hands.
There is unlikely to be any change in emphasis with him at the helm.
Mr Smyth, the South Belfast MP, can expect strong support from the
more than 100 delegates from the Orange Order who have voting rights at
the election.
A poll published in a Dublin Sunday newspaper showed that of Ulster
Unionist voters questioned, 41% favoured Mr Maginnis as leader, with 13%
opting for Mr Taylor. Mr Smyth got 14% and Mr Ross just 3%.
However, David Trimble, the Upper Bann MP who has declared he will not
run for the leadership, received 18% of support and it is believed that
in his absence much of that would transfer to Mr Taylor.
The Prime Minister is certain to have used the private farewell
luncheon for Mr Molyneaux to discover his views on who his successor is
likely to be.
The meal was atteded by Norma Major and Ulster Secretary Sir Patrick
Mayhew.
Mr Major is understood to have decided on the lunch following Mr
Molyneaux's retirement announcement on Monday, the day after his 75th
birthday, to thank him for his steadying influence and contribution to
the search for peace in Ulster.
Although Mr Molyneaux will remain as MP for Lagan Valley until the
next General Election, he is not expected to stand again and it is
thought likely that the long-serving Privy Councillor will be offered a
seat in the House of Lords.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
