<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Life for baldies far from smooth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BALD men are burdened with feelings of depression, low self-esteem,
and the fear of being unattractive, it was claimed yesterday.
Young men who go bald prematurely suffer the most, according to a team
of psychologists studying the effects of hair loss.
A survey of more than 180 men with an average age of 36 revealed that
increasing degrees of hair loss were accompanied by loss of self-esteem.
Bald or balding men felt unattractive, depressed, socially withdrawn,
and tended to be introverted or neurotic, the study found.
Dr Pamela Wells, who led the research at Goldsmith's College, south
London, said it was time people stopped regarding baldness as a joke.
''It's appalling the way people think it is hilarious when people go
bald and try to get a hair transplant or hairpiece.
''It would be absolutely unthinkable to treat women who are worried
about their appearance the way we treat bald men.''
The men involved in the study did not know the research was about
baldness.
Divided into three groups, the bald, the balding, and those with a
full head of hair, they were asked questions about their smoking habits
and level of self-confidence.
''The results were pretty profound in the younger people,'' said Dr
Wells. ''You don't expect to find such significant effects when you do
this kind of analysis.''
She said one of the researchers knew a student who became suicidal
after going bald in his 20s.
The researchers believe the negative way bald men regard themselves is
not a true reflection of how others see them.
</TEXT>
