<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots convoy to Bosnia held up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 14-STRONG convoy which left Scotland earlier this month for Bosnia
and which includes Scots Labour MP John Home Robertson has had its aid
efforts put on hold in the wake of the Sarajevo market blast.
With the possibility of retaliatory air strikes against the Bosnian
Serbs for the attack in which 37 died, Edinburgh Direct Aid has had to
shelve plans to move supplies into the city.
However, Dr Denis Rutovitz, the director of Edinburgh Direct Aid, who
is with the convoy held up in Split, has pledged that the mercy mission
will get through eventually.
''I have been to Sarajevo often enough now to have made many
friends,'' Dr Rutovitz told The Herald yesterday in a telephone call
from the former Yugoslavia.
''I just find it very upsetting,'' he stated. ''It is very personal
and you worry about the people. It's so terrible for those who are
there.''
Dr Rutovitz said that before Monday's blast in Sarajevo he would have
been ''100% confident'' of reaching the city as planned but the
situation had changed dramatically.
''If there was to be Nato air strikes the Serbs might respond by
bombarding everything in sight.''
Edinburgh Direct Aid set out on their 25th relief mission on August 17
with lorry loads of food, clothing and toiletries for Sarajevo and
Tuzla.
The party travelled despite the dangers highlighted earlier by the
recent deaths of two British aid workers near Sarajevo, one of whom was
34-year-old Mr Neil Golightly, from Broomhill, Glasgow.
They were killed on the Mount Igman road to Sarajevo -- the route
Edinburgh Direct Aid would take -- when their truck, part of a convoy
run by the Surrey-based charity Phoenix Aid International Direct, of
which the Scot was a co-founder, crashed after coming under fire.
* The last British troops to pull out of the UN ''safe haven'' of
Gorazde will arrive home tomorrow, the Army said yesterday.
Nearly 80 Royal Welch Fusiliers will fly into RAF Brize Norton,
Oxfordshire, including Lieutenant-Colonel Jonathan Riley who commanded
the battalion during its hazardous six-month tour of duty in Bosnia.
The final contingent to withdraw from Gorazde was given safe passage
by road through Serb territory to Belgrade from where it is expected to
travel on to the UN base at Split before flying home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000190</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000190</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Region holds the line over rail timetable.   Regulator's boost for Strathclyde.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON,CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE'S uncompromising stance in laying down the law on the
level of rail services within the region is behind ScotRail's
embarrassing slippage in the Government's increasingly chaotic
privatisation timetable.
Perhaps even more crucially, however, the independent Rail Regulator
has now pledged to promote Strathclyde's interests so far as possible,
according to a document in the possession of The Herald.
Regulator John Swift, QC, is determined to ensure that any commercial
aspirations are not only matched with the public interest but with those
such as Strathclyde who actually pay for the rail services.
Mr Swift is also adamant that the privatisation process must take
place in a manner that ensures the industry is not left to ''pick up the
pieces'' from a programme carried out too hastily or without regard to
the interests of users.
Such views -- expressed at a meeting with key players in the sell-off
process -- go a long way towards explaining why next month's invitation
to ScotRail to bid for the train operating franchise has been postponed,
railway experts said last night.
They also underpin growing suspicions that ScotRail, along with
InterCity West Coast main line, will not be in private hands before a
General Election.
Mr Swift's declaration that Strathclyde's interests should be promoted
in any agreement concerning track access is a massive boost for the
council.
Strathclyde is battling to retain rights to control fares, timetables,
and the standards of trains, in return for paying ScotRail #30m a year
to run the largest commuter network outside London.
The Herald has a full transcript of the Rail Regulator's meeting,
attended by, among others, the directors of ScotRail and Railtrack and
officials from the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising -- and the
Department of Transport and British Railways Board.
Mr Swift was called in earlier this month to adjudicate on a proposed
track access agreement between ScotRail and Railtrack which would have
serious implications for Strathclyde passenger services.
In June, Lord Cameron had refused to grant the region and Strathclyde
Passenger Transport Executive an interim interdict in the Court of
Session, aimed at enforcing an existing agreement with British Rail, due
to expire on September 30.
However, Mr Swift believes that both the council and PTE will have ''a
critical role'' in the formulation of policy and decision making within
the Strathclyde network.
Lines are now under the control of Railtrack and, to run trains, BR
has to agree access, with the contract to be approved by Mr Swift.
The transcript reveals that:
* Strathclyde, although willing to talk, will ''not compromise'' its
principles, especially the council taxpayers' right to determine the
level of services for which they pay;
* The PTE considers the proposed access contract is ''too loose'' --
neither guaranteeing that ScotRail would continue to deliver existing
services, nor that a future franchisee would meet obligations, and that;
* Doubts exist about the reasonableness of Railtrack's charges, even
if it is willing to open the books for inspection and to itemise
individual costs.
Strathclyde's transport committee chairman, Councillor Charles Gordon,
said the region had spent #400m at today's prices on expanding rail
services and he deplored ''the hiatus'' being imposed on the network
because of privatisation.
Councillor Gordon also told Mr Swift of concerns that Railtrack was
not investing in infrastructure, despite council offers to enhance and
develop the network.
However, ScotRail and Railtrack officials appeared content with the
terms of the proposed contract, although niggling matters of flexibility
and reliability remain.
Strathclyde's contribution to ScotRail now stands at #110m, because of
Railtrack's soaring access charges after the Government raised the real
cost of railway assets to get a better return from a sale.
The Government has guaranteed to make up the difference but only for
the moment. Strathclyde fears that funding could dry up next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
