<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000192</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000192</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato launches retaliatory raids on Serbs after Bosnians threaten to wreck peace talks. British general's plan of attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Rupert Smith, the British UN Commander in Bosnia, yesterday
prepared the plans to punish the Bosnian Serbs for the shelling of a
Sarajevo market which killed 37 people and wounded more than 80.
The UN said it had been confirmed Bosnian Serb forces were
responsible.
Spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Chris Vernon said the risks of Serb
retribution for a Nato strike were low after the final contingent of
British peacekeepers left Gorazde and reached Belgrade yesterday.
In London, Mr Major was contacted by French President Jacques Chirac
and spent 15 minutes discussing the Bosnian crisis, Downing Street said.
After the UN had concluded Bosnian Serbs were responsible for the
attack, it said all options had been reviewed, including the use of Nato
air power, to punish them.
UN officials also said that if bad weather had prevented a retaliatory
air strike, British and French heavy artillery of the UN Rapid Reaction
Force, dug in on Mount Igman outside Sarajevo, could have been turned on
Serb positions.
A Nato spokesman said General Smith had assessed the action with
Admiral Leighton Smith, the commander-in-chief of the alliance's
southern flank.
''We will know their assessment after the action has been taken,'' he
said.
He added that the US aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt had cancelled
a port visit to Rhodes and was steaming back to the Adriatic.
The West has been reluctant to take action to punish Serb aggression
since hundreds of UN peacekeepers were taken hostage in retaliation for
previous air strikes this spring, but the withdrawal of the remaining 77
Royal Welch Fusiliers from Gorazde leaves only two UN military observers
and one political officer in the town.
The only major concentration of peacekeepers still on the Bosnian Serb
side of the confrontation lines is about 450 Russians around Sarajevo.
The Russians, traditional friends of the Serbs, are considered to be at
much less risk.
UN forces have been ordered to stay out of Bosnian Serb territory
during the current crisis, the UN confirmed.
In Sarajevo the misery continued, with a four-year old girl killed and
two of her friends wounded when another mortar bomb exploded outside
homes near the city's brewery. A 22-year-old man was also wounded in the
latest attack.
The UN threats have failed so far to appease an angry Bosnian
government, which said it would pull out of peace talks unless the Serbs
were punished.
Bosnian President Alia Izetbegovic, in Paris for the talks, demanded
heavy artillery or Nato strikes against the besieging Serbs.
If there was no punishment for the shelling he said: ''Bosnian public
opinion demands that we pull out of peace talks.''
Confirmation that Serbs were responsible also brought calls for
military action from Muslim countries sympathetic to Bosnia, and both
the French and German foreign ministers.
In Paris, Foreign Minister Herve de Charette said: ''We want a
reprisal since it is clear from the analysts that the origin is Serb.''
With pressure building up for tough action, Washington ordered the
aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt to Bosnia's Adriatic coast with
dozens of warplanes aboard.
Pentagon officials called it a prudent step in view of the
circumstances.
As US diplomats in Paris struggled to keep their peace drive on
course, the Bosnian Serb parliament abruptly changed course and welcomed
the American plan.
Parliament speaker Momcilo Krajisnik said it has ''many elements which
prompt our optimism in the final solution to the crisis and
establishment of peace''.
''We have agreed to continue negotiations, believing that the chances
for achieving peace are much better today,'' he added.
However the timing of the sudden shift inevitably raised suspicions
about Serb sincerity and whether they were simply manoeuvring in the
hope of putting off massive UN and Nato retaliation.--Reuter
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000193</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000193</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth acts on store plan for football pitches</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634116</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONCERN that sports facilities should be protected from development
has prompted Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to intervene in the
determination of an application for a large foodstore on football
pitches at Toryglen Park, Glasgow.
He has instructed Glasgow district's planning committee to refer the
application from Jaymarke Development Prospecthill Ltd. to the Scottish
Sports Council.
Mr Forsyth said: ''The Scottish Sports Council are best placed to
provide the necessary professional and independent advice on the local
requirements for sport. It is therefore important that their view is
sought so that the council can take the right decision based on the best
advice.''
The applicants seek outline planning consent to erect a 60,000sq ft
foodstore on part of the playing fields, create 587 parking spaces, and
provide servicing facilities.
The 9.2 acre site lies on the Aitkenhead Road/Prospecthill Road
junction.
Planning chairman, Councillor Hugh Macrae, confirmed the application
would be referred to the Scottish Sports Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000194</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000194</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boys held as slab crushes woman, 74</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634117</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEN-year-old boy was being held by police last night and two others,
aged nine and 10, released on police bail after an elderly woman was
killed by a concrete block.
The 74-year-old pensioner was returning from the shops with her
husband and 43-year-old daughter when the heavy slab struck her on the
head, shattering her skull and killing her instantly.
Residents of flats around Grayson Heights, in Kirkstall, Leeds, rushed
to help after hearing the screams of the daughter.
Locals said youngsters regularly used the rooftop of the 150ft high
flats as a play area, and often threw down heavy objects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000195</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950830-000195</DOCID>
<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Company in link with contract for health HQ</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Morrison Group last year was given a detailed specification to
build the new headquarters of Highland Health Board at least a fortnight
before other competitors, and subsequently went on to win the contract,
worth almost #2m, earlier this year.
The company, which is chaired by Mr Fraser Morrison, who also chairs
Highlands and Islands Enterprise, was given the information by
representatives of Highland Health Board, which is chaired by Mr John
Robertson, who is also a member of the board of HIE.
On Friday, Scottish Office Minister George Kynoch issued a statement
which insisted that Morrisons had no ''inside track'' to the contract to
build the new Inverness HQ of the North of Scotland Water Authority,
which is also chaired by Mr John Robertson.
Mr Kynoch said he had every confidence in Mr Morrison and Mr Robertson
and deplored any attempt to denigrate them.
This followed a report in The Herald last Wednesday that Morrisons had
lodged a detailed planning application three days before any local
competitors had even received the specification and that Morrisons was
the only company to be promoted by HIE in negotiations with the water
authority.
In the case of the new Highland Health Board offices, Morrisons -- who
finalised the contract on March 28 this year -- lodged a planning
application at Inverness divisional planning office on Friday, September
2, last year for approximately 23,500 sq ft on land the company owned at
Beechwood, Inverness.
This contained detail obviously contained in the health board's
specification.
An invitation to tender was sent out on August 12 but not received
until August 15. This contained information from the health board's
agents, the Edinburgh-based quantity surveyors, cost engineers, and
project managers Faithful and Gould.
This proposed a complicated formula which required developers to
survey and value seven existing health board properties in Inverness,
which the developer would then take on, receiving only the balance
between their value and the contract price.
This formula was abandoned on September 29, but most of the
competitors were still busy with its time-consuming procedure when
Morrisons lodged their detailed planning application.
When asked how they could have been so far ahead, a spokesman for the
Morrison Group explained: ''In July, we were approached by those
representing the health board, Faithful and Gould and the Neil Munro
Property Consultancy, and asked about the availability and likely cost
of a building.
''At that time, we didn't know who their client was. However, later
that same month, we had a site visit with them. At that meeting, the
project manager from Faithful &amp; Gould, Donald Lawson, gave us two
volumes of tender contracts, both dated July 1994.
''On page three of volume two, there are all the space specifications
for the building.''
Yesterday, when The Herald contacted Mr Lawson, who is a director of
Faithful &amp; Gould, to ask why only one company had been given this
information in July, he said: ''I am not prepared to discuss this matter
with you because of client confidentiality.''
A spokesman for Highland Health Board said Faithful and Gould had
operated on behalf of Highland Health Board to assist in the disposal of
existing properties and to secure the provision of a new headquarters
office where all board activities would be organised under one roof.
The firm was appointed after a competitive tendering process.
''On September 21, 1994, Faithful and Gould reported to HHB that they
had contacted eight companies on August 12 with a view to pursuing
developments that would meet the board's needs. Returns were asked for
from these companies by 12 noon on Septmber 16.
''Three offers were received by the board by that time, with a further
late submission. One of these, Morrisons, offered best value and was
accepted by the board after further negotiation in March 1995.
''In all of its activities, HHB is conscious of its responsibility
with regard to best use of public funds and has ensured that competition
for the building of the new headquarters has been conducted in
accordance with the highest standards of financial probity,'' the
spokesman said.
0 Labour trade and industry spokesman Brian Wilson, who has been
highly critical of the quango system in the Highlands, said last night:
''It looks as though Mr Kynoch will have to get his whitewash brush out
again.
''The central principle is that where there are overlapping interests,
fairness should not only exist but must be seen to exist.
''The whole point of competitive tendering is surely that everyone
starts from the same point. Whatever Mr Kynoch states after cursory
examination, that hasn't happened in either of these cases.''
Mr Robertson could not be contacted for comment.
</TEXT>
