<HEADLINE>Drugs test kits now available for companies to screen employees</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID,MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH company is marketing test kits to employers who want to
screen their workers for drugs abuse.
Greenock based Bio-Generics offers kits which test urine for ecstasy,
speed, cannabis, or cocaine, and already have contracts with a number of
large public and private-sector organisations.
Last year, they introduced the kits for sale to parents. Now, thanks
to their expansion into the industrial sector, they are giving them free
to parents.
However, the head of one of Scotland's major medical research
companies warned employers that sloppy testing could result in expensive
lawsuits by aggrieved employees.
Dr Walter Nimmo, chief executive of Inveresk Clinical Research, said
inadvertant passive smoking of cannabis was one possible source of false
accusation they had discovered while screening volunteers for their
clinical drug-testing programmes.
Human volunteers are given a thorough medical check-up beforehand and
are screened for drugs, whether recreational or prescribed, which might
put them at risk when combined with the trial product or confound the
results.
''We regularly have to turn away people who we find have been taking
cannabis. We can't prove it but we think it is possible that some of the
positives are the result of passive cannabis smoking,'' said Dr Nimmo.
''For one thing, everyone, regardless of whether they are smokers or
not, tests positive for nicotine. Our tests don't quantify the amount
but clearly tobacco smoke is ubiquitous.
''We get people who test positive for cannabis and say they haven't
been using it and, sometimes, we are inclined to believe them. They may
have been to a party recently, they have been straight with us on
previous occasions, and they have no reason to lie since it is in
confidence and they have to be excluded from the trial anyway.''
Other problems could arise if employers who carried out testing failed
to ensure a secure chain of custody for samples and left the risk, or
suspicion, of a mix-up somewhere along the line.
''Cutting corners on that could be a false economy if a company were
to be sued not only for unfair dismissal but false accusations of drug
abuse,'' he warned.
Mr David Wallace, diagnostic consultant with Bio-Generics, said: ''We
have been doing a lot of negotiating with companies. We have some
contracts and several large companies are in the process of introducing
tests but confidentiality is paramount to them.
''They are interested not so much because they have a particular
problem but because they think they should do it to show a public
awareness of the problem. American companies are more in tune with drug
testing.
''Safety is always something employers have to be aware of but my
impression is that it is not so much a question of personal problems but
of community involvement, to make sure drugs are not being used or
traded within the work premises.''
Mr Wallace said that, legally, pre-employment testing was no problem.
To begin testing an existing workforce, he recommended prior warning
that this was going to be a new part of the contract of employment, with
minimum notice of six weeks.
Thanks to the growth in commercial sales from the company's other
products in mainstream medical testing, they are providing the kits free
to parents, who can get them through the recommendation of their family
doctor.
</TEXT>
