<HEADLINE>No room for equity gloom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART MCINTOSH, HERALD PROPERTY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS HOMES</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976634120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE clouds of gloom still rolling up from the south should not be
allowed to cast their shadow over Scotland's property market. The
problem for builders, estate agents and house sellers north of border is
that perceptions of the market here continue to be affected by the bad
news from England.
The key differences between the markets north and south of the border
are these: while house sales are not booming in Scotland, nor are they
moribund -- houses which are put on the market at the right price will
sell; most importantly, values in Scotland are still holding up, which
means that negative equity is not a real factor in the Scottish property
equation, according to the latest statistics from the TSB.
The bank's Quarterly Scottish House Price Monitor shows that the
average domestic Scottish property rose in value by 3.9% in the three
months to the end of July 1995.
This change exactly reverses the fall experienced in the previous
quarter. The index is adjusted for changes in geographic area, property
type and proportion of first-time buyers. However, compared to the same
quarter one year ago, the index is showing a fall of 4.3%. It now seems
clear, from the bank's graphs, that Scotland had a temporary market
surge during the second quarter of last year which gradually dissipated
until the index turned up again during the second quarter of this year.
The TSB says these figures confirm the seasonal recovery of the market
from its depressed state in the autumn and winter of 1994/95. Meanwhile,
the volume of new mortgages has increased significantly in the quarter
to end of July 1995 compared to the previous quarter -- but is still
down on the same quarter one year ago.
First-time buyers continue to display confidence accounting for 38% of
all new mortgage transactions, a share similar to that in the same
period last year.
The bank's statistics also show that negative equity has not made any
real inroads into the Scottish market. The average price paid by
first-time buyers has been static for the last three years, with only a
slight indication of a fall in the last two quarters. ''There is little
evidence in these figures of significant negative equity,'' says a TSB
spokesman.
The bank calculates that Scotland's negative equity is confined to
first-time buyers who purchased a flat or maisonette in Aberdeen,
Dundee, or Glasgow one year ago with a 100% mortgage -- and who have not
made any capital repayments.
''There may be individual cases where negative equity exists but,
overall, it is not a Scottish problem,'' says the bank spokesman.
These latest results confirm the underlying strength of the Scottish
housing market. Despite the year-on-year fall in activity, the overall
price index is now rising, the number of new mortgages has increased,
first-time buyers continue to be active in the market and there is no
real evidence of a negative equity problem. ''Sustainable'' is the most
appropriate adjective to describe the current state of the Scottish
housing market, says the TSB.
This optimistic outlook is boosted by Scottish Office statistics which
show that new private-sector house building increased during the first
quarter of this year. Between January and March there were an estimated
4,903 starts in Scotland, an increase of 22% on the same period in 1994.
* Meanwhile, Stewart Saunders, Lothian's largest independent firm of
estate agents, has announced record sales of #1.95 million for July.
This is an increase of 40% on sales in the same month in 1994 an 1993
and is almost double the figure or 1992. The average price of properties
sold during July was #84,000, with five sales in the #100,000-#150,000
bracket and one over #250,000. Eight of the properties sold were new.
''This is a remarkable result, as the first two weeks of the month
were quiet, as is normal for this time of year,'' said David Alves,
managing director of Stewart Saunders. ''It's significant that the
figures are more than 20% higher than our previous record, achieved in
1989. Demand in the second-hand market is still not particularly
bouyant. Accurate pricing, enthusiastic and professional marketing, and
careful attention to presentation are still vital ingredients in
securing a sale.''
</TEXT>
