<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chief constable's doubt on policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN,HOME AFFAIRS CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GRAMPIAN'S chief constable said yesterday he doubted whether there was
a chief constable in the land who really believed enforcement policies
were successful in dealing with the drugs problem.
Dr Ian Oliver said the police were highly successful at catching drugs
dealers but that enforcement was simply like ''whispering in a steel
mill''.
He made his views known in the context of a seminar which his force
will hold in Aberdeen in October at which the theme will be that the
correct and long-term way to tackle drugs in society is through
education to reduce demand.
The conference message will be that everyone should have a commitment
to face up to drugs, including every company in the country and where
safety -- either of the public or of employees -- is an issue that
policy should include random testing of employees.
Dr Oliver said: ''Random tests in the workplace are only a small part
of the whole issue. The true position is that the whole of the UK is
awash with illegal drugs and if anyone wants them they can get them.
Coincidentally, there are a whole lot of people who for a variety of
reasons don't know this or do not want to know.
''We believe that education is more important than enforcement and it
is no longer any good society wringing its hands and saying someone
should be doing something. The message from the conference will be that
you should be doing something and that includes every employer who has a
safety issue to deal with.''
The conference, which will address the issue of both random testing
and ''with cause'' testing in the workplace, is sponsored by a number of
companies, including Shell UK, BT, and British Airways, which already
have urine and breath testing for drugs and alcohol. Dr Oliver
emphasised yesterday that the main object was to assist people with
problems to address them.
The Scottish Police Federation's deputy general secretary, Mr Tom
Rowatt, said: ''While we are not really any different from any other
occupation in this respect, I think that before any such policy happened
we would have to see plainly that there was an issue that was giving
concern. There seems to be absolutely no evidence of this.''
The chairman of the Scottish Council for Civil Liberties, Glasgow
lawyer Alan Miller, said: ''You cannot introduce mandatory drugs testing
in the workplace without consent. It would have to be a voluntary or
contractual agreement, otherwise it would be a gross interference with
people's liberties and privacy. Taking a sample might even constitute an
assault.''
</TEXT>
