<HEADLINE>SNP'swelfarestate planattacked</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Party yesterday unveiled its vision of a
post-independence welfare state and stepped into an immediate
controversy over whether its proposals were uncosted pie-in-the-sky.
The party conference in Perth next month will debate an agenda well to
the left of Mr Tony Blair's New Labour but leaders faced an immediate
accusation yesterday that the lack of any funding proposals undermined
their aspirations.
The SNP agenda to be discussed at Perth will include a motion calling
for:
* Full employement.
* A minimum wage at the level accepted by trade unions.
* Social security ''which ensures that no member of the community
needs to live in poverty''.
* A basic income payment covering the jobless, elderly, the disabled,
students, and lone parents.
The plans were condemned by Scottish Conservative chairman Sir Michael
Hirst, who said: ''The SNP is the most left-wing party in Scottish
politics. At the conference, we will see the usual rag-bag mixture of
unrealistice, unworkable, and uncosted proposals.''
SNP chief executive Mr Michael Russell said a series of policy
documents would be published over the next few weeks on economic and
financial details.
</TEXT>
