<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Barrymore steals TV awards show</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TROUBLED comic Michael Barrymore last night received an ovation as his
show, Strike It Lucky, was named Quiz Programme of the Year at the
National Television Awards.
Obviously moved by the emotion of the audience just days after he
admitted being gay, he said: ''Thank you for giving me the encouragement
to carry on at the moment.''
He is now living apart from his wife of 19 years, Cheryl, who remains
his manager.
Speaking on stage at the Wembley Conference Centre, where he received
his award from Hughie Green, Barrymore joked: ''May I first of all
apologise about the cut of my suit. It is not the best and my wardrobe
has been thrown out.''
Barrymore's reception was one of the warmest of an evening in which he
was nominated for, and won, three awards, the others being Most Popular
Entertainment Presenter and Most Popular Family Programme, for
Barrymore.
Host of the evening, GMTV presenter Eamonn Holmes, said: ''In the
light of the events of the last couple of weeks, we really appreciate
Michael being here tonight.''
Later, Barrymore, 43, made a moving speech about the problems he has
had since he admitted that he was gay.
He said: ''If I had known it was going to turn out like this, I would
have opened my mouth years ago. I'm probably going to come out another
two times.''
He thanked his fans who have deluged him with letters of support and
joked: ''I had a telegram from Hugh Grant which said, 'Dear Michael,
thank you, thank you, oh thank you'.''
Other winners were: Most Popular Drama -- Soldier Soldier; Factual
Entertainment -- Animal Hospital Week; Talk Show -- Des O'Connor
Tonight; Actor -- Robson Green; Soap -- Coronation Street; Comedy
Performer -- Brian Conley; Newcomer -- Angela Griffin; Comedy Programme
-- Men Behaving Badly; Young People's Programme -- Top of the Pops;
Actress -- Anna Friel.
</TEXT>
