<HEADLINE>Historic vote for Labour candidate. Ayr to select best woman for the job</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR Party members in Ayr will be involved in a piece of political
history in 12 days when they are asked to choose a prospective
parliamentary candidate from a list containing only women.
As the debate rages within the party nationally over whether the
practice of women-only shortlists should continue after the
''experimental'' phase, The Herald has learned that members in Ayr will
be asked to choose from five candidates on September 10.
The successful candidate will go forward to contest the seat currently
held for the Conservatives by Mr Phil Gallie.
The combination of a tiny majority, boundary changes that have robbed
Mr Gallie of thousands of potential votes in the affluent suburbs of
Alloway and Doonfoot, and overall discontent with the Government make
the seat eminently winnable for Labour.
Five candidates from a wide variety of political backgrounds have been
chosen to go to the people in a contest that will be a mixture of
mini-convention in Ayr and postal ballots.
After the votes are counted, having been cast by each member on a
single transferable vote system, the successful candidate will be
announced. The candidates are:
* Ms Neelam Backshi, currently a Strathclyde Regional councillor
representing Maryhill and Summerston who was unsuccessful in gaining a
nomination for a seat on the new Glasgow unitary authority. She was
involved in an industrial tribunal recently when she claimed racial
discrimination had led to her failing to be considered for a job with
Falkirk District Council as an equal opportunities officer. Ms Backshi
has the backing of the constituency women's section.
* Ms Cathy Jamieson, a former Strathclyde social worker who now works
with homeless teenagers. She has held office in the Cunninghame South
constituency of Mr Brian Donohoe for many years and is also involved
with the left-wing Campaign Group in Scotland. Ms Jamieson is backed by
the Co-op movement, TGWU, and the influential Ayr North branch of the
party. She has the backing of South of Scotland Euro-MP Alex Smith.
* Ms Renee Gillan, a librarian with Kyle and Carrick District Council
who is also a shop steward with Unison and has union and district
backing.
* Ms Elaine Murray, who represents Ayr South on Strathclyde Regional
Council since winning it from the Tories at the last election. She has
also won a seat on the shadow South Ayrshire Council representing
Dundonald.
* Mrs Sandra Osborne, worker with Women's Aid and the member for
Whitletts on the new South Ayrshire authority. There is heavy branch
backing for the wife of last Labour candidate Alistair Osborne, who came
so close to winning the seat from the Conservatives.
Political observers in the area await the outcome of the contest with
interest but what appears to be most important to the party is that the
strongest candidate possible is returned without even a whiff of sour
grapes from powerful male figures in the party who may have fancied
their chances.
It appears that the contest may be between Ms Jamieson, with her
Campaign connections seen as being on the left of the party, and Mrs
Osborne, who is considered more moderate but still strongly supporting
the important issues of women's rights and equal opportunities.
Ms Backshi is the most experienced of the candidates as far as local
authority work is concerned but many voters may be looking for a more
local figure to represent the interests of an area that values its
''independence''.
Councillor Murray has not been regarded as forthright enough on some
issues by sections of the party and was described by one party insider
as ''not hungry enough'' to have persuaded enough supporters.
The final choice, in common with those who choose her, will make
history as Mr Blair has made it clear he considers the move a one-off
process.
</TEXT>
