<HEADLINE>Revenge attack over Sarajevo.  Nato jets pound the Serbs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nato war planes, believed to be from Nato, roared over the darkened
skies of Sarajevo early this morning and bombed Serb-held areas to the
east and south of the city.
The planes could be heard in clear skies above the Bosnian capital,
after which distant flashes could be seen and explosions heard.
Sarajevo, which is virtually without electricity, was darkened.
United Nations and Nato officials had been pondering a response to
Monday's mortar bomb massacre in the Bosnian capital in which 37 people
were killed and 85 wounded.
UN investigators said that attack was carried out by the Bosnian Serb
forces who surround the capital.
The CNN television network in Washington said US officials confirmed
that Nato airstrikes had started against Serb locations around Sarajevo.
The network also quoted the officials as saying earlier reports that
Nato was contemplating artillery attacks by the British and French Rapid
Reaction Forces in the region were meant to confuse Bosnian Serbs until
the air strikes had begun.
It quoted Pentagon sources that the first wave of jets intended to
destroy the Bosnian Serb air defence system, clearing the way for
further strikes all over the area, particularly artillery sites. The
sources said the jets, mainly US war planes, would ''pound away'' at
Serb targets for up to three or four days.
It was a similar tactic to the Gulf war.
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, taking seriously the threat of
Western military power, struck a conciliatory tone and said the Serbs
were willing to accept a new US peace plan as a basis for negotiations.
The Contact Group of France, Britain, Germany, Russia and the United
States trying to negotiate a peace deal had agreed that military
reprisals should be carried out.
</TEXT>
