<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE, DEFENCE CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The U2 spy plane which crashed shortly after take-off yesterday at RAF
Fairford, in Gloucestershire, killing its pilot, was en route for Bosnia
to pinpoint Serb gun positions for Nato air strikes.
The reconnaissance mission was ordered after the Serb mortar attack.
The pilot of the U2R, Captain David Hawkins, successfully ejected but
died from his injuries at the Princess Margaret Hospital, Swindon, a
USAF spokesman said.
Mr Chris Brothers, who runs a petrol station near the base perimeter
fence, saw the aircraft crash. He said: ''As it circled after take-off,
it was obvious it had some sort of problem. When it came back round, it
was very close to the runway and one wing touched the ground.
''It then veered off to the left of the runway. I saw something red,
like an anorak, catapult out of it. It must have been the ejector-seat
and parachute. The plane then crashed with a massive impact and a great
fireball erupted close to our petrol station.''
Last night, a US Air Force investigation was under way into the cause
of the crash.
The U2, which first flew 40 years ago and is little more than a
high-powered glider equipped with cameras and electronic sensors, was
part of a precision location strike system squadron normally located at
Beale Air Force base in California. The squadron belongs to the US 9th
Strategic Reconnaissance wing.
The decision to authorise a manned surveillance flight came after the
loss of two remotely-piloted Predator aircraft over Bosnia earlier this
month. Five of the experimental Predators, equipped with high-resolution
video and stills cameras, were deployed last month to Gjader airforce
base in Albania to support Nato operations over the Bosnian war zone.
The aircraft can be controlled in video-arcade style from the ground
500 miles away and can loiter over a target area for up to 24 hours at
heights over 25,000ft.
US operators in Albania reported the first loss of contact with a
Predator over Bosnia on August 11 but would not confirm whether it had
been shot down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950830-000205</DOCNO>
