<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shevardnadze survives car bomb blast. Assassins target head of Georgia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976634128</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE leader of the republic of Georgia and former Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze escaped with cuts and bruises when a
massive car bomb blasted his motorcade yesterday.
He condemned the bombers as cowards and terrorists.
Mr Shevardnadze, 67, was taken to hospital with cuts caused by flying
glass after a Soviet-made Niva four-wheel-drive vehicle exploded outside
the Georgian parliament building in the capital, Tbilisi. His face and
hands were splattered with blood.
Mr Shevardnadze, who worked under President Mikhail Gorbachev, had
been on his way to a ceremony to sign Georgia's new constitution. It
gives a future president strong powers and Mr Shevardnadze is the
front-runner in the November election.
A furious Mr Shevardnadze said of his attackers: ''They want the Mafia
to run the country. They will not get it.''
His car was said to be leaving the inner courtyard of the parliament
when the bomb exploded nearby. Several other cars were destroyed.
Press secretary Ramaz Sakvarelidze said: ''It's clear Shevardnadze's
enemies tried to assassinate the head of our state to stop the signing
ceremony.''
Several other people were reported injured when the blast shattered
all the windows on one side of the parliament building.
Georgia, a former Soviet republic, has been wracked by crime, coups,
and civil war since it became independent in 1991.
Mr Shevardnadze, who helped end the Cold War, resigned as Soviet
Foreign Minister in December 1990. He returned to lead his native
Georgia after its first elected president, Zviad Gamsakhurdia, was
ousted in a coup.
He foiled several assassination attempts as Georgia's Communist leader
from 1972 to 1985. During Georgia's 1993 war in the breakaway Abkhazia
region, he went to the front line and survived several near-misses from
shells.
</TEXT>
