<HEADLINE>Safety fears for Celtic's Euro tie. Safety fears for Celtic's European tie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER, RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC asked the SFA yesterday to intervene with Europe's governing
football body UEFA and spell out their concerns over the European Cup
Winners' Cup clash in Georgia in two weeks.
They did so after receiving warnings from the Foreign Office in London
about the volatile situation in the relatively new republic, once part
of the Soviet Union.
Celtic supporters also called for the tie to be cancelled and warned
the team should refuse to go if the situation in Georgia is as volatile
as reported.
An official Foreign Office document states quite clearly and
chillingly: ''Uncontrolled possession of firearms is widespread
throughout Georgia.''
It adds: ''Visits to most parts of Georgia can be made in relative
safety although travel at night outside the capital Tbilisi should be
avoided if possible.''
Celtic have been drawn to play Dynamo Batoumi, a team from a Black Sea
resort town close to the border with Turkey and around 200 miles away
from the nation's capital.
Yesterday, alarmed by the Foreign Office report, Celtic sent security
chief Mr George Douglas to Batoumi to take a first-hand look at the
situation and assess the potential for trouble. But, while the Scottish
Cup-holders are making representations to UEFA, it would seem they have
little chance of having the venue changed.
SFA chief executive Jim Farry confirmed that he had spoken to UEFA on
Celtic's behalf.
But a spokesman for UEFA said last night: ''A team from Yugoslavia
played in Batoumi last week in the preliminary round of this competition
and there was no trouble whatsoever. As far as we are concerned, the
game will take place on September 14 as scheduled.''
Celtic's fears were intensified by the Foreign Office suggestion that
''incidents of mugging, theft, and pick-pocketing in all cities are
increasing''.
There is also a diphtheria epidemic raging through parts of the
country and warnings to travellers include special safety precautions
once you are in your hotel room. Locking a door does not seem to be
sufficient.
But it is UEFA and not the Foreign Office who will decide Celtic's
fate and last night it looked as if the game would simply be given the
go-ahead.
The official observer, Dr Edgar Obertufer of the Swiss FA, said last
night: ''I was there last week with the team from Yugoslavia and there
was another team from Macedonia in the country playing in the UEFA Cup
at the same time. Neither of these teams had any complaints about the
situation. Nor did I.''
There is little doubt that the observer's report -- and Dr Obertufer
is one of the most experienced officials on the Continent -- will carry
the day with the European Union and Celtic will be forced to make the
long journey to the other side of Europe. That in itself offers up
further problems.
The Georgian Consulate in London warned that the airport at Batoumi
would not be big enough to take a long-haul jet. The recommended route
appears to be travelling to Istanbul and from there going into Batoumi
24 hours before the game, returning to Turkey after the match, and
flying back from there on Friday.
Celtic would then be left trying to prepare for a game the next day
while combating travel fatigue and a four-hour time difference.
</TEXT>
