<HEADLINE>More police for Strathclyde</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN, HOME AFFAIRS CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Police, which managed earlier this year to reach --
through the persistence of Chief Constable Leslie Sharp -- the
establishment authorised in 1975, will get approval today to recruit
another 260 operational officers.
For months, the Scottish Office has been studying the case put forward
by Mr Sharp and his police authority at Strathclyde Regional Council to
give the force operational strength commensurate with today's workloads.
It has been anticipated for days that the Scottish Office Home Affairs
Minister, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, will make the announcement when
he visits the force headquarters in Glasgow today.
The police authority chairman, Councillor James Jennings, said last
night he was ''very hopeful'' that that would be the outcome of the
visit.
He anticipated that permission also would be granted for phase six of
the force's civilianisation programme to go ahead, releasing another
major body of officers for operational duties, which would increase the
number of new personnel on the streets to more than 400.
He confirmed that the new wave of officers would be paid for out of
overtime money already in the force's budget. The additional officers
would mean a corresponding drop in the need for overtime to be paid out,
freeing up the resource.
For years, the force strength of Strathclyde has been a political bone
of contention between Labour-controlled Strathclyde Region and the
Tories at the Scottish Office.
Mr Sharp forced his way through the political battle lines, recruiting
440 officers last year to raise the force numbers to 6954 -- the
establishment which was authorised 20 years ago when the force was
created. He did not stop there, announcing his intention to seek
additional constables to cope with the hugely-increased workload the
force has faced in the last 10 years.
Meantime, applications closed earlier this week for the job of chief
constable, which will be vacant when Mr Sharp retires on December 31.
The #86,988 post has attracted six applicants, two of them from
Scotland, and not all are from chief constables.
The police authority will meet on September 25 to draw up a short
leet, which will be passed to the Scottish Secretary, who either
approves the leet or weeds out applicants he considers to be unsuitable.
Interviews for the post will start on October 9.
</TEXT>
