<DATE>950830</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NHS wage deal on the cards</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT, RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976634133</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is poised to offer a national minimum wage structure
throughout the NHS, a concession which could resolve the long-running
pay dispute.
The stalemate had threatened to escalate into industrial action within
weeks.
However, senior NHS managers are arranging talks with unions
representing around 900,000 staff, most of whom have opposed the
Government's insistence on offering just 1% nationally together with the
prospect of more, up to a further 2% in the case of nurses, via local
negotiations.
NHS sources suggest the call to fresh talks will come this morning
from the health service director of human resources, Mr Ken Jarrold, and
that negotiations could resume next week.
Although the Royal Colleges of Nursing and Midwives, both outwith the
TUC, had virtually accepted the existing situation, the other unions and
associations, led by Unison which represents about 440,000 NHS workers,
have opposed rigorously what they see as a move to sideline them.
They are all currently balloting on various forms of industrial
action, including a one-day strike by Unison members, with the results
imminent and action expected to be called from around the middle of
September.
It is understood that in an attempt to head off industrial action, the
NHS is now prepared to discuss national minimum rates which would be
upgraded each year to reflect the outcome of the previous year's
bargaining.
National union officials would be involved in determining the level at
which the minimum rates would be set each year, thus retaining
substantial union involvement.
The NHS unions, the bulk of which had seen the move towards more
localised bargaining as an attack on their central role, are expected to
be more receptive to such a compromise. It would, in effect, see wage
rates set locally but with national fall-back levels agreed subsequently
to ensure that no NHS grade or location can fall below nationally agreed
minima.
Such a nationally agreed pay level, which could be improved upon
locally, and upgraded in advance of the next year's negotiations, is
seen as the most likely formula for resolving the long-running dispute.
The dispute began in early March when the workers review body for
600,000 nurses and midwives recommended a 1% across-the-board rise. It
was subsequently offered to administrative and clerical grades, hospital
ancillaries, and ambulance workers, all of whom rejected it.
NHS staff who attacked the offer were told that individual trusts
would increase the 1% to around 3%, and Health Minister Gerald Malone
pleaded with nurses to settle the dispute as most would get 3%.
However, while almost all of the 530 NHS trusts have now topped up the
1% national award with local offers, many of them were linked to
efficiency ''strings''.
The dispute escalated as the full extent of the conditions emerged.
Unions claimed many of the deals meant cuts in holiday, night-shift and
unsocial-hours' allowances, longer working hours, regrading, and
acceptance of local pay bargaining.
In June, the 300,000 members of the traditionally moderate Royal
College of Nursing voted overwhelmingly to scrap their 79-year-old
no-strike clause in favour of one allowing limited industrial action.
There have also been arguments over how many trusts have actually
offered the full 3% with the union benchmark ''no strings'' test.
In Scotland, the decision by Glasgow's Victoria Infirmary to offer the
basic 1% -- the lowest in the country -- was described as ''absolutely
outrageous'' by the RCN, who said only nine out of 47 Scottish Trusts
had made 3% no-strings-attached offers.
Across the UK, Unison said almost all trusts had made offers but only
150 met the ''no strings criteria'' although the Government claimed the
number was much larger.
There have been few settlements and there will still need to be much
negotiating before the threat of industrial action is lifted.
Asked whether talks were likely to be reopened, Unison head of health,
Mr Bob Abberley, said last night: ''I hope so as there is a need to find
a solution because we are moving ever nearer to industrial action.''
</TEXT>
